\par \par \uc2 U.S. Companies Should Show Confidence in the U.S.\par \par \uc2 ROSABETH MOSS KANTER: The first and foremost action is to show confidence in the U.S.\u8212\'20\'14by investing in U.S. jobs, training U.S. workers, buying from U.S. suppliers, joining with U.S. public schools to improve quality and produce a work-ready population, especially in STEM skills.\par \par \uc2 No amount of finger-pointing about problems or talk about what someone else should do\u8211\'20\'13whether Congress or the public schools\u8212\'20\'14will improve the business climate. It's a self-fulfilling prophecy, as I argue in my book, "Confidence." If more companies show their confidence in particular regions, they will attract others, and then banks will unlock capital for small businesses; regional skills coalitions will support job training; higher education will increase industry-relevant research and development; and voters who see job prospects will be more willing to support business-friendly policies.\par \par \uc2 The rise of Albany, N.Y., as a semiconductor-manufacturing hub is a good example. Cutting-edge research in nanotechnology plus encouragement from the governor led \uc2 IBM\uc2  to make a large investment, which in turn led Intel to move its East Coast headquarters to Albany, which led others to follow. And employer partnerships with public high schools and community colleges, such as P-TECH (Pathways in Technology Early College High School), which \uc2 IBM\uc2  helped create in Brooklyn and spread to Chicago, are proving so successful that President Obama unveiled $100 million in challenge grants to create more such partnerships nationwide.\par \par \uc2 Don't get me wrong. I'm not advocating for a "Made in America" movement; those campaigns haven't worked in the past (as I showed in my book "World Class") and won't in the future. Businesses should not make foolish choices just because it is seen as patriotic, and it is also important to invest in global growth.