\par \par \uc2 Why Business Leaders Have Lost the Respect of Main Street\par \par \uc2 ROBERT HOWELL: I believe that the current weak economic conditions are primarily due to failed government policies. Legislation during the 1990s encouraged homeownership by those who could not afford it. Relaxed (\uc2 Fannie Mae\uc2  and \uc2 Freddie Mac\uc2 ) lending requirements led to a spate of subprime mortgages that were then used to underwrite financial derivatives which ultimately blew up, creating the financial crisis of 2008. Fiscal policy aimed at stimulating the economy\u8212\'20\'14but also resulting in large deficits and increased national debt levels\u8212\'20\'14and an extraordinarily low-interest-rate monetary policy have actually hurt the business \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and overall economy. New regulations for the financial sector, the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , and, of course, the Affordable Care Act, have all added to business costs and uncertainty.\par \par \uc2 However, the business sector is not without its warts. Arrogance and greed do not endear business leaders and the business sector to Main Street. When business leaders flaunt their lifestyles (multiple homes and jets) and compensation, in some cases reaching 500 times that of the average worker, it is very difficult for the middle-class to have a lot of sympathy and respect for business generally and business leaders specifically. Somehow, business leaders have got to regain the respect of Main Street by revisiting their compensation practices and their public image. Over the past 25 years, executive compensation has exploded; it may take some time and, even, a new generation of more authentic leaders, committed to balancing their social, environmental, and economic (the proverbial "triple bottom line") responsibilities, with a big dose of humility, to regain respect and trust. It is time for today's business leaders to truly become statesman leaders