\par \par \uc2 Puts Zigs and Zags Into Your Business Plan\par \par \uc2 DOV SEIDMAN\uc2 : Start by realizing that business today faces a zeitgeist that is radically different from just a few years ago.\par \par \uc2 The world is so much more volatile today\u8212\'20\'14financially, environmentally, socially\u8212\'20\'14that the old ways of plotting linear plans just don't work anymore. Bubbles and boom-and-bust cycles no longer move in 20 years or five years or even one year. Some are less than a quarter. Natural disasters and supply-chain disruptions are occurring with greater and greater frequency.\par \par \uc2 Business is often a convoluted affair, yet too many leaders behave as if it were neat, tidy and eminently predictable. They try to force a straight line onto a curvilinear reality. They continue to operate as if we can superimpose precise forecasts, accurate budget projections, and calibrated performance arrows on a complex and interwoven reality. Then they are surprised to find their enterprises less productive and more vulnerable as a result.\par \par \uc2 The problem is that they're trapped in an \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and mind-set that is partly of their own making. For at least a generation, it has been axiomatic that business should systematize based on preordained results and elaborate predictive models. They've successfully scaled models and products, services and processes\u8212\'20\'14TQM, CST GRC, CRM, HRIS, ERP.\par \par \uc2 The urgent need now is to scale values by translating them into corporate practices, leadership and individual behaviors and create valuable relationships. The reality described above combines with this imperative to compel a paradigm shift.\par \par \uc2 This will require a rethink. We need a single, radical transformation: Business must return to the idea that it is a journey.\par \par \uc2 Imagine a staffer came to you and said, "We have a great financial plan for the future, but one thing is clear: There will be plenty of ups and downs." Some would be inclined to fire her. But we should celebrate her, because the age of planning\u8212\'20\'14as we came to understand it in the late 20th century business model\u8212\'20\'14is over.\par \par \uc2 Workers are not inspired by execution plans. They don't elevate their behavior based on implementation timetables. That kind of thinking has depressed employee engagement numbers to historic lows\u8212\'20\'14two-thirds of U.S. employees are not fully engaged in their work and are less productive as a result.\par \par \uc2 A journey is not a mad dash to a number at the end of the quarter. But when I say business needs to embrace a curvilinear path, where things go up and down, I'm not suggesting acceptance of subpar performance or lower standards. I mean we need to lean in to a difficult, uneven terrain. To embrace the up-and-down reality of markets by journeying, understanding that while the ultimate goals are higher and further, the path will zig and zag.\par \par \uc2 That requires simultaneously adopting an ethos of resilience and building an engine of propulsive growth. Which is not complicated\u8212\'20\'14but not easy, either. Business has never before had to do those two things at the same time.\par \par \uc2 The formulaic business practices of the past are fading, and failing, fast. Organizations built for the long haul are ones that accept the inevitability of hard times. They pursue journeys of significance, knowing that true success will only arrive as a byproduct of sustainable philosophy.\par \par \uc2 Dov Seidman\uc2  ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://twitter.com/DovSeidman"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 @DovSeidman}}}\uc2 ) is founder and CEO of LRN, an advisory-services firm, and author of\u160\'00\'A0"HOW: Why HOW We Do Anything Means Everything."\par \par {\*\shppict{\pict\jpegblip\picw76\pich76\picscaley75\picscalex75\picwgoal1520\pichgoal1520
