\par \par \uc2 Stop Exporting American Jobs\par \par \uc2 ROBERT PLANT:\u160\'00\'A0The need to improve the business climate in the U.S. is not just an economic imperative but an ethical one.\par \par \uc2 For the last few decades the prevailing business model has been to export manufacturing to external sites of production, predominantly in Asia. However, while the benefits of low-cost sourcing lead to a virtuous cycle of low-cost products, higher profits and in the short term happy shareholders, it also leads to a negative spiral of skill erosion, innovation decay, intellectual property leakage and unemployment over the long term. As such, the emphasis on outsourcing has to be reconsidered and a more balanced sourcing approach adopted if the country is to prosper over the long term, provide jobs for its population and build a skill base for the future.\par \par \uc2 The initial buds of this are being seen as leading firms such as\u160\'00\'A0Ford\u160\'00\'A0and\u160\'00\'A0 Caterpillar\u160\'00\'A0have embraced reshoring. This is not just a noble act on their part. It is based on sound economics as well as an eye on the future. These and other companies have embraced new technologies, methods of production and re-engaged with their communities to enable this to happen.\par \par \uc2 GE, another reshoring pioneer, opened a plant in Louisville, Ky., to produce their GeoSpring Water Heater. The plant has enabled the company to cut the price of the heater to consumers\u160\'00\'A020% below the costs of an Asian sourced product.\par \par \uc2 Business leaders therefore should look closely at embracing reshoring for their own products as well as using their lobbyists to promoting it within the political-legislative arena. The "Made in the U.S.A." model has benefits for both the firms and the population within which they reside, building a better society and prosperous economy for all.\par \par \uc2 Robert Plant ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://twitter.com/drrobertplant"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 @drrobertplant}}}\uc2 ) is an associate professor at the School of Business Administration, \uc2 University of Miami\uc2 , in Coral Gables, Fla.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 greg : \uc2 Regional Politics | c315 : \uc2 Conferences/Exhibitions | c41 : \uc2 Management Issues | gcntsu : \uc2 Continuing Education | gcrpln : \uc2 Career Planning | c31 : \uc2 Marketing | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | gcat : \uc2 Political/General News | gcom : \uc2 Society/Community/Work | gedu : \uc2 Education | gjob : \uc2 General Labor Issues | gpir : \uc2 Politics/International Relations | gpol : \uc2 Domestic Politics | ncat : \uc2 Content Types | nfact : \uc2 Factiva Filters | nfcpin : \uc2 FC&E Industry News Filter\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RE\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 usa : \uc2 United States | namz : \uc2 North America\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\cl