\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Ethics Watchmakers are forging convincing CSR relationships. By Robin Swithinbank\par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  (CSR) is often dismissed as a featherweight concept dreamt up by marketing men. But in the watch world, which grows richer by the year and is increasingly forging links with non-profit organisations, it can produce significant results.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Recent efforts prove the point - and highlight the wide variety of watchmaker's approaches to CSR.\par \par \uc2 In September 2013, 33 unique fine watches donated by brands went under the hammer in Monaco at the Only Watch auction in aid of research into Duchenne muscular dystrophy, raising more than \u8364\'20\'AC5m.\par \par \uc2 In October, Rolex announced Olafur Eliasson, the artist, and Michael Ondaatje, the novelist, would be among the experts taking part in its 2014-15 Mentor and Prot\u233\'00\'E9g\u233\'00\'E9 Arts Initiative, an arts mentoring scheme that has drawn high-profile names since 2002.\par \par \uc2 And the Audemars Piguet Foundation has worked on 75 projects in 34 countries to raise awareness of environmental issues, with a focus on protecting forests.\par \par \uc2 Whatever the motives, the imperative for luxury watch brands to "give something back" by lending support to charities is an increasing priority. But are consumers convinced?\par \par \uc2 Some experts say the luxury industry's involvement in charitable and social projects can create consumer confusion. "While individuals can be both 'selfish' and 'selfless' depending on the circumstances, they can never be both at the same time," says Carlos Torelli, associate professor of marketing at the Carlson School of Management, \uc2 University of Minnesota\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Catherine Walker, a researcher at the Directory of Social Change, a UK independent research charity, and author of The Company Giving Almanac , says: "The concept of CSR clashes psychologically with the motivations for buying luxury goods, and needs to be carefully managed."\par \par \uc2 But she adds, "Any CSR is better than no CSR, and while in order to change things you'd need people to stop buying luxury watches, and give more money to developing countries, it may be easier to persuade them to give a small percentage of their purchase price to good causes."\par \par \uc2 Certainly some non-profit organisations are happy to enter into such arrangements with luxury watch brands. \uc2 M\u233\'00\'E9decins Sans Fronti\u232\'00\'E8res\uc2 , the humanitarian aid organisation, last year partnered with Nomos Glash\u252\'00\'FCtte, the German watch house. MSF receives a donation of 100 euros, pounds or dollars from the sale of each of 6,000 limited edition watches sold by the company in Germany, the UK and the US. Proceeds from this tie-up will be added to an initial \u8364\'20\'AC200,000 donated to MSF when the scheme was first run in Germany.\par \par \uc2 "Partnerships with luxury brands are quite new for MSF," says Antoine Bogaerts of MSF's fundraising team. "It helps us to reach people who we might not have had the opportunity to address before."\par \par \uc2 He adds that \u163\'00\'A3100 can go a long way. The sum will pay for 37 full sets of emergency wound dressing supplies for treatment in the field, or 25 wool blankets to protect displaced people from the cold in winter.\par \par \uc2 Nomos Glash\u252\'00\'FCtte acknowledges that luxury products have no relevance in crisis situations, but says this should not prevent it from supporting the aid agency. "Since mechanical watches were not on MSF's priority list for emergency aid, we figured that funds and additional awareness for their organisation was the best we could do," says Uwe Ahrendt, the brand's chief executive.\par \par \uc2 Luxury watch retailers are also involved. Half of the donation made to MSF under the Nomos Glash\u252\'00\'FCtte scheme will come from retailers. One of the participating UK retailers is Watches of Switzerland.\par \par \uc2 "This project has given us an opportunity to support an organisation whose mission and values we believe in, and to behave in a socially responsible way," says \uc2 Justin Stead\uc2 , chief executive of Aurum Holdings, parent company of Watches of Switzerland, Goldsmiths and \uc2 Mappin & Webb\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Stephen Urquhart\uc2 , Omega's president, believes brands benefit from CSR because projects often reflect the mood of consumers. Omega's latest CSR project is with the GoodPlanet Foundation. It will help fund two ocean-based projects near the Indonesian island of Sulawesi.\par \par \uc2 "Companies in all industries are aware that their potential customers are socially aware and are attracted by companies that share their passions, whatever they might be," he says.\par \par \uc2 Although it has become a hackneyed phrase, the merits of "doing good" are enough motivation for some brands. "We believe it's everyone's responsibility to be respectful of the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," says Zahra KassimLakha, Jaeger-LeCoultre's global head of strategy.\par \par \uc2 "For us, that means environmental protection, commitment to human values, and the preservation of knowledge and skills."\par \par \uc2 Jaeger-LeCoultre, for its part, is involved with the Unesco World Heritage Centre and (Red), the Aids charity, as well as the UK-based Prince's Foundation for Children and the Arts.\par \par \uc2 For smart-thinking companies, CSR activities can create opportunities to enrich a brand's values. In June, the British brand Bremont launched Codebreaker, a watch made in partnership with the Bletchley Park Trust, which maintains the site where Alan Turing, the cryptanalyst, and his colleagues broke the Enigma code during the second world war.\par \par \uc2 The watch enhances Bremont's profile as a British company by incorporating wood from Bletchley's Hut 6, metal from an Enigma coding machine rotor and paper taken from punch cards used by the codebreakers. Bremont paid the trust an undisclosed figure at the start of the project, which it intends to recoup through watch sales.\par \par \uc2 "If you walk around Bletchley Park, it's falling down. It needs money, it needs support," says Giles English, Bremont co-founder. "We can help do something. Their PR operation is small-scale and we can add weight to it. In return, they're giving us an amazing story."\par \par \uc2 How luxury watchmaker IWC is helping to preserve the Gal\u225\'00\'E1pagos Islands\par \par \uc2 FT.com/watches-jewellery\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 gdev : \uc2 Development/Humanitarian Aid | gcha : \uc2 Charities | c184 : \uc2 Joint Ventures | c18 : \uc2 Ownership Changes | cactio : \uc2 Corporate Actions | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | gcat : \uc2 Political/General News | gcom : \uc2 Society/Community/Work | gdip : \uc2 International Relations | gpir : \uc2 Politics/International Relations | ncat : \uc2 Content Types | nfact : 