cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 It's been a long time -- maybe never -- since I've read a book that made me feel proud or even a little encouraged about the moral compass of the world's largest companies. Corporations, after all, exist to make money. Last I checked, doing good deeds is not listed as a fiduciary duty. But Christine Bader's thought-provoking book, ''The Evolution of a Corporate Idealist: When Girl Meets Oil'' (Bibliomotion, 264 pages), argues that this may be changing, at least among some of the people who work at these companies.\par \par \uc2 I know, I know, I can see your eyes rolling already -- and your skepticism may increase when you learn that Ms. Bader spent nearly a decade at BP, as what I guess you would call a corporate human-rights specialist. Yes, such jobs exist.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 How can a company that was excoriated -- and paid billions in fines -- over the Deepwater Horizon oil spill claim to care about human rights? Ms. Bader had left BP by the time of the spill. But she was still working for the company when an explosion occurred at its Galveston refinery, killing 15 people, after which numerous safety violations were found. She expresses ''puzzlement and embarrassment'' that she was not deeply involved in the aftermath of the explosion, which had been framed as an industrial accident rather than a human rights violation. Thus, she writes, it was not considered part of her assignment.\par \par \uc2 While acknowledging that the explosion should have ''challenged her impression of BP as a responsible company in which I was playing a key role,'' she also makes a case that when it came to the global projects on which she worked, the company made an effort to do the right thing -- a contradiction that is playing out in many other companies as well.\par \par \uc2 Americans have been so cynical about big business for so long that it's hard to fathom that some people at large corporations have begun to accept that trying to take the high road -- whether it's policing child-labor laws among Pakistani suppliers or installing unrequired smoke detectors in a Chinese factory -- can sometimes help their bottom line.\par \par \uc2 The author, however, places the issue in a context far broader than mere profits. ''What we are actually talking about here,'' she quotes one of these ''corporate idealists'' as saying, ''is the fundamental question of our age: How does a global business operate?''\par \par \uc2 Ms. Bader started at BP in 1999 and, shortly after, oversaw the relocation of 127 Indonesian villagers, whose land had been seized by the government to make way for a natural gas plant. The project required myriad economic and environmental studies, the moving of certain sacred rocks, the building of model homes, rigorous outreach to the villagers and the odd meeting with tight-lipped army generals.\par \par \uc2 Although you could argue that this was simply smart risk mitigation -- unhappy villagers elsewhere have blocked entry roads and staged unpleasant protests -- The Wall Street Journal, for one, hailed the Indonesian project as unprecedented and a ''unique piece of social engineering.''\par \par \uc2 The ensuing years have seen a surge in the field of \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 , known as C.S.R. The people who work in it have all sorts of highfalutin job titles, but Ms. Bader calls them all ''corporate idealists.'' They commonly work in developing countries, trying to introduce Western standards into situations where, if something goes wrong, their bosses may get the blame.\par \par \uc2 It was Ms. Bader, for example, who struggled with one of BP's Chinese partners to put smoke detectors, not to mention hot water, in worker dormitories. As in many of these situations, persuading them to do so meant bridging a yawning cultural gap. When BP pushed Chinese safety managers to take media training classes, for example, they couldn't understand why. ''If there's a major accident,'' a BP manager replied, ''the health and safety manager is often the one to explain to the media what has happened.''\par \par \uc2 One Chinese executive seemed puzzled: ''But we wouldn't let the media know what's happened,'' he said.\par \par \uc2 The new realities of rapid globalization have helped make corporate morals de rigueur, Ms. Bader argues. Formal C.S.R. programs began popping up in the 1990s, a phenomenon that Ms. Bader suggests was propelled by the rise of the Internet. Now, an industrial disaster is more likely to be live-blogged to readers, shareholders and decision makers around the world. That was the case with the Rana Plaza factory collapse in Bangladesh in which more than 1,000 workers died -- though that also underscored that the world still has a long way to go when it comes to safety issues.\par \par \uc2 We are living in an age of ''changing expectations,'' Ms. Bader writes, and whether a C.E.O. likes it or not, the world will often judge the company responsible for actions of those even tangentially involved in the business, from vendors to partners.\par \par \uc2 Ms. Bader's book, to be released later this month, is a good primer on the C.S.R. phenomenon. She was there near the beginning, and while her on-the-ground experiences would give way to working behind desks and advising a Harvard professor drafting a set of United Nations C.S.R. standards, she put on a journalist's hat for this book and drew from dozens of interviews she did with others in the field.\par \par \uc2 The C.S.R. specialist occupies an unusual niche in the modern multinational, she writes, as much an outsider dealing with wary insiders as an insider dealing with wary outsiders. The best in the field are obliged to shelve some of their highest ideals, she says, realizing that the only way to bring true change to large companies is via ''incrementalism.''\par \par \uc2 After Ms. Bader left, she watched in dismay as millions of barrels of oil spread into the Gulf of Mexico in the Deepwater Horizon disaster of 2010. ''I read the coverage wide-eyed and slack-jawed, as the company that I loved for its progressive position on human rights and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  was being pilloried,'' accused of negligence of both, she writes. ''Had my nine-year relationship with BP been a sham?'' she asks. What she realizes is that a ''flawed and complex'' corporation like BP may well be ''advancing human rights in some ways while compromising them in others.''\par \par \uc2 ''The Evolution of a Corporate Idealist'' is a quick read, effortlessly gulped during a long airplane flight. The writing is clear and concise, and if the book doesn't leave one convinced that every multinational has suddenly developed a guiding conscience, it does offer some encouragement that many are on the way. No matter how you parse it, that has to be a good thing.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl1