d \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 To increase its appeal, Pivot is turning to names that would be familiar to millennials in realms like politics, Broadway, Hollywood and \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 . (The channel specializes in purpose-driven programming because issues like protecting the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  appeal to many younger Americans, channel executives explain.)\par \par \uc2 For instance, Meghan McCain, who formerly hosted a show on Pivot called ''Raising McCain,'' will return to the channel. Ms. McCain, a daughter of Senator John McCain, will be one of three hosts of ''TakePart Live,'' a late-night talk show that the channel will move to 10 p.m. in May.\par \par \uc2 ''TakePart Live'' is also getting a new production company, Embassy Row, which specializes in live talk and chat shows like ''Watch What Happens Live'' on Bravo and ''Talking Dead'' on AMC.\par \par \uc2 The Broadway name joining the Pivot lineup is Lin-Manuel Miranda, the creator and star of the musical ''In the Heights,'' who is working on a musical about Alexander Hamilton. Mr. Miranda, who also writes the rap that Neil Patrick Harris delivered at the end of Tony Awards ceremonies, is among the cast members of ''Freestyle Love Supreme,'' an original show composed of 10 30-minute episodes that features performances of improvised, freestyle rhyme based on audience suggestions. ''Freestyle Love Supreme,'' billed by Pivot as a special, is scheduled to begin in October.\par \par \uc2 The Hollywood star power is to be supplied by the cast members of the channel's first original scripted series, ''Fortitude,'' a 12-episode drama set in the Arctic. Pivot has given the show a green light in partnership with a unit of \uc2 British Sky Broadcasting\uc2 . The cast includes Stanley Tucci, Luke Treadaway, Michael Gambon and Christopher Eccleston.\par \par \uc2 In keeping with Pivot's tilt toward purpose programming, the drama is ''an eco-thriller'' that should appeal to Generation Y, \uc2 Evan Shapiro\uc2 , president of Pivot, said at a breakfast on Wednesday in Midtown Manhattan, where the channel held its 2014-15 upfront presentation.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Treadaway made brief remarks during the breakfast, as did Mr. Manuel and Ms. McCain. She drew laughs when she described how the ''new election cycle'' coming up in the fall ''is like Super Bowl time for me.''\par \par \uc2 Also speaking at the breakfast was Tom Szaky, chief executive of a sustainability company, TerraCycle, that will be the subject of an original, unscripted series called ''Human Resources.'' Pivot plans 10 30-minute episodes of the show, starting on Aug. 8.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Shapiro called ''Human Resources'' a ''docu-comedy,'' and that was borne out by the amusing clips he showed from the series, filmed at the TerraCycle office in New Jersey.\par \par \uc2 The channel's executives encourage advertisers to sign branded-entertainment deals in addition to running traditional commercials. Hyundai, Monster.com, Silk and Stonyfield are among brands that have worked with Pivot to create branded content like digital shorts, interstitial clips and 30-minute specials.\par \par \uc2 Pivot is available in about 45 million homes. The channel is not rated by Nielsen but intends to be, hence the expansion of its programming schedule -- more than 300 hours of original shows in 2014, executives said -- and its outreach to advertisers.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faau