dent raw materials.\par \par \uc2 \u8216\'20\'18\u8216\'20\'18Businesses manage risk, that\u8217\'20\'19s one of the main functions of management,\u8217\'20\'19\u8217\'20\'19 said Adrian Sym, executive director of the Alliance for Water Stewardship, a group that promotes the responsible use of water.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 In the case of water, \u8216\'20\'18\u8216\'20\'18it could be \u8216\'20\'18Do I have enough water to do what I need to do for this business? Is the quality of this water sufficient to enable me to do that?\u8217\'20\'19\u8217\'20\'19\u8217\'20\'19 and will local authorities remain willing to license a company\u8217\'20\'19s usage, Mr. Sym said. \u8216\'20\'18\u8216\'20\'18These are the things businesses are dealing with.\u8217\'20\'19\u8217\'20\'19\par \par \uc2 Water supply stresses are intensifying everywhere from California to South Africa, the result of climate change, booming populations and the growing numbers of people moving to cities and adopting resource-intensive, middle-class lifestyles.\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 World Economic Forum\uc2 , in its annual report on global risks, published in January, ranked water crises as the third-biggest risk to stability in the decade ahead, behind fiscal crises and unemployment. Without changes in business practices, the demand for fresh water could be 40 percent higher than supply by 2030, according to the 2030 Water Resource Group, a public-private consortium that is housed within the \uc2 World Bank\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s \uc2 International Finance Corp\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 The first to feel the pinch, and to begin doing something about it, have been food and beverage companies, which depend heavily on water for their basic ingredients. Agriculture accounts for an estimated 75 percent to 80 percent of world water use.\par \par \uc2 \u8216\'20\'18\u8216\'20\'18When we look at how our business operates, we use a lot of output from Mother Nature, and that stuff doesn\u8217\'20\'19t happen without water,\u8217\'20\'19\u8217\'20\'19 said \uc2 Jerry Lynch\uc2 , vice president and chief sustainability officer at \uc2 General Mills\uc2 , whose brands include Cheerios, \uc2 Pillsbury\uc2  and Green Giant. \u8216\'20\'18\u8216\'20\'18You don\u8217\'20\'19t grow plants, cows don\u8217\'20\'19t produce milk without water. So it\u8217\'20\'19s pretty fundamental to our business.\u8217\'20\'19\u8217\'20\'19\par \par \uc2 Clothing and other textile-based industries that depend on cotton \u8212\'20\'14 a particularly thirsty crop \u8212\'20\'14 or on water-intensive dying processes are also exposed. Paper production and mining, too, are big water users.\par \par \uc2 So is the energy sector. Water is key to many of the industry\u8217\'20\'19s most basic processes, from coal mining and fracking, or hydraulic fracturing, to the cooling of gas, coal and nuclear power plants. Energy production accounts for 15 percent of all water consumption, the United Nations said in releasing a March report on water and energy.\par \par \uc2 The coal industry in particular has done little to address its heavy water usage, said Iris Cheng, a climate and water expert at \uc2 Greenpeace International\uc2 , based in Amsterdam.\par \par \uc2 The problem is acute in China, where coal generation is widespread and authorities want to locate new power plants away from cities because of concerns about air pollution, she said. That often means they end up in arid parts of the country\u8217\'20\'19s west, draining water that is needed for farming and other purposes, Ms. Cheng said.\par \par \uc2 Many energy firms, Ms, Cheng said, are reluctant to say too much publicly about their water usage. \u8216\'20\'18\u8216\'20\'18Because people realize they\u8217\'20\'19re very exposed, they\u8217\'20\'19re being very, very careful about how and when they report on their water risk,\u8217\'20\'19\u8217\'20\'19 she said.\par \par \uc2 The Alliance for Water Stewardship, backed by big companies like \uc2 Nestl\u233\'00\'E9\uc2  and \uc2 General Mills\uc2 , as well as water and environmental groups including \uc2 the Nature Conservancy\uc2  and \uc2 WaterAid\uc2 , in April published detailed guidelines that businesses can use to assess their water risk.\par \par \uc2 Water issues are inherently local, and the new standard encourages business to work with other users in their area, from residents and small-scale farmers to government officials, said Mr. Sym.\par \par \uc2 While companies have generally regarded water as the public sector\u8217\'20\'19s responsibility, many governments are no longer able to pay for the necessary infrastructure investments, said Thomas Chiramba, head of the fresh water unit at the \uc2 United Nations \b \highlight22\uc2 Environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  Program\uc2 , which helped develop the alliance\u8217\'20\'19s standard.\par \par \uc2 \u8216\'20\'18\u8216\'20\'18Everyone has to chip in, because water is everyone\u8217\'20\'19s business,\u8217\'20\'19\u8217\'20\'19 Mr. Chiramba said.\par \par \uc2 Not everyone is impressed by big companies\u8217\'20\'19 talk about water awareness and responsibility.\par \par \uc2 Alex Money, a researcher at the University of Oxford\u8217\'20\'19s Smith School of Enterprise and the \b \highlight22\uc2 Environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , who surveyed 60 of the world\u8217\'20\'19s biggest companies, said he found that most of them had done more in the past to improve water efficiency than they planned to do in the future.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Money said that reflected the reality that most businesses trying to reduce water usage would have begun with the easiest, highest-return measures, meaning they stood to gain little from the next steps, which are likely to be more expensive and deliver less savings.\par \par \uc2 Still, \uc2 Laurent Auguste\uc2 , innovation and markets director at \uc2 Veolia Environnement\uc2 , a French contractor that provides water services, said he saw companies\u8217\'20\'19 concerns about water issues moving from technical specialists and \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  departments to the offices of top executives.\par \par \uc2 In Qatar, for example, \uc2 Veolia\uc2  is helping to eliminate all discharge from a Shell natural gas liquefaction plant, treating all wastewater so the factory can reuse it.\par \par \uc2 \u8216\'20\'18\u8216\'20\'18We are at a time when pressure on the resource will lead people to be smarter,\u8217\'20\'19\u8217\'20\'19 he said. \u8216\'20\'18\u8216\'20\'18But we are very much at the starting point.\u8217\'20\'19\u8217\'20\'19\par \par \uc2 The companies taking water most seriously are those that operate in the developing world, said Adebayo Adeloye, a professor of water resources management at \uc2 Heriot-Watt University\uc2  in Edinburgh. While wealthy countries may suffer from drought too, the most acute problems are in poor nations that lack the infrastructure to cope, he said.\par \par \uc2 In places like Nigeria, some companies are trying to ensure their own water supplies by building mini-reservoirs or dams and installing storage tanks, he said.\par \par \uc2 \u8216\'20\'18\u8216\'20\'18Where they know that nothing is guaranteed, companies are taking this very, very seriously and looking at ways they can make themselves self-sufficient,\u8217\'20\'19\u8217\'20\'19 he said. \u8216\'20\'18\u8216\'20\'18People in those countries literally have turned themselves into mini-utilities because of the failure of the framework.\u8217\'20\'19\u8217\'20\'19\par \par \uc2 In parts of Africa and southern Asia, big companies are also beginning to consider helping governments finance new water infrastructure in places where it would enable them to expand their businesses, said Mr. Money.\par \par \uc2 It\u8217\'20\'19s \u8216\'20\'18\u8216\'20\'18the idea of corporate water return as the counterpart to corporate water risk,\u8217\'20\'19\u8217\'20\'19 he said.\par \par \uc2 Over all, Mr. Money said, most companies only focus seriously on water if it is likely to have a clear impact on their bottom line. \u8216\'20\'18\u8216\'20\'18No one cares more than companies about making a profit, so to the extent that it affects their business this stuff is for real,\u8217\'20\'19\u8217\'20\'19 he said.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 c13 : \uc2 Regulation/Government Policy | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | ncat : \uc2 Content Types | nfact : \uc2 Factiva Filters | nfcpin : \uc2 FC&E Industry News Filter\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RE\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 uk : \uc2 United Kingdom | eecz : \uc2 European Union Countries | e