rowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Copyright 2014 The Financial Times Ltd. All rights reserved. Please do not cut and paste FT articles and redistribute by email or post to the web. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Global development organisations have been doing a lot of soul searching recently. With multinationals and private foundations moving into their territory, tackling everything from healthcare to food security, the sector is no longer the only game in town.\par \par \uc2 This has implications not only for the way development dollars are spent. It is also shaping institutions' approach to human capital.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 For some, this involves self reflection. Most prominently, the \uc2 World Bank\uc2  is undergoing an internal restructuring, an ambitious project that is not without critics. The idea is to remove regional barriers to knowledge exchange by creating global practices, with pools of specialists in areas such as education and agriculture or finance and markets.\par \par \uc2 Sean McGrath\uc2 , \uc2 the World Bank Group\uc2 's vice-president of human resources, admits the process has not been easy, with staff being asked to change roles and locations.\par \par \uc2 "Having to work in a different \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  is challenging," he says. "But we want the collective whole to be greater than the sum of the parts."\par \par \uc2 Breaking down silos across large institutions means placing a greater emphasis on managerial skills than in the past. "Like most public systems, historically we've invested in our technical capabilities," says Mr McGrath. "We haven't given equal investment to people's role as managers - and as junior managers."\par \par \uc2 Rather than wait until they are promoted to senior levels, he explains, the bank will now foster management skills much earlier in people's careers.\par \par \uc2 But if the bank is seeking change internally, others in the sector are looking outwards, using the web and social media to tap into ideas from the outside world in models first seen in the corporate sector.\par \par \uc2 Innovation fever has broken out across the development world, with job titles that include the word "innovation" and the creation of departments called "labs" designed to work with universities, entrepreneurs, companies and others.\par \par \uc2 Several factors are behind the changes. First, institutions such as the \uc2 World Bank\uc2  have watched their relative influence in global development diminish as newcomers have entered the development sphere.\par \par \uc2 These include organisations such as the \uc2 Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation\uc2 , the \uc2 Global Fund To Fight Aids, Tuberculosis and Malaria\uc2 , and the \uc2 Gavi Alliance\uc2 , which supports immunisation for children in poor countries. All have significant funds at their disposal.\par \par \uc2 "The global landscape has shifted pretty radically," says Scott Morris, a senior associate at the Centre for Global Development and an expert on issues relating to international financial institutions. "On the financial side, it's simply that the \uc2 World Bank\uc2  is becoming a smaller player in relative terms as there are new, larger sources of capital available for investment in poorer countries."\par \par \uc2 The global financial crisis has also taken its toll, with fiscal austerity hitting public-sector budgets.\par \par \uc2 Stretched finances focus attention on efficiency and measuring impact.\par \par \uc2 Sharad Sapra, principal adviser and director of Unicef's Innovation Centre in Nairobi, says: "There's a shift from programme delivery to programme results and a large part of that has evolved out of the financial crisis and looking for value for money."\par \par \uc2 Because tighter budgets mean doing more with less, many are looking for ways to harness the power of the private sector and the resources of global capital markets.\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 UK's Department for International Development\uc2 , for example, has used challenge funds to create incentives for companies to make business investments in developing countries when they might otherwise be too risky. In April, it launched a development impact bond to raise investment funds for the prevention of sleeping sickness in Uganda.\par \par \uc2 Development impact bonds - through which governments or international donors pay investors returns when a programme's goals have been achieved - are among a range of financing mechanisms being explored as a means of channelling investment funding into development.\par \par \uc2 Armed with private capital, organisations can make their development dollars go further. But this also requires them to hire finance-savvy individuals and others with skills not traditionally seen in the development world.\par \par \uc2 This is not always easy. While more business executives are seeking meaning in their careers and want to work for organisations helping solve big global problems, these days public sector institutions are not the only places they can do this.\par \par \uc2 From private foundations to the CSR (\b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 ) units of multinationals, executives looking for purpose have plenty of potential employers from which to choose. "There are a lot of places where you can be a development practitioner today," observes Mr Morris.\par \par \uc2 One way to build human capital is for organisations to look outside their own four walls.\par \par \uc2 The tabular content relating to this article is not available to view. Apologies in advance for the inconvenience caused.\par \par \uc2 <>Unicef, the \uc2 UN\uc2  children's agency, has established a growing network of innovation labs in countries ranging from Armenia to Zambia. At the labs, companies, academics and public sector groups work together on ideas and projects.\par \par \uc2 In April, the \uc2 US Agency for International Development\uc2  (\uc2 USAID\uc2 ) launched the Global Development Lab to promote use of science, technology and innovation and partnerships with a wide range of individuals and organisations.\par \par \uc2 Development Innovation Ventures (DIV), part of the Global Development Lab, uses an open competition to solicit ideas for tackling global poverty.\par \par \uc2 While a small team runs the unit, an investment panel - made up of \uc2 USAID\uc2  experts, venture capitalists, social enterprises, impact investors, academics and others - vets the ideas and decides which are worth supporting.\par \par \uc2 Investing relatively small amounts, DIV continues to support only those that demonstrate that they work.\par \par \uc2 It is a strategy more often seen among Silicon Valley investors, explains Jeff Brown, DIV's director. "And it recognises that in-house alone, we don't have the expertise to know which of these is the best."\par \par \uc2 These new approaches to development will be tough for some to adopt. After all, seeking and developing ideas externally means you need to relinquish a certain amount of control. As the \uc2 World Bank\uc2  has found, breaking down internal silos can be painful.\par \par \uc2 However, the changes may help organisations compete for talent. Mr Brown says about half his team took pay cuts to join DIV.\par \par \uc2 "It's pretty easy to recruit when you're asking people to come and look at some of the coolest ideas on the planet," he says.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CO\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 wbgrup : \uc2 The World Bank Group\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IPC\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 ON | ON24\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15