\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Commitment The number of leaders who think \uc2 CSR\uc2  very important has fallen, writes Elaine Moore\par \par \uc2 As economists make guarded statements to the effect that the worst of the financial crisis may be over, a public debate is under way over who is benefiting most from the global economic recovery.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Inequality has become this year's talking point, propelling Thomas Piketty's Capital in the Twenty-First Century into the \uc2 New York Times\uc2  best-seller list. The book's findings have been used in many arguments, including an unexpected reference by shareholder activist \uc2 Carl Icahn\uc2  in his criticism of executive pay at \uc2 Coca-Cola\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 There are signs that the financial crisis, which did so much damage to corporate reputations and balance sheets, put \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  (\uc2 CSR\uc2 ) on the back burner.\par \par \uc2 But think-tanks say that Mr Piketty's book, which argues that governments must act to address the widening gap between rich and poor, could prompt a wider debate about the way capitalism is structured, and lead to new commitments.\par \par \uc2 CSR\uc2  has already entered into the mainstream. More than 85 per cent of the companies that make up the FTSE 100 are reporting on responsibility, and companies are aware of the expectation that a published strategy should be in place.\par \par \uc2 Global plans have been made to formalise a definition of corporate responsibility, including the \uc2 UN Global Compact\uc2  , and governments have publicised the actions taken by domestic companies.\par \par \uc2 In the UK, \uc2 David Cameron\uc2 , the prime minister, appointed Philip Green, the former chief executive of United Utilities, as an adviser on responsible business and set up an informal working group called the Open Business Forum to discuss ways to improve transparency.\par \par \uc2 In April, the government published its response to a consultation on \uc2 CSR\uc2  as part of its Responsible \uc2 Business Week\uc2 , in which it outlined ways businesses could contribute to long-term sustainable growth. The report found that most companies were going beyond legal requirements to manage and enhance their economic, environmental and societal impacts.\par \par \uc2 In spite of those findings, there are signs that enthusiasm among governments is not being matched by companies.\par \par \uc2 A recent survey of more than 1,000 chief executives by the \uc2 UN Global Compact\uc2  and \uc2 Accenture\uc2 , the consultancy, found that few business leaders believed that their company's share price reflected its responsible business initiatives. The number who thought initiatives would be very important to the success of their business had fallen over the past few years to fewer than half of those surveyed.\par \par \uc2 The mood is markedly different from the early years of the new millennium, when business leaders gathered to discuss climate change and ways in which markets could reward sustainable behaviour.\par \par \uc2 Pre-crisis, advocates of \uc2 CSR\uc2  were encouraging businesses to consider positive social behaviour as a virtuous cycle that would feed into their corporate performance. Investing in communities would, the thinking went, improve a company's reputation with its customers and the wider world, which would in turn attract better talent and so develop the business and eventually the wider economy.\par \par \uc2 The advent of the financial crisis and economic downturn has put pressure on a model that makes it difficult for business leaders to pin down shorter-term benefits.\par \par \uc2 "When the financial crisis first struck, it seemed like there was a window of opportunity for serious reflection on the wider purpose of business," says Mallen Baker, an adviser on responsible business. "But that was shortlived, and the typical reaction to recession - to achieve growth at all costs - rather took over. The good news is that the financial crisis did not lessen the commitment by businesses on the whole."\par \par \uc2 However, Peter Lacy, managing director of strategy and sustainability services for \uc2 Accenture\uc2  in the Asia-Pacific region, says businesses may have stalled in their advancement of sustainability.\par \par \uc2 "Chief executives see business caught in a cycle of 'pilot paralysis' - individual, small-scale projects, programmes and business units with an incremental impact on sustainability metrics," he wrote in a report on the future of \uc2 CSR\uc2  .\par \par \uc2 Other organisations say the crisis has focused and streamlined the types of \uc2 CSR\uc2  business leaders engage in.\par \par \uc2 The UK's \uc2 Charities Aid Foundation\uc2 , which works with about 7,000 employers, including most of the FTSE 100 companies, says spending on responsible business has picked up over the past few years, as has interest in special vehicles, such as funds and bonds, used to give effectively.\par \par \uc2 Amy Clarke, head of advisory and consulting, says: "Since the depth of the economic downturn, we have seen increasing interest in and appetite for the use of social investment vehicles alongside more traditional philanthropic donations and grants."\par \par \uc2 "We find that companies are . . . more strategic and want to maximise the impact of their philanthropic capital for a longer period of time. Put simply, they are looking for more bang for their bucks."\par \par \uc2 If companies are struggling to make a business case for investment in certain schemes they can adopt a new approach, say analysts: sustainability.\par \par \uc2 Action to reduce packaging, cut electricity, water and fuel use not only helps the planet, it can also cut costs.\par \par \uc2 Unilever\uc2  announced last year it had cut its energy use and its operating costs by $395m since 2008, while \uc2 Intel\uc2  announced in 2012 that its energy reduction produced $23m in annual costs savings since 2001.\par \par \uc2 CSR International, a London-based social enterprise, believes investment in \uc2 CSR\uc2  will rise as a result of the crisis, as companies think more broadly about their actions.\par \par \uc2 Last year, it interviewed professionals within the sector and found that more believed spending on \uc2 CSR\uc2  would increase than thought it would decrease.\par \par \uc2 However it also discovered that most made a distinction between \uc2 CSR\uc2  that focused on philanthropy - such as donations - and corporate sustainability programmes.\par \par \uc2 The professionals predicted that \uc2 CSR\uc2  programmes primarily focused on philanthropy - such as sponsorship, donations and charity volunteering - were likely to suffer substantial cuts.\par \par \uc2 Corporate sustainability programmes, on the other hand, which attempted to link the good of the planet with profit, would go from strength to strength.\par \par \uc2 Business in the Community, a charity backed by some of Britain's biggest companies, insists corporate engagement in \uc2 CSR\uc2  has not dipped in the wake of the crisis.\par \par \uc2 "The expectation might have been that business would go into survival mode," says Stephen Howard, chief executive.\par \par \uc2 "But this hasn't been the case. What has been remarkable, is how responsible business has responded to the challenging external \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and how the requirement to do more with less, has driven a new understanding by businesses of its contract with society."\par \par \uc2 Mark Price\par \par \uc2 Managing director, Waitrose\par \par \uc2 'A flourishing modern business is responsible in spirit, attitude and action.\par \par \uc2 Profitability and responsibility are not incompatible goals, they go hand in hand. What is good for society is good for business.'\par \par \uc2 Christine Hodgson\par \par \uc2 Executive chair, \uc2 Capgemini\par \par \uc2 'In today's unpredictable economy, the need for responsible business practices is critical. That is why a commitment to high ethical standards and core values underpins everything we do.'\par \par \uc2 Ian Cheshire\par \par \uc2 Chief executive, Kingfisher\par \par \uc2 'Business is an engine for change. We are bumping up against planetary pressures, so responsible business is the only strategy to securing viability in the long term.\par \par \uc2 If business is the heartbeat of our economy, responsible business keeps it pumping.'\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CO\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 coca : \uc2 The Coca-Cola Company\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctl