ntbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (Copyright (c) 2014, Dow Jones & Company, Inc.)   \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 PARIS -- While activist investor \uc2 Nelson Peltz\uc2  advocates breaking up \uc2 DuPont Co\uc2 . to unlock value in its divisions, many European investors are more focused on the value of \uc2 DuPont\uc2 's environmental targets -- from carbon emissions to water use.\par \par \uc2 "When I go to Europe, our investor interactions, they are constantly inquiring about our sustainability goals," says Nick Fanandakis, \uc2 DuPont\uc2 's chief financial officer.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 "Very seldom do I get a quarterly [financial] question from an investor. They don't want to know about the quarter, they want to know about five years out, 10 years out," he adds.\par \par \uc2 Ask almost any of the CFOs who court investors in Europe, and they will tell you they have to tailor their company's story around their environmental, social and governance strategies. European investors want to see long-term targets and metrics to measure success. The planet typically trumps short-term profits.\par \par \uc2 "European investors are used to challenging companies on this," says Benoit Bergua, a senior analyst in London for capital-markets research firm Ipreo. "They really do believe that if a company has strong sustainability or a good corporate-responsibility performance, then financially it will outperform."\par \par \uc2 Investment companies such as French asset manager Amundi, jointly created by \uc2 Credit Agricole\uc2  and \uc2 Societe Generale\uc2 , have developed formulas to evaluate companies on nonfinancial factors. The firm has a team of analysts that looks at general and industry-specific criteria, based on guidelines from the United Nations, \uc2 Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development\uc2 , \uc2 World Resources Institute\uc2  and others international organizations.\par \par \uc2 Criteria are weighted by sector. For an auto maker, for example, environmental factors account for 38% of the company's sustainability score, compared with 28% for a drug company.\par \par \uc2 Social issues, by contrast are worth 42% in the pharmaceutical sector, but only 34% for the auto industry.\par \par \uc2 "If [environmental or social] practices are unsustainable, we of course have to consider our reputational risk," said Romain Boscher, Amundi's global head of equities.\par \par \uc2 While investors have been driving the trend, legislation in Europe will soon require companies to disclose their impact on the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and society.\par \par \uc2 By 2017, companies with over 500 employees in the 28 \uc2 European Union\uc2  countries will have to publish annual nonfinancial reports.\par \par \uc2 These companies must detail their environmental performance, human-rights policies and diversity in management, among other things, following guidelines set out by the Global Reporting Initiative, which advocates clear disclosure in those areas, or the International Integrated Reporting Council, whose members include international regulators.\par \par \uc2 In addition, companies must include information about their suppliers. The mandate is expected to affect more than 6,000 companies, including some U.S.-based multinationals.\par \par \uc2 Investors hope this will make performance benchmarks more uniform, allowing for easier comparisons across sectors and countries.\par \par \uc2 "The definitions of sustainability are not always exactly the same around the world," says Mr. Boscher.\par \par \uc2 Of course, many American companies already publish their own version of sustainability reports. Last year, 72% of the companies in the S&P 500 index filed such reports, up from 53% in 2012 and 20% in 2011, according to the \uc2 Governance & Accountability Institute Inc\uc2 ., a research firm.\par \par \uc2 Because the criteria they use vary widely, the \uc2 World Federation of Exchanges\uc2 , which represents global stock markets, set up a working group in March to improve consistency and share best practices.\par \par \uc2 The group is expected to debate proposals at its annual meeting next month.\par \par \uc2 But not all CFOs are eager to calculate their company's sustainability. A survey last year by Duke University's Fuqua School of Business found that American CFOs were much less interested in \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  -- using environmentally friendly products or giving back to a local community, for instance -- than their European peers.\par \par \uc2 Less than half of the 353 American financial chiefs polled said it was important to their business strategy, compared with 63% of CFOs in Europe.\par \par \uc2 Many investment companies want to get a better grip on how companies might respond to risks and opportunities arising from environmental and other controversies, says Bozena Jankowska, a global co-head for the environmental and sustainability unit of \uc2 Allianz Global Investors\uc2  in Germany.\par \par \uc2 "We have. . .had discussions with a number of U.S. food retailers to assess their resilience in the context of the [genetically modified food] labeling debate," she says.\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.djreprints.com/link/DJRFactiva.html?FACTIVA=wjco20140923000091"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 License this article from Dow Jones Reprint Service}}}\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CO\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 dupnt : \uc2 E.I. DuPont de Nemours & Company\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 i25 : \uc2 Chemicals | ibasicm : \uc2 Basic Materials/Resources\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd