ing to include that provision, many Europeans oppose it. The measure has become one of the main sticking points in negotiations over the proposed trade pact, known as the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 A review of more than 150,000 public comments on the matter ''clearly shows that there is a huge skepticism'' toward the investment guarantee provision, Cecilia Malmstrom, the \uc2 European Union\uc2 's trade commissioner, said in a statement on Tuesday.\par \par \uc2 The trade pact itself is no sure bet, as negotiators on both sides of the Atlantic have shown little progress after more than a year of periodic talks. For European opponents of the investment guarantee provision, the concern is that if it became part of a trade agreement, it would give companies a legal opening to erode European standards in environmental protection, food quality and labor rights.\par \par \uc2 The issue has become the rallying point for groups that mistrust the \uc2 European Union\uc2 , which they see as being unable to control migration and trim unemployment in the bloc, and are suspicious of the United States, which is widely regarded as mismanaging its global power and clumsily imposing electronic surveillance that threatens the privacy of European citizens.\par \par \uc2 Powerful figures like Sigmar Gabriel, the German economy minister, have called that clause unnecessary, and Matthias Fekl, the French junior minister for trade, has said that including it would make any deal unacceptable to Europe.\par \par \uc2 But many American and European trade experts say the guarantee should be part of any modern trade agreement between the \uc2 European Union\uc2  and the United States, which have the two largest economies in the world. Such proponents note that recently agreed-upon European accords with Canada and Singapore contain the guarantee, although those pacts still await ratification by European lawmakers.\par \par \uc2 On Tuesday, Ms. Malmstrom said she was still not ready to recommend how to modify the guarantee or say whether it should be jettisoned. Instead she highlighted the main issues raised by the results of the 140-page review of public comments and noted there were ''areas that can be reformed.''\par \par \uc2 The proposed trade pact has been under formal negotiation since early 2013, when it was announced by President Obama in his annual State of the Union address. It was initially welcomed by \uc2 European Union\uc2  leaders as a debt-free way to spur economic growth in a region plagued by a long debt crisis and high unemployment.\par \par \uc2 Yet progress has been slow.\par \par \uc2 Despite seven rounds of rotating meetings in Washington and Brussels, the negotiators have been at odds over how to lower tariffs and, among other sticking points, whether to include financial services in any deal.\par \par \uc2 The next round of talks is scheduled in Brussels during the first week of February. But talks on the investment guarantee will remain suspended until the \uc2 European Commission\uc2 , the \uc2 European Union\uc2 's executive branch, can try to hash out a possible compromise. Officials said on Tuesday that they had no firm timetable for taking that step.\par \par \uc2 The call for comments on the investment guarantee was conducted by the \uc2 European Commission\uc2  from March through July, and generated 150,000 responses. \uc2 European Union\uc2  officials said that was probably a record for such an exercise, although it indicated there might have been considerable lobbying by advocacy groups, as about 145,000 of those responses were submitted through online platforms using ''predefined, negative answers.''\par \par \uc2 The comments -- officially known as a public consultation -- showed trade unions and other campaign groups seeking more assurances that governments could regulate in the public interest, and seeking obligations on businesses to abide by standards on human rights, the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 , according to the commission.\par \par \uc2 But ''excluding investment protection from the T.T.I.P. negotiations is simply not an option,'' said Lourdes Catrain, a partner in Brussels with the law firm \uc2 Hogan Lovells\uc2 , using the trade proposal's acronym.\par \par \uc2 ''The United States is the E.U.'s largest trading partner, and it clearly wants investment protection," said Ms. Catrain, whose firm advised companies participating in the public consultation. ''Leaving it out of that deal would weaken Europe's negotiating position with China and other parts of the world where European companies are seeking similar investment protections.''\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CO\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 usagov : \uc2 United States Federal Government | euruno : \uc2 The European Union\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\