ight\rin0\lin0 \b LA\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 English\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Copyright 2015, The Washington Post Co.  All Rights Reserved.   \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 President \uc2 Obama\uc2  signed an executive order Thursday dictating the federal government will cut its\u160\'00\'A0greenhouse gas emissions\u160\'00\'A040 percent over the next decade from 2008 levels and increase the share of renewable energy in the federal government's electricity supply to 30 percent during that same period.\par \par \uc2 Simultaneously, federal suppliers including \uc2 Honeywell\uc2 , \uc2 IBM\uc2 , \uc2 General Electric\uc2  and other major U.S. firms are pledging to\u160\'00\'A0reduce their own carbon footprint by 5\u160\'00\'A0million metric tons over the next 10 years compared with 2008 levels. Taken together with the new executive order this would cut overall U.S. emissions by 26 million tons by 2025, the equivalent of taking nearly 5.5 million cars off the roads for a year.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Speaking to reporters Thursday at the Energy Department, \uc2 Obama\uc2  said that "America once\u160\'00\'A0again is going to be leading by example."\par \par \uc2 "So we're proving that it is possible to grow our economy robustly while at the same time doing the right thing for our \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and tackling climate change in a serious way," he said.\par \par \uc2 White House senior adviser Brian Deese\u160\'00\'A0estimated the new measures will save $18 billion; the federal government has already cut its overall emissions 17 percent since \uc2 Obama\uc2  took office, saving $1.8 billion.\par \par \uc2 The move comes on the day the president is meeting with Britain's Prince Charles\u160\'00\'A0\u8212\'20\'14 a prominent environmentalist and climate change advocate \u8212\'20\'14 and his wife, the Duchess of Cornwall, in the Oval Office. \uc2 Obama\uc2  and Charles are slated to discuss the two nations' efforts to address global warming, as well as\u160\'00\'A0encouraging \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 , creating opportunities for young people and preserving historical and cultural ties between\u160\'00\'A0Britain and the United States.\par \par \uc2 The\u160\'00\'A0executive order details\u160\'00\'A0how the government will meet the new climate target. This will include reducing energy use in federal buildings by 2.5 percent per year between 2015 and 2025, instructing agencies to obtain 25 percent of their energy from carbon-free sources by 2025; and increasing the carbon-per-mile efficiency of\u160\'00\'A0federal fleets 30 percent from 2014 levels over the next decade while increasing the percentage of zero emission and plug-in hybrid vehicles in federal fleets.\par \par \uc2 After\u160\'00\'A0signing the executive order at the White House, \uc2 Obama\uc2  toured\u160\'00\'A0the Energy Department's rooftop solar panels and attended a roundtable there where some of the federal suppliers discussed their\u160\'00\'A0new climate\u160\'00\'A0commitments.The companies will publicly disclose how closely they are meeting these greenhouse gas reduction pledges over time.\par \par \uc2 The federal government is the largest energy consumer in the United States \u8212\'20\'14 with the military accounting for roughly half of its total energy use \u8212\'20\'14 though its greenhouse gas emissions constituted\u160\'00\'A0only 0.6 percent of the nation's total output in 2013, according to federal data. Still, \uc2 Christy Goldfuss\uc2 , acting director of the White House Council on Environmental Quality, said federal\u160\'00\'A0actions can have a huge impact given its reach and the scope of its supply chain.\par \par \uc2 "President \uc2 Obama\uc2  has made it clear that climate change is an all-hands-on-deck challenge," Goldfuss said,\u160\'00\'A0noting the federal portfolio boasts\u160\'00\'A0360,000 buildings, 650,000 fleet vehicles, and $445 billion\u160\'00\'A0in spending\u160\'00\'A0on goods and services.\par \par \uc2 While the federal government met\u160\'00\'A0the\u160\'00\'A0climate target \uc2 Obama\uc2  set out in his first term relatively easily, it \u160\'00\'A0has faced some challenges in reducing greenhouse gas emissions in some areas. The 2007\u160\'00\'A0Energy Independence and Security Act dictated all new federal buildings and those undergoing major\u160\'00\'A0renovations had to use fossil-fuel free energy by 2030. The Energy Department has been slow to implement the rule, and a bipartisan coalition in \uc2 the Senate\uc2  is seeking to roll back the measure.\par \par \uc2 In October DOE put out guidance that keeps the target in place but allows for some exceptions, including an exemption if an agency determines that it is not technically practical to meet it.\par \par \uc2 Dave McCurdy\uc2 , president and CEO of the American Gas Association, said in a statement that while his group supports federal efforts to address climate change the government shouldn't make it harder for Americans to use natural gas.\par \par \uc2 "We have repeatedly reminded this administration about the benefits of direct use of clean natural gas in homes and businesses," McCurdy said, " Natural gas used directly for heating, water heating, cooking and clothes drying is the most efficient, affordable and environmentally friendly way to use this abundant, domestic resource."\par \par \uc2 At the same time, the liberal think tank \uc2 Center for American Progress\uc2  issued a report Thursday finding\u160\'00\'A0that greenhouse gas emissions generated by\u160\'00\'A0gas, oil, and coal extracted from federal lands and waters accounts for one-fifth of the nation's total carbon output.\par \par \uc2 The group\u8212\'20\'14which is usually supportive of the administration, and employed both\u160\'00\'A0Deese and Goldfuss before they joined the White House\u8212\'20\'14called the emissions "a blind spot in U.S. efforts to address climate change."\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 i1 : \uc2 Energy\cell \pa