ypenny notes that the Founders pledge and "CSR was the last thing on my mind" when starting her company.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Philanthropy by founders and others who have made money is highly commendable, but it is a mistake to conflate it with corporate responsibility, social or otherwise.\par \par \uc2 The Quaker chocolate manufacturers of a couple of hundred years ago and Henry Ford both knew that decent working conditions and wages were not only responsible but good for business. Embedding principles such as those of the \uc2 UN Global Compact\uc2  on human rights, working conditions the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and anti-corruption is very different from philanthropy. Both have their place. There may be discussion as to when the best time might be for entrepreneurial owners to think about giving away some of any gains, but it is absolutely never too early to build a consideration of the impact and utility of your product or service on society and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  into the fabric of your enterprise and to consider whether the human and physical aspects of the production process are indeed responsible.\par \par \uc2 Considering the benefits or otherwise of your product and processes on society and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  is not philanthropy, it is the foundation of a good business.\par \par \uc2 Mark Moody-Stuart\par \par \uc2 London E1, UK\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\fa