h15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Copyright 2015 The Financial Times Ltd. All rights reserved. Please do not cut and paste FT articles and redistribute by email or post to the web. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 * Myanmar\u8217\'20\'19s biggest conglomerates \u8211\'20\'13 such as Asia World, Htoo and Max Myanmar \u8211\'20\'13 dominate key industries and have evolved into professional organisations. They are seeking foreign capital, partnerships and management expertise to drive future expansion.\par \par \uc2 * However, Myanmar\u8217\'20\'19s troubled reputation and the slow pace of economic reform still deters foreign investors. Many are awaiting the outcome of November\u8217\'20\'19s general election, which we expect to maintain the status quo.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 * Significant challenges remain in attracting foreign investment, including navigating continued US sanctions and reputational risks arising from local firms\u8217\'20\'19 links to contentious issues like land appropriation.\par \par \uc2 * Since Myanmar began its economic liberalisation programme in 2011, a raft of new private businesses have been launched. However, few have the resources to challenge the established conglomerates.\par \par \uc2 It is four years since Myanmar began the slow and tortuous process of economic and political reform, after half a century of authoritarian military rule. It was a pariah state for two decades following a political crackdown in 1990. The country has enormous potential, boasting large reserves of oil and gas, gemstones and an array of agricultural and mineral commodities.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 But it faces serious challenges in creating an open and transparent business \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Years of international isolation led to the formation of about 20 powerful and highly profitable domestic conglomerates that dominate vast swathes of the economy and hinder attempts to foster competition. Most of these conglomerates (see chart) made their fortunes under former military leader General Than Shwe, who ruled from 1992 to 2011. The tight grip they hold over key industries, such as construction, manufacturing and transportation, means that foreign investors often have little choice but to do business with them.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 Large conglomerates dominate economy\par \par \uc2 The most influential conglomerates \u8211\'20\'13 Asia World, Htoo and Max Myanmar \u8211\'20\'13 have highly diversified operations and each generates annual revenues of at least $500m-1bn.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 Asia World, the largest of the three, is involved in an array of sectors including construction, transport and retail. It is led by Steven Law, the son of the late Lo Hsing Han, who founded Asia World after making his fortune in drug trafficking. Htoo is controlled by tycoon Tay Za, and has interests such as logging, shipping and mining. Max Myanmar\u8217\'20\'19s portfolio, meanwhile, includes hospitality, manufacturing and banking, and the firm is headed up by \uc2 Zaw Zaw\uc2 .\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 Myanmar\u8217\'20\'19s isolation created an illiquid marketplace, largely devoid of bank lending. This was to the advantage of the large conglomerates, which cultivated close ties with the ruling military junta. They were able to secure control of import and export operations, with concessions in extractive industries, and sign big deals with China. They also benefited from weighty public development contracts handed out by the junta as part of stuttering efforts to privatise the economy in the 1990s. Cash generated by these deals was used to expand operations across an array of sectors. Further sweeping privatisation efforts in recent years have led to the sale of more than 300 state-owned assets, to the continued benefit of these conglomerates.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 Foreign investment growing\par \par \uc2 Today, looking to maintain their dominant position and capitalise on the opportunities presented by Myanmar\u8217\'20\'19s economic and political reforms, many of these conglomerates are seeking foreign investment.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 Several joint-venture (JV) agreements between conglomerates and foreign investors have been signed, resulting in the entry of global brands into Myanmar, including:\par \par \uc2 * \uc2 Jaguar\uc2  and \uc2 Land Rover\uc2  \u8211\'20\'13 owned by \uc2 Tata Motors\uc2  \u8211\'20\'13 and Ford, via a tie-up between local firm Capital Diamond Star (CDSG) and Thailand\u8217\'20\'19s RMA.\par \par \uc2 * \uc2 Mitsubishi Motors\uc2  and \uc2 Yum Brands\uc2 , through Yoma Strategic.\par \par \uc2 * \uc2 Accor\uc2  , via a tie-up with Max Myanmar.\par \par \uc2 * \uc2 British American Tobacco\uc2 , Skechers Footwear and \uc2 Quiksilver\uc2 , through Sein Wut Hmon.\par \par \uc2 A number of major US companies have also recently disclosed investment in the country, including:\par \par \uc2 * Consumer goods giant \uc2 Colgate-Palmolive\uc2 , which in late 2014 acquired a local toothpaste-maker.\par \par \uc2 * \uc2 Coca Cola\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 * Money-transfer company \uc2 Western Union\uc2 , which signed a deal with Kanbawza Bank.\par \par \uc2 * Casualwear retailer Gap.\par \par \uc2 The country has begun to liberalise its banking sector, granting licences to nine foreign banks, and while many foreign institutions still refuse to fund projects in Myanmar, others have lifted restrictions. Singapore\u8217\'20\'19s \uc2 United Overseas Bank\uc2 , for example, has begun issuing loans in the country, including those for the refurbishment of the Rangoon Excelsior hotel.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 World Bank\uc2  has also begun lending again in Myanmar (see chart), while the \uc2 International Finance Corporation\uc2  (\uc2 IFC\uc2 ) is building credit facilities for mid-sized domestic banks. Over the longer term, foreign investment and management will be crucial to the development of Myanmar\u8217\'20\'19s financial sector.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 Foreign expertise sought\par \par \uc2 In addition to seeking foreign capital, a number of Burmese companies are looking to attract foreign talent and modernise their management structures. Supermarket firm City Mart, the Kanbawza Group (KBZ) and Max Myanmar are among the many Burmese groups that have hired foreign managers.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CIf a domestic group is able to retain foreign talent it is a sign that the company is heading in the right direction,\u8221\'20\'1D said Philippe May, a former Asia World employee who is now chief business officer at Max Myanmar\u8217\'20\'19s Ayeyarwady Bank.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 Serge Pun and Associates\uc2  \u8211\'20\'13 whose diversified interests include Singapore-listed Yoma Strategic and First Myanmar Investment \u8211\'20\'13 has foreign managers that have been with the group for more than a decade. The company has been a popular play among foreign investors seeking Myanmar exposure, although enthusiasm has dipped a little in recent months (see chart).\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 However, few expats end up in leadership roles due to protectionist local regulations. Furthermore, while many Burmese conglomerates are keen to modernise their operations, plum roles are still often handed to family members, who generally retain a disproportionate level of control. This weakens corporate governance, which hinders attempts to attract outside funding. \u8220\'20\'1CThe conglomerates that are doing the best tend to be those that no longer operate as family-run businesses,\u8221\'20\'1D said the head of a Yangon-based investment firm.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 Lingering sanctions a hindrance\par \par \uc2 Indeed, improved transparency is crucial for Burmese firms, as it can contribute to the lifting of US sanctions that still hang over many local tycoons.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 Myanmar has been subject to international sanctions since 1988, when they were first imposed by Japan. The US followed suit in 1997, banning new investment by US firms. Most developed nations lifted sanctions entirely after 2011, but although the US eased its rules in 2013, most of its sanctions remain.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 As part of these sanctions, the \uc2 US Treasury\u8217\'20\'19s Office of Foreign Assets Control (OFAC) \uc2 prohibits US entities from trading with so-called specially designated nationals (SDN) and most of the businesses they control. Individuals can petition OFAC to be removed from the SDN list. While the final decision rests with the \uc2 US Congress\uc2 , OFAC retains considerable discretion over removal, leading to complaints that the process is skewed and politically motivated. OFAC has stated it applies five criteria for individuals seeking removal from the list:\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 * Provide transparent business accounts.\par \par \uc2 * Sever all business ties to the military.\par \par \uc2 * Resolve land ownership issues for appropriated land.\par \par \uc2 * Support \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 * Support general economic and political reforms.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 Win Aung, the head of diversified conglomerate Dagon International, was the first tycoon to be removed from the list in April 2015 after petitioning OFAC for 14 months. It is possible that this was expedited by pressure from Japanese investors who have committed funds to the Thilawa Special Economic Zone, in which Mr Aung plays a leading role.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 Many other business owners, however, have yet to be removed. Both Mr Tay Za and \uc2 Mr Zaw Zaw\uc2  remain on the list, despite active public relations campaigns. The sanctions have somewhat hindered both groups\u8217\'20\'19 efforts to link up with foreign partners. \u8220\'20\'1CEven non-American companies are cautious about dealing with SDN-listed companies\u8221\'20\'1D, a businessman told FT Confidential Research.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 Reputational risks remain\par \par \uc2 The inconsistencies in the SDN sanctions process are highlighted by the scores of businesses involved in controversial resource extraction industries and questionable land acquisition practices that are not on the list.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 KBZ, for example, one of the country\u8217\'20\'19s largest conglomerates, is heavily involved in such controversial sectors, including significant interests in mining.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 Sein Wut Hmon, a conglomerate wholly owned by businessman Maung Myint, is similarly involved in controversial projects. It has come under scathing attack by London-based environmental watchdog \uc2 Global Witness\uc2 , which has accused it of colluding with military battalions in north-eastern Shan state to confiscate large swathes of farming land for conversion into rubber plantations, providing little compensation and forcing local people into unpaid labour. Yet it remains off the SDN list.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 This is not a one-off: at least 5.3m acres of land \u8211\'20\'13 equivalent to 35 times the size of Yangon \u8211\'20\'13 have been awarded to agribusiness investors in recent years, mostly without owners\u8217\'20\'19 consent, according to \uc2 Global Witness\uc2 .\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 In the absence of an SDN listing, there is no legal obstacle to foreign investment in companies involved in such controversies. But they do create reputational risks, similar to those associated with Hoang Anh Gia Lai in Vietnam, for example, which has been accused of large-scale forest clearing and illegal logging.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 Such reputational risks extend across a wide range of lucrative industries, including mining, gems, jade and timber, though a number of local firms are now looking to withdraw from these areas as part of attempts to get themselves removed from the SDN sanctions list and attract foreign capital. Max Myanmar, for example, claims to have exited gem mining.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 However, mining activity around Myanmar has gathered pace over the last year and official Chinese imports of jade have soared (see chart).\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 Newer players expand aggressively\par \par \uc2 Further down the economic scale, Myanmar\u8217\'20\'19s economic liberalisation programme has spurred a surge in private business start-ups, though few of these new businesses have the clout to challenge the big conglomerates.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 Nonetheless, unhindered by sanctions and sometimes supported by strong balance sheets, many are aggressively expanding into new growth sectors such as tourism, hotels and banking, which hold the promise of straightforward arrangements with foreign partners (see Insight, below).\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 One prominent example is CDSG, headed by Ko Ko Gyi, which was named a Global Growth Company at the \uc2 World Economic Forum\uc2  in 2014. The group is highly diversified. In addition to the tie-up with RMA mentioned above, the company this year created a new JV, Lluvia, with Japan\u8217\'20\'19s \uc2 Mitsubishi\uc2 , which will invest $200m in food businesses.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 Power structure to remain unchanged\par \par \uc2 While there are reasons for optimism, Myanmar\u8217\'20\'19s general elections in November present a degree of risk to the current stability. In May, the US renewed its existing Myanmar sanctions \u8211\'20\'13 which, in addition to SDN restrictions, block imports of Burmese jade and other gemstones \u8211\'20\'13 and any further easing of restrictions is, in effect, dependent on the election\u8217\'20\'19s outcome.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 The Burmese legislature is made up of two houses, a 224-seat upper house and a 440-seat lower house. The current opposition National League for Democracy (NLD) party, led by \uc2 Aung San Suu Kyi\uc2  \u8211\'20\'13 who is barred from running for president on account of the foreign passports held by her two British sons \u8211\'20\'13 is expected to win a large number of seats in both.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 However, the military retains 25 per cent of seats across both houses, providing it with an effective veto on any attempt at real political reform because changes to the constitution require at least 75 per cent of parliament\u8217\'20\'19s support.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 While there are concerns that a disputed election could lead to political unrest, the general consensus is that the ruling Union Solidarity and Development Party (USDP) will remain in power after the poll.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 On the assumption that the elections will be held in a free and fair manner, the NLD looks likely to pick up large numbers of seats in central Myanmar, including in the cities of Yangon and Mandalay, while the USDP looks likely to retain support in some rural areas. We expect the election\u8217\'20\'19s outcome to encourage a two-party system in Myanmar, although the general consensus is that the USDP will still call the shots regardless of the result, due to its stranglehold over the constitution. Although the status quo is unlikely to change significantly, the loosening of US sanctions should continue as long as economic and political reforms remain on the table.\par \par \uc2 ---\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 INSIGHT: Travel portal part of new wave\par \par \uc2 Nay Aung returned to his native Myanmar from the US three years ago and founded online travel agency Oway. The company now employs 130 staff and is part of a new generation of companies spearheading growth in new industries.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 Myanmar\u8217\'20\'19s burgeoning tourism industry has recorded annual growth of 50-100 per cent over the last four years. The country attracted 3.5m tourists last year, although Mr Aung estimates that more than half the visitors entered by land from bordering Thailand, and are unlikely to have spent heavily. As such, the number of higher-spending tourists from further afield may have numbered about 1.5m. To put this figure into perspective, Thailand attracted 26m visitors in 2014, Vietnam 9m and Cambodia 6m.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CThere is huge market potential,\u8221\'20\'1D Mr Aung said. Myanmar\u8217\'20\'19s tourism industry is predominantly cash-based, but this is set to change as more people book travel online. And there are a growing number of small firms \u8211\'20\'13 including some operated by foreigners \u8211\'20\'13 that are looking to take advantage. Oway allows people to pay for travel-related bookings with credit cards and has grown rapidly to become a market leader in domestic flight ticketing.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 Nonetheless, the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  for budding entrepreneurs in Myanmar remains uncertain, and largely determined by government policy. As far as Mr Aung is concerned, it is vital that the government limits the conglomerates\u8217\'20\'19 stranglehold over the economy. \u8220\'20\'1CThe government needs to encourage a broader base of companies to move up the ladder,\u8221\'20\'1D he said. The extent to which it is prepared to abandon its traditional links with these large companies, however, remains unclear.\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.ft.com/emerging-markets/ft-confidential-research"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 FT Confidential Research }}}\uc2  is an independent research service from the \uc2 Financial Times\uc2 , providing in-depth analysis of and statistical insight into China and Southeast Asia. Our team of researchers in these key markets combine findings from our proprietary surveys with on-the-ground research to provide predictive analysis for investors.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 gvote1 : \uc2 National/Presidential Elections | gcat : \uc2 Political/General News | gpir : \uc2 Politics/International Relations | gpol : \uc2 Domestic Politics | gvote : \uc2 Elections\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \cl