reholder activism by Roman Catholic investors. \par \par \uc2 This spring, as \uc2 Pope Francis\uc2  prepared his 183-page encyclical calling for a phaseout of fossil fuels, several Catholic institutions in the U.S., including universities and religious orders, began taking steps to dump stocks with heavy exposure to coal and other greenhouse-gas-emitting energy sources.   \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 They also urged companies ranging from \uc2 Bank of America Corp\uc2 . and \uc2 Kraft Foods Group Inc\uc2 . to \uc2 DuPont Co\uc2 . to disclose more information about their carbon emissions and the environmental impact of their businesses.\par \par \uc2 Catholics, who number more than one billion world-wide and account for the largest organized religion in the U.S., control an estimated $150 billion in assets, according to Daniel Nielsen, a director at Christian Brothers Investment Services, a Chicago investment-management firm.\par \par \uc2 The encyclical, which calls {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.wsj.com/articles/pope-delivers-powerful-message-on-climate-change-1434621606"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 global warming a major threat to life on Earth}}}\uc2 and urges \u8220\'20\'1Curgent and compelling" steps to halt it is \u8220\'20\'1Ca wake-up call that climate change is a crisis," he said.    \par \par \uc2                                                                                                                             The papal letter, titled \u8220\'20\'1CLaudato Si: On Care For Our Common Home," is an in-depth discussion of the church's teachings on the subject. It was published June 18, but the Vatican announced it more than a year in advance, and many Catholics were sympathetic with its goals.   \par \par \uc2 Sister Nora Nash, a nun with the Sisters of St. Francis, outside of Philadelphia, who serves as her order's director of \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 , thinks the encyclical will help her keep up the pressure on companies in its portfolio for more environmental disclosures. \par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1COur earth is fragile. In the heart of the corporate world, we feel that we, too, can make a difference," she said. \par \par \uc2 The septuagenarian nun met with \uc2 Chevron Corp\uc2 . representatives in mid-June to urge the company to release more information about the hydraulic fracturing, or fracking, it does in her state, and its impact on the region's water. \par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CEvery part of our area is being pipelined to death," she said. \par \par \uc2 A Chevron spokesman said, \u8220\'20\'1CWe value their input, as well as the input of other stockholders." \par \par \uc2 At the largest 250 U.S. companies, Catholic groups have submitted 12 \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 -related shareholder proposals this year, up from seven in 2014, according to Proxymonitor.org, a website sponsored by the Manhattan Institute's Center for Legal Policy, a public-policy research group. \par \par \uc2 The movement has yet to produce major environmental policy changes at American companies, or to evolve into a coordinated campaign, but it is chipping away at the margins. \par \par \uc2 Among this year's proposals, religious investors asked companies to produce reports on sustainability and climate-change risk, to create targets for greenhouse-gas emissions, or appoint a director with environmental expertise.\par \par \uc2 The Sisters of the Holy Names of Jesus and Mary, who operate mostly in the U.S. and Canada, asked \uc2 Bank of America\uc2  in May for a report on climate change. \par \par \uc2 The bank opposed the request, saying in a proxy filing that a report detailing emissions and risk across all of its lending, investing and financing activities would \u8220\'20\'1Crequire considerable resources without conveying useful information." It said it already discloses greenhouse-gas emissions from its U.S. electric utility portfolio, and pointed to other reports, policies and procedures to address climate-change risk. \par \par \uc2 A \uc2 Bank of America\uc2  spokeswoman declined to comment.\par \par \uc2 Another religious order, the Missionary Oblates of Mary Immaculate, asked Kraft to produce and release a \u8220\'20\'1Ccomprehensive" sustainability report \u8220\'20\'1Cdescribing its environmental, social and governance performance and goals, including greenhouse-gas reduction goals."\par \par \uc2 At shareholder meetings in late May, the Sisters of St. Dominic of Caldwell asked \uc2 Chevron\uc2  and \uc2 Exxon Mobil Corp\uc2 . to provide better information on carbon emissions. That same month, another New Jersey-based order, the Sisters of Charity of St. Elizabeth, asked fellow shareholders of chemicals maker \uc2 DuPont\uc2  to support a resolution that the company monitor the herbicide farmers used with its crop seeds. \par \par \uc2 The companies opposed these proposals, saying in their proxies that the  information was available elsewhere, or that its publication wouldn't be a good use of corporate resources. Holders of between 5% and 30% of the companies' shares outstanding voted in favor of the measures. \par \par \uc2 DuPont\uc2  declined to comment beyond its filings. Kraft didn't respond to requests for comment.  \uc2 Exxon\uc2  sent company representatives to meet with Vatican officials in May to discuss global warming, a spokesman said.\par \par \uc2 Catholic investors have increased their environmental efforts in corporate boardrooms since late last year, when the pope indicated he would release the encyclical ahead of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.wsj.com/articles/china-pledges-to-cut-emissions-ahead-of-paris-climate-talks-1435682794"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 United Nations climate talks in Paris}}}\uc2  set for late 2015.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CThere is more pressure on Catholic investors to divest fossil fuels," said Father Michael Crosby, whose religious community in Milwaukee holds about $2,000 in \uc2 Exxon\uc2  shares. \u8220\'20\'1CYou have to either get out, or do something to get these companies to diversify their business models." \par \par \uc2 At \uc2 Exxon\uc2 's annual meeting in May, he asked Chief Executive \uc2 Rex Tillerson\uc2  \u8220\'20\'1Cto get an expert on the board" to advise the company on renewable energy. \par \par \uc2 Renewable energy \u8220\'20\'1Conly survives on the backs of enormous government mandates that are not sustainable," the CEO responded. \u8220\'20\'1CWe on purpose choose not to lose money."\par \par \uc2 Mercy Investment Services, the investment arm of the Sisters of Mercy, said it raised social issues at more than 140 companies this year, either directly or through shareholder resolutions. It said about a third of these efforts focused on environmental matters.\par \par \uc2 Under guidelines from the U.S. Conference of Catholic Bishops, Catholic institutions traditionally avoid companies that, among other things, produce tobacco or weapons of mass destruction or do stem-cell research.  \par \par \uc2 As many as 30% of public companies already fail the most rigorous application of these standards, said Jason Baron, who helps clients of \uc2 Bank of America\uc2 's U.S. Trust unit build portfolios that meet their individual social responsibility standards. Equally rigorous screening for carbon emissions would put 12% to 15% of more of them off limits. \par \par \uc2 Of course, attractive returns are still a goal for Catholic funds. \u8220\'20\'1CWe don't help people sleep at night by ethically losing money," Mr. Baron said. \par \par \uc2  Because each institution brings its own interpretation of church doctrine to its portfolio, each investment thesis is unique, according to James Ryan, an adviser with \uc2 Merrill Lynch\uc2 's Private Banking & Investment Group. \par \par \uc2 Catholic investors looking for ways to succeed both financially and ethically might simply sell off stocks they find environmentally questionable. \par \par \uc2 At a June 5 meeting in Dublin, the managers of the Oblate International Pastoral Investment Trust, which oversee $400 million in assets for more than 200 Catholic organizations, voted not to invest in resources or utility companies heavily involved in thermal coal and oil sands.  \par \par \uc2  The group may expand its blacklist in coming months, said Father Seamus Finn, the trust's head of global advocacy work.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CThe encyclical adds a universal call from the church that hasn't been there before," he said. \u8220\'20\'1CThis is an urgent, moral responsibility."\par \par \uc2 After the encyclical's release, Greg McIntire, portfolio manager for the SEI Catholic Values Funds, which oversee $170 million in assets in Pennsylvania, began planning to factor a company's carbon footprint into its investment choices for its clients. \par \par \uc2 Georgetown University\uc2 , one of 225 U.S.-based Catholic colleges and universities, with a $1.4 billion asset pool as of June 2014, said last month that it would no longer invest in coal companies. \par \par \uc2 American Coal Council President Betsy Monseu said institutions decide to sell off shares of coal companies for a variety of reasons. \par \par \uc2                 Write to Emily Chasan  at {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "mailto:emily.chasan@wsj.com"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 emily.chasan@wsj.com}}}\uc2  and Maxwell Murphy  at {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "mailto:maxwell.murphy@wsj.com"}}{\fldrslt{\c