lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b ET\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 11:38 AM GMT\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b SN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Financial Times (FT.Com)\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b SC\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 FTCOM\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LA\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 English\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Copyright 2015 The Financial Times Ltd. All rights reserved. Please do not cut and paste FT articles and redistribute by email or post to the web. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 The continuing migrant and refugee crisis has spurred hundreds of people, charities and aid organisations into action as stories and images shock the world.\par \par \uc2 But as Europe\u8217\'20\'19s governments come under pressure to act, what should the business community be doing to alleviate the crisis?\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 That was the question posed in the latest monthly online debate to members of the FT City Network, a group of more than 50 top financiers and businesspeople.\par \par \uc2 Sir Win Bischoff, FRC\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CBig business\u8221\'20\'1D as you call it has no direct role to play in this crisis. However, we all know how short some businesses say they are of skilled workers. They could list the skills they are looking for and for each refugee they take on with the requisite skills, they would not have to meet the normal immigration and nationality tests. In return, they would obligate themselves to take on an additional refugee who does not have the sought-for skills and would agree to train [them] for, say, a year to provide a skill.\par \par \uc2 Gives jobs, broadens skills, meets a shortage, is no charge on the Exchequer or taxpayer, while helping in a crisis.\par \par \uc2 Dame Fiona Woolf, former Lord Mayor of the City London\par \par \uc2 Sir Win has rightly focused on the skills perspective, which is an obvious one for big business. The question then arises as to whether big business has a role to play in influencing government policy, which has had its difficulties. It could do so from a skills perspective or some other perspective such as \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 , diversity, social mobility or humanitarian. It would need to show that it was prepared to lead by example and that might be a challenge.\par \par \uc2 Whatever angle you choose, business is going to have to deal with its own staff, shareholders and other stakeholders. Sir Win\u8217\'20\'19s approach based on skills is arguably the strongest in terms of justification to them. Sadly, some of the migrants will not be able to take up the opportunity to work or be trained and we do not know what proportion [will be] women for example.\par \par \uc2 Tidjane Thiam, \uc2 Credit Suisse\par \par \uc2 In the short term and on a tactical level, large companies can do at least three things: provide work opportunities for the migrants, support the charities that are working hard to address this human tragedy, and do everything they can to encourage their employees as individuals and citizens to get involved. Many companies are doing some or all of the above and that should not be underestimated \u8212\'20\'14 big business\u8217\'20\'19s philanthropic efforts tend to be pretty substantial nowadays.\par \par \uc2 In the longer run and on a more strategic level, I think it is incumbent on big business to continue to hold civil society\u8217\'20\'19s feet to the fire on issues such as skill shortages and the demographic deficit that are in danger of ultimately overwhelming Europe; and one can see that to some extent in the differing responses of Germany and Britain to the crisis. The fact that Germany is considerably below its replacement birth rate and the UK is not has had a marked influence on the debate beyond the differing social and cultural attitudes to immigration prevalent in these countries. I am actually encouraged by the German reaction as I think it sends a positive message about the demographic future in Europe.\par \par \uc2 Clearly, the bigger geopolitical issues of foreign policy, war and migration that underlie the current crisis are beyond the direct competence or remit of business to address, whatever views business leaders may have on them. However, business leaders should continue to promote actively the ideas of free movement of goods, capital and services, which will lead to the economic growth and the job creation that will keep the migrants at home and make them tourists rather than migrants \u8212\'20\'14 as we have seen again and again happen in many countries.\par \par \uc2 Large companies must continue to work hard to create a more open world economy and spread prosperity around the globe, the only real long-term answer to this crisis.\par \par \uc2 Johannes Huth\uc2 , \uc2 KKR\uc2 ,\par \par \uc2 As Springer, \uc2 Bayer\uc2 , Eon, \uc2 Evonik\uc2  and many other large corporates in Germany have demonstrated, big business has a clear role to play in this crisis, offering employment opportunities, supporting charities and encouraging their employees to do the same. Global companies operating in an international \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  simply cannot ignore this issue and their social responsibility in this matter.\par \par \uc2 Dame \uc2 Alison Carnwath\uc2 , \uc2 Land Securities\uc2 ,\par \par \uc2 I see this challenge principally as a societal issue which demands a humanitarian and policy response. Policy needs to be joined up and clearly within Europe the issue adds to the list of numerous others requiring speedier and better Governance. Politicians are responding individually, the media is analysing the causes and consequences of migration and business will look to see how it will effect their modus operandi.\par \par \uc2 Business wants to be seen as more compassionate and will probably use language which reflects this and may adjust their philanthropic activities. Business may find opportunities to train and improve their skills \u8212\'20\'14 the construction industry is woefully short of labour. At the margin diversity may be improved. It is too early to say whether there may be fundamental changes to the cost of labour or demographics. Business\u8217\'20\'19s approach should be measured in my view and as a voice should use its influence to urge the \uc2 UK government\uc2  to provide a consistent response \u8212\'20\'14 tricky with Cameron\u8217\'20\'19s attempts at renegotiations at the moment \u8212\'20\'14 and a compassionate one.\par \par \uc2 James Bardrick, \uc2 Citigroup\par \par \uc2 Much has already been said on the need for human and corporate compassion and to identify where skills shortages may match the desire of migrants who have been driven out of their home communities to work and be allowed a safe and better life for themselves and their families. We should all try to think creatively, as Sir Win has already demonstrated, how our organisations and our people might help with jobs or other support in the communities that we operate from in the UK.\par \par \uc2 Citi is a global company with businesses and customers in over 100 countries, many of them in developing and growing parts of the world. Within some of those countries and across local borders unfair and worse regimes and conditions exist and, here, we and \u8220\'20\'1Cbig business\u8221\'20\'1D can responsibly try to play a role.\par \par \uc2 We should continue encouraging, supporting and enabling economic progress, investment and job creation using our capabilities and influence with clients and, where possible and appropriate, governments. We should seek to promote, as Tidjane has already said, the principles of free, fair and transparent trade and business, so as to improve the safety, sustainability and prosperity of those economies so that people can choose to stay at or closer to home.\par \par \uc2 Simon Walker, \uc2 Institute of Directors\par \par \uc2 Business leaders, along with the rest of the British people, have been deeply moved by the current refugee crisis, so many of our members will welcome the government\u8217\'20\'19s move for straightforward humanitarian reasons.\par \par \uc2 We also recognise that there is a positive business and economic rationale for bringing in refugees. Historically, victims of conflict \u8212\'20\'14 from the Huguenots to the Jews fleeing Nazi brutality, and refugees after the crushing of the 1956 Hungarian revolution \u8212\'20\'14 have ultimately made a valuable contribution to British society. If one is an optimist about people, then welcoming into any community people willing to integrate and work hard to rebuild their lives will end up as an economic positive. In a generation Britain may look back on refugees from Syria \u8212\'20\'14 as it does now on the Ugandan Asians expelled by Idi Amin \u8212\'20\'14 and applaud the dynamism and determination which they ended up adding to our society. That is not the prime reason for a humanitarian gesture, but it may well amount to an additional benefit.\par \par \uc2 There is undoubtedly a skills shortage \u8212\'20\'14 and, in some fields, there\u8217\'20\'19s also a motivation shortage. The opportunity to recruit people, many in dire circumstances, could give firms loyal and able employees of the calibre of those who entered Britain after the Hungarian uprising. Supporting the charities and organisations helping refugees will show big business \u8220\'20\'1Cdoing its bit\u8221\'20\'1D, and could help companies enthuse their existing workforce.\par \par \uc2 The Yugoslav refugees settled in Denmark in the 1990s, like the Cubans evacuated to Florida after Castro took power, brought low-skilled but highly productive employees into their economies.\par \par \uc2 Steve Jobs, we might also remember, was the son of a Syrian immigrant.\par \par \uc2 Jean-Pierre Mustier, Tikehau\par \par \uc2 While I fully endorse all the comments which have been made about tactical and strategic actions big business could take to help deal with the migrant crisis, a lot of the focus has been put on what we could do at home, here in Europe. It will be important as well, once the wars in these countries come to an end, that big business, supported by European governments, export credit agencies, the EIB or the \uc2 World Bank\uc2 , can help redevelop the local economies of these countries by making investment and relaunch their activities there. Only by acting locally we should be able to deal with the source of the problem.\par \par \uc2 Robert Swannell\uc2 , \uc2 Marks and Spencer\uc2 ,\par \par \uc2 There are many wonderful organisations who are properly equipped and experienced to support the truly appalling refugee and migration issues and understand the issues much better than most businesses ever could on their own.\par \par \uc2 Companies should have authentic core values and purposes and stay true to them. It is sustained work that truly makes a difference. If helping refugees and migrants (or great organisations that support them) is part of that core purpose, either in the UK or in other parts of the world, then of course those businesses should continue to help and no doubt redouble their efforts.\par \par \uc2 But there are so many good causes and so many areas of deprivation and they are not all on television. There is a danger with any issue that captures the public attention that, like young children on a football pitch, everyone single-mindedly scampers after the ball and fails to see what is going on around them.\par \par \uc2 Last year, Ebola was on our television screens daily. People learned where Liberia, Guinea and Sierra Leone were on the map. People gave generously. But Ebola was only an additional grim burden in Liberia, a country trying hard to build itself after years of conflict.\par \par \uc2 Despite great efforts, 50 per cent of the child population in Liberia is malnourished, 10,000 children die from chronic malnutrition each year and 80 per cent of families live below the poverty line. \uc2 Unicef\uc2  is working with the Liberian government to try to eradicate child malnutrition in Liberia.\par \par \uc2 How many people and businesses are still trying to help with these and other issues in Liberia now that the Ebola panic has disappeared from our screens? How many continue to care?\par \par \uc2 I would argue for sustained support over many years in any area where business is truly connected and can make a difference, not occasional bursts of energy and attention.\par \par \uc2 Helena Morrissey\uc2 , Newton/The Investment Association\par \par \uc2 All the suggestions are excellent and I am sure that individual businesses can come up with plenty of innovative ways of helping in this crisis. One point has not been raised yet: surely we also need to ask why this refugee crisis started in the first place. Is it a coincidence that most of the refugees are travelling from {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.ft.com/topics/places/Syria"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Syria }}}\uc2 , {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.ft.com/topics/places/Libya"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Libya }}}\uc2  and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.ft.com/world/asiapacific/afghanistan"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Afghanistan }}}\uc2 ? It is important that we react effectively to crises and events. But it is also important to consider why they happen.\par \par \uc2 While I realise there is a range of views about how far businesses should get involved, as people (and leaders) we are all party to these events. We are co-creators by our actions and our silence. The reality is that a tendency to resort to violence and aggressive sanctions, rather than diplomacy, will inevitably lead to suffering in the countries involved and have significant knock-on effects here at home. Rather than always trying to cope with the consequences of war, perhaps we should put our collective attention on war itself and think more deeply before we resort to violence and consider instead more enlightened ways of sorting out our differences. Otherwise, as Robert Louis Stephenson said: \u8220\'20\'1CSooner or later, everyone sits down to a banquet of consequences.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Katherine Garrett-Cox\uc2 , Alliance Trust\par \par \uc2 The need for compassion in dealing with mass migration and displacement is vital. Co-ordination across Europe is critical and the more co-ordinated our governments can be, the better the chance we have of finding a solution to help deal with the truly tragic scenes we have seen unfolding at borders across Europe.\par \par \uc2 Business, too, has a role to play. Business can work to fulfil its moral obligation to encourage greater sustainability across many of the world\u8217\'20\'19s economies. By actively promoting a sense of social responsibility and in giving back to society, business can help to support a stable capital market and provide opportunities to the many, not just the few. This is a process that will take time to deliver, but the crisis we are seeing today highlights how important it is for us all to start working together now to prevent matters deteriorating further.\par \par \uc2 Sir Philip Hampton, GSK\par \par \uc2 To me there are two main themes. The first is that Europe has to deal with the fact that large numbers of displaced people have arrived in a desperate state who must be helped. I don\u8217\'20\'19t think the role of business is fundamentally different from that of governments or citizens, through moral or financial support, or both.\par \par \uc2 The second is the much harder question of policy in relation to continuing mass migration, for economic or distress reasons. We may all have the aspiration that peace and prosperity in troubled places will help, but it probably won\u8217\'20\'19t help much in the near term. I don\u8217\'20\'19t know anyone who has a clear, practical solution to the challenge of continuing mass migration into Europe, but it seems to me a job for politicians and not big business, to answer your question directly.\par \par \uc2 At the moment the humanitarian drivers dominate, rightly. There will be tougher issues to address.\par \par \uc2 Lord (Mervyn) Davies, Corsair\par \par \uc2 Thanks to communication improvements we are able to watch live pictures of crises as they unfold, more so than ever before.\par \par \uc2 War, climate change and unpleasant regimes result in extraordinary numbers of innocent people being displaced. They search for food, protection for their children and a normal life. We are so lucky.\par \par \uc2 The images we are witnessing across Europe are disturbing and as senior business people we cannot just sit there and say it is somebody else\u8217\'20\'19s problem. However, the challenge is how do we contribute or help beyond giving donations to the normal charities which, in turn, are stretched?\par \par \uc2 We all sometimes worry that things happen during our lifetime and then we look back with hindsight and sadness that we didn\u8217\'20\'19t speak up or do more.\par \par \uc2 We have had so much scientific, technological and other advancements during the last 50 years. Millions of people have been taken out of poverty and, yet, still today the rich/poor divide and the lack of schooling, water and food are serious challenges. There needs to be a new global architecture for dealing with these problems. Business has to contribute more and has to pressurise all governments that it is a time for leadership, which demands innovation and courage.\par \par \uc2 European leaders need to realise that this migrant issue will only increase in scale \u8212\'20\'14 it will not go away and we may be just at the beginning. The creation of more adequately funded camps, job creation and a master plan are needed now. This is a crisis of extraordinary magnitude and there is a danger that every government will put it in the \u8220\'20\'1Ctoo difficult to resolve\u8221\'20\'1D basket. That would be a failure of leadership at a time when these people need their and our help.\par \par \uc2 The solution is for a master group of committed politicians, charity experts and business leaders to come up with a detailed plan for execution with adequate resources and with the power to implement. This is a problem that goes beyond country boundaries. The world should help the world.\par \par \uc2 Michael Tory, Ondra\par \par \uc2 Business, in my view, has three roles that can make a real difference: helping lead public opinion in favour of the long-term societal benefits of taking in refugees (ie, beyond the pure humanitarian motive); where possible, making available employment opportunities once they have settled; and finally philanthropic, as has been noted elsewhere.\par \par \uc2 The experience of the 50,000 Vietnamese who came in the 1970s to Canada \u8212\'20\'14 my home country, which has been entirely populated by the descendants of immigrants and refugees \u8212\'20\'14 illustrates the exceptional value and dynamism brought by energetic, aspirational people seeking to build safer and better new lives for their families, often at great personal sacrifice compared to what they left behind.\par \par \uc2 Guy Hands, Terra Firma\par \par \uc2 The debate on the issue of refugees coming to the UK has naturally focused on humanitarian issues. This is understandable given the media coverage surrounding the hardship of many of these people. However, businesspeople need to make clear that accepting refugees and other migrants that have in-demand skills would be of huge economic benefit to the UK.\par \par \uc2 While accepting refugees is seen by many as an act of charity, what seems to be lost in this debate is that the UK has a substantial skill shortage in many areas and a large number of these people would be able to address many of the country\u8217\'20\'19s skill gaps. Waves of skilled migrants have, over the centuries, provided skills, diversity and economic stimulus which has been hugely beneficial to many countries; indeed, the long-term success of many countries has largely been measured by their ability to welcome and integrate skilled people from other cultures.\par \par \uc2 The UK should embrace the opportunity to allow skilled refugees and migrants to work hard and build a new life for themselves and their families, rather than seeing this as an act of charity.\par \par \uc2 Samir Desai\uc2 , Funding Circle\par \par \uc2 The migrant crisis is harrowing and Britain should clearly do its part to help those in need. But this also highlights how our immigration policies have long been at odds with the government\u8217\'20\'19s desire to build the UK into a digital hub. The FT recently reported that four out of 10 Silicon Valley companies were started by immigrants, yet in the UK visa applications are almost impossible to attain for skilled technology engineers.\par \par \uc2 This slowed to a crawl in the run-up to the election and has not recovered. Immigration is clearly a difficult issue and is affecting communities around the UK; however, in an increasingly competitive global marketplace we have to allow our fast-growing companies to be able to bring on board the best talent if we want to succeed. Some bolder thought in this area is needed.\par \par \uc2 Nigel Wilson\uc2 , \uc2 Legal & General\uc2 ,\par \par \uc2 Excellent note, Mervyn.\par \par \uc2 Globally we have to deal with intra-country migration and inter-country migration. China and India have major issues with the former and the west with the latter.\par \par \uc2 The irony of course is that we need mass migration to keep the world economy growing \u8212\'20\'14 and while the \uc2 UK government\uc2  has said they want only tens of thousands of immigrants per year, we are having hundreds of thousands a year. This has contributed significantly to economic growth in the UK and, indeed, in the US. This has been the case since the first machine age. As we enter the second machine age it is equally true.\par \par \uc2 Germany, Italy and Spain will have a working population by 2030 some 9m less than today. And with an ever-increasing retired population they have to increase the age of retirement and the number of immigrants \u8212\'20\'14 both politically and socially difficult to implement.\par \par \uc2 Because we are all empathetic or sympathetic to the current plight of immigrants we may have a more rational debate about the long-term benefits of immigration.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b