ves. Environmentalists largely applaud the efforts but have reservations about the actual impact.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Adidas, the world's No. 2 sporting goods company behind \uc2 Nike Inc\uc2 ., said the project, to be announced Thursday and funded by the \uc2 European Union\uc2 , would assemble experts from a variety of industries to develop a \u8220\'20\'1Csuper-material" that can be used for performance sports gear, and later be broken down and remolded repeatedly.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CIn a world of limited resources, recyclable materials is something we as an industry need to be leading in," said Gerd Manz, technology and innovation vice president at Adidas and head of the new project.\par \par \uc2 Critics have long pointed out the environmental damage caused by a sharp rise in garment consumption world-wide. Alongside fast fashion retailers, the sportswear industry is responding to consumer patterns by manufacturing and selling an increasing amount of sportswear and shoes. In this way the industry is contributing to pollution, said Yixiuo Wu, a project leader at \uc2 Greenpeace\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Sport Infinity, as Adidas's new project is called, is one of several steps Adidas has taken recently to boost its ethical credentials.\par \par \uc2 The German sportswear giant on Tuesday said it would join \uc2 Microsoft Corp\uc2 ., \uc2 Sony Corp\uc2 . and several other companies in a United Nations initiative to become a \u8220\'20\'1Cleading example" in tackling climate change, by agreeing to measure its climate footprint and reduce emissions where possible. In April, Adidas announced a partnership with awareness-raising network Parley for the Oceans, through which it aims to make sportswear out of recycled ocean waste.\par \par \uc2 The first concept shoe created through this cooperation was however not significantly different from Adidas's current non-green shoe collection. The yarn used for the shoe upper was indeed made of fibers from waste plastic and fishing nets, but the sole was still made out of newly manufactured plastic. Adidas said at the time that the shoe was a concept shoe only, and that it would be worked on and turned into a consumer product in coming months.\par \par \uc2 Millennials are particularly attuned to whether businesses share their beliefs, said \uc2 Matt Powell\uc2 , a sports industry analyst at NPD Group. \u8220\'20\'1CSustainability is a very important value to this cohort," he said.\par \par \uc2 Adidas executive board member Glenn Bennett said environmentalism can \u8220\'20\'1Ccontribute to lasting economic success."\par \par \uc2 More retailers are trying to burnish their environmental-friendly image by telling consumers how green they are.\par \par \uc2 Levi Strauss & Co\uc2  recently said it would expand its garment collection all over the U.S. to boost its recycling program.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Wu, the \uc2 Greenpeace\uc2  project leader, said he supports extended use and recycling of materials, but that \uc2 Greenpeace\uc2  is concerned about issues such as contamination of recyclable materials.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CThe companies themselves need to be more transparent," he said.\par \par \uc2 Nike Inc\uc2 . has since the 1990s collected used athletic shoes and recycled them into performance gear and incorporated them into sports surfaces such as soccer courts. \uc2 Greenpeace\uc2 , however, in its latest assessment identified \uc2 Nike\uc2  as a \u8220\'20\'1CGreen washer"\u8212\'20\'14a company that cynically uses green marketing to appear more environmental than it is. \uc2 Greenpeace\uc2  said \u8220\'20\'1Cthe ambition level and the transparency \uc2 Nike\uc2  demonstrated to consumers is questionable."\par \par \uc2 A Nike spokesman said the company is committed to a goal of zero discharge of hazardous chemicals by 2020 and has made \u8220\'20\'1Cmeaningful progress" toward that goal, including establishing several programs, working to develop no-water textile machines, and phasing out the use of a specifically harmful chemical.\par \par \uc2 Sweden's \uc2 Hennes & Mauritz AB\uc2 , the world's second-biggest fashion retailer, announced earlier this month it would offer an annual \u8364\'20\'AC1 million ($1.12 million) prize for new techniques to recycle clothes. Since 2013, the company has collected used garments in-store and it is now retailing collections made partly out of recycled materials.\par \par \uc2 Last year, the company collected almost 7,700 tons of used clothing at its stores\u8212\'20\'14the equivalent of about 40 million T-shirts. Estimates suggest the company sold about 550 million new garments in 2011. Since then, \uc2 H&M\uc2 's sales have risen almost 40%.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CThere is really only one rule in fashion, and that is to recycle your clothes," an \uc2 H&M\uc2  spokeswoman said.\par \par \uc2 However, \uc2 H&M\uc2  remains a fast fashion retailer and largely benefits from increased consumption.\par \par \uc2 In Mr. Wu's opinion, future fashion consumption needs to be about sharing and secondhand use of clothes, \u8220\'20\'1Cinstead of constantly buying new items."\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CIt is not only about what we consume but also how much," he said.\par \par \uc2 Earlier this year, \uc2 H&M\uc2  also joined forced with \uc2 Puma SE\uc2 -owner \uc2 Kering SA\uc2  to support textile-recycling firm Worn Again in developing a technology for separating and extracting fibers in mixed-material clothes.\par \par \uc2 Paula Alexander Becker, a management professor at \uc2 Seton Hall University\uc2  and author of the book \u8220\'20\'1C\b \highlight22\uc2 Corporate Social Responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 " said these initiatives are \u8220\'20\'1Cof course" tied to marketing campaigns, targeting customers that care about the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 This should however not undermine the legitimacy of these efforts, she said, adding that the industry is moving toward \u8220\'20\'1Cmanaging for the triple bottom line: people, planet, profits."\par \par \uc2 In its new Sport Infinity project, Adidas said it not only hopes to create a material that can be recycled as many times as possible, but also one that doesn't require the use of strong chemicals and adhesives.\par \par \uc2 In the course of the three-year program, it plans to cooperate with experts from a variety of industries, including German chemicals giant \uc2 BASF SE\uc2 , Austrian design and brand consultancy firm Kiska GmbH, several international universities and textile connoisseurs.\par \par \uc2 Adidas said it hopes to use the new material in anything from soccer cleats to performance sportswear and soccer balls, eventually offering customers the chance to hand in their old products and recycle them into custom-made new ones.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CUltimately, wouldn't it be nice to not consider used products waste anymore?" said Mr. Manz. \u8220\'20\'1CWe believe in a second life for our products. This is the future, after all."\par \par \uc2 Write to Ellen Emmerentze Jervell at {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "mailto:ellen.jervell@wsj.com"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 ellen.jervell@wsj.com}}}\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\c