pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Mr Harper hit on the idea of a service that would provide lawyers on a temporary basis for in-house corporate legal departments and later for other law firms. Originally set up within the firm of \uc2 Berwin Leighton Paisner\uc2 , LOD has now been spun off as a separate entity.\par \par \uc2 Ms Irani\u8217\'20\'19s iProbono project is an online platform connecting lawyers prepared to offer free services to civil society organisations. iProbono has teams in London and New Delhi, although it operates in 31 countries. The judges were particularly impressed with the legal support iProbono had been able to offer on child protection matters in India.\par \par \uc2 The judges felt both these contenders were tapping into the same phenomenon: lawyers increasingly want to work in different ways, whether flexibly or by offering pro-bono services.\par \par \uc2 As the argument continued on which of these two should win the award, some of the judges began to ask: can\u8217\'20\'19t they both win? Why do we need to separate such worthy candidates? The rest of us could see no reason why not. So, in the 10th anniversary year of FT Innovative Lawyers, Mr Harper and Ms Irani are joint winners.\par \par \uc2 Winners\par \par \uc2 Simon Harper\uc2 , LOD (Lawyers on Demand)\par \par \uc2 LOD (Lawyers On Demand) sent shockwaves through the legal industry when it was launched in 2007 as an original alternative legal services provider. \uc2 Simon Harper\uc2 , the man behind this idea, led the project to make it a successful and now independently managed business after it was spun off from \uc2 Berwin Leighton Paisner\uc2  as a separate entity.\par \par \uc2 Mr Harper developed the idea for LOD after observing contradictory pressures in the legal industry that were exacerbated by the global financial crisis: he recognised that while buyers of legal services needed to make their budgets stretch further, more lawyers were looking for flexibility and autonomy. Since being established, LOD has grown 700 per cent and now has a turnover of more than \u163\'00\'A312m and a team of more than 200 lawyers.\par \par \uc2 Mr Harper\u8217\'20\'19s innovation has been copied by several big law firms in the UK. More than a third of the top 20 firms now have similar offerings.\par \par \uc2 But Mr Harper continues to innovate. He has developed an evolution of the LOD model that sends in teams of lawyers who use technology and data analytics to support in-house legal departments. This new avenue accounted for more than half of the 40 per cent growth LOD posted last year.\par \par \uc2 Shireen Irani, iProbono\par \par \uc2 Shireen Irani, Fieldfisher\u8217\'20\'19s director of corporate responsibility, founded iProbono to provide an online platform for civil society organisations to engage with lawyers and students willing to provide legal assistance.\par \par \uc2 It was while she was reading for an LLM that Ms Irani recognised the desire of fellow students to contribute to society. But she also noted the absence of an easy and flexible way to do so. When she joined Fieldfisher in 2007, she decided to harness this potential and pitched her ideas to the firm, which lent its support to the organisation, which is an independent charity.\par \par \uc2 The success of iProbono revolves around a core team in London and New Delhi, led by Ms Irani. An easy-to-access networking platform caters for the limited resources of civil society organisations and the desire of lawyers to provide assistance in a flexible manner. It has a global reach, in 31 countries, with 1,200 organisations and 50,000 volunteers on its network who have varying levels of experience, skills and availability. The platform has a registration process, which is used to match projects to volunteers\u8217\'20\'19 interests.\par \par \uc2 The organisation has provided legal support on a wide variety of issues, from child welfare, slavery, education and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  to the rights of girls on the Indian subcontinent.\par \par \uc2 Other individuals\par \par \uc2 Camille Abousleiman, Dechert\par \par \uc2 Camille Abousleiman has been a driving force behind legal work in capital markets in the Middle East. In the early 1990s, while working in Latin America when the Mexican peso crisis struck, he sensed an opportunity for the development of capital markets in the Middle East, adapting new structures long before the investment banks.\par \par \uc2 His market firsts include the then largest international placement offering, the first equity listing of a Middle Eastern company on the \uc2 London Stock Exchange\uc2 , the first eurobond issued by a private company and a bank in the region and the first and second listings on \uc2 Nasdaq\uc2  Dubai.\par \par \uc2 Mr Abousleiman has guided transactions for sovereigns and companies through regime change, constitutional crises and assassinations. His work has helped to preserve investors\u8217\'20\'19 access to capital markets under extraordinary circumstances \u8212\'20\'14 Egypt and Tunisia returned this year following the Arab Spring and subsequent upheavals.\par \par \uc2 Simon Baggs\uc2 , Wiggin\par \par \uc2 As the head of Wiggin\u8217\'20\'19s intellectual property and rights protection team, and managing director of Incopro, \uc2 Simon Baggs\uc2  has been at the forefront of the fight against the online infringement of businesses\u8217\'20\'19 intellectual property.\par \par \uc2 Mr Baggs founded Incopro in 2012 after recognising that businesses were inadequately protected from growing global challenges in the form of counterfeiting and piracy.\par \par \uc2 But he realised that legal skills alone were not enough. Incopro therefore also offers technology and intelligence services that allow clients to counter threats.\par \par \uc2 In 2013, Mr Baggs achieved a groundbreaking success for the film industry. Under his guidance the sector won the first UK site-blocking order, which requires internet service providers (ISPs) to block subscribers from accessing websites that infringe businesses\u8217\'20\'19 copyright.\par \par \uc2 In October 2014, he won another landmark victory for client Richemont. His advice acted as the catalyst for the luxury goods group to secure a court order blocking websites that infringe trademarks by selling counterfeit goods online.\par \par \uc2 And this March, a High Court order required the UK\u8217\'20\'19s five leading ISPs to ensure that they blocked access to specific websites that allowed users to download films illegally.\par \par \uc2 Having identified a gap in the market for legal protection of intellectual property, Mr Baggs has significantly contributed to filling it, not just with Incopro but also with some important legal precedents.\par \par \uc2 Michael Hatchard\uc2 , \uc2 Skadden, Arps, Slate, Meagher & Flom\par \par \uc2 Michael Hatchard\uc2  has played an integral part in the rise of \uc2 Skadden, Arps, Slate, Meagher & Flom\uc2  in the City.\par \par \uc2 He has been at the forefront of significant changes in mergers and acquisition law over an extensive career. He developed the use of demergers in hostile bids and created a new structure for hostile acquisition in the 1980s. More recently, he led the team on \uc2 Pfizer\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s bid for rival drugs group \uc2 AstraZeneca\uc2  and created the structure for more binding commitments and post-offer undertakings.\par \par \uc2 Invited to comment on the liability structures underwriting UK privatisations, he was appointed adviser to the government broker, where he created a structure that forms the basis for all \uc2 UK government\uc2  privatisations.\par \par \uc2 Mr Hatchard\u8217\'20\'19s innovations also extend to new products. He was instrumental in developing a new topping insurance product for client \uc2 Aon\uc2 , following changes to the Takeover Code that removed break-fee protection for failed bids.\par \par \uc2 David Kerr\uc2 , \uc2 Bird & Bird\par \par \uc2 David Kerr\uc2  has built his career on innovation in law firm leadership. He has driven \uc2 Bird & Bird\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s strategy of continuously developing technology-focused expertise. Under his leadership the firm has grown from a small, specialist London-based outfit into a network of lawyers in 28 offices and 18 countries.\par \par \uc2 Mr Kerr has also been determined not to abandon the firm\u8217\'20\'19s heritage as one focused on intellectual property and technology. Instead, the firm\u8217\'20\'19s growth has been strictly confined to these areas.\par \par \uc2 This has also been a key part of Mr Kerr\u8217\'20\'19s international growth strategy: local market expertise combined with the international \uc2 Bird & Bird\uc2  brand \u8212\'20\'14 a formula used in the opening of the Sydney office in November 2014, when \uc2 Bird & Bird\uc2  merged with leading local technology and communications firm Truman Hoyle.\par \par \uc2 Mr Kerr has also overseen operational innovation, developing the Virtual General Counsel service to help resource companies with no internal lawyers; establishing Baseline, a joint venture with ASE Consulting to offer clients a multidisciplinary service; and launching a matter planning and profitability initiative to provide clients with more flexible and transparent pricing proposals.\par \par \uc2 Sir Nigel Knowles, \uc2 DLA Piper\par \par \uc2 In just 19 years Sir Nigel Knowles has taken a Yorkshire firm that had its roots in a Sheffield debt-collecting practice and turned it into one of the largest firms in the world in revenue terms.\par \par \uc2 As head of Dibb Lupton Broomhead he first merged with Manchester firm Alsop Wikinson, but by 2006 his firm had a base in the City of London and a tie-up with US firms Piper Rudnick and Gray Cary Ware & Freidenrich.\par \par \uc2 By 2009 his firm\u8217\'20\'19s rapid expansion and work for the Prince\u8217\'20\'19s Trust had won him a knighthood.\par \par \uc2 It was not all smooth going. As an early adopter of both a transatlantic link and the Swiss verein structure, under which affiliates remain separate entities, the firm that had become \uc2 DLA Piper\uc2  came under criticism.\par \par \uc2 But Sir Nigel\u8217\'20\'19s commitment to making the structure work meant that other top firms have followed suit and the structure is now considered commonplace in the profession as the way to expand internationally.\par \par \uc2 Sir Nigel\u8217\'20\'19s appetite for game-changing was further shown when he was one of the first senior lawyers to take advantage of the Legal Services Act, liberalising parts of the profession, to invest in the holding company of Riverview Law, which offers a different way of delivering legal advice.\par \par \uc2 Yulia Kyrpa, AEQUO\par \par \uc2 Yulia Kyrpa is an outstanding specialist in the field of banking and finance law, at a time of immense challenges. Ms Kyrpa has tackled the difficulties surrounding the 2014 Ukraine revolution with a commitment to reform.\par \par \uc2 Ms Kyrpa assisted the \uc2 European Bank for Reconstruction and Development\uc2  on the launch and implementation of state insurance of household deposits and bank reform, bringing Ukraine\u8217\'20\'19s legislation into line with best international practice.\par \par \uc2 Ms Kyrpa\u8217\'20\'19s full-scale legal assistance for NCH Capital, a leading US private equity fund, was essential in achieving the acquisition of the insolvent Astra Bank from the state.\par \par \uc2 The deal brought new US money into the country, demonstrating to foreign investors that, despite the crisis, it was possible to enter into successful and credible transactions.\par \par \uc2 When President Yanukovych fled Ukraine, Ms Kyrpa and her team faced the challenge of finding grounds in the constitution to justify the appointment and scope of the temporary Ukrainian government.\par \par \uc2 And by finding innovative legal solutions Ms Kyrpa and her team ensured that Ukraine could agree borrowing from the \uc2 EU\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 P\u225\'00\'E1draig \u211\'00\'D3 R\u237\'00\'EDord\u225\'00\'E1in\uc2 , Arthur Cox\par \par \uc2 P\u225\'00\'E1draig \u211\'00\'D3 R\u237\'00\'EDord\u225\'00\'E1in\uc2  is a well-recognised name among leading corporate lawyers and has played a key role in the Irish banking crisis as part of the Arthur Cox team.\par \par \uc2 He trained in a Wall Street firm before joining Arthur Cox, where in 2003 he was elected managing partner at just 37 years old. He developed a new vision for the firm that would turn its focus from being a domestic Irish practice to one that could operate on an international stage.\par \par \uc2 Mr \u211\'00\'D3 R\u237\'00\'EDord\u225\'00\'E1in, as lead external adviser to the Irish state, was at the centre of the Irish banking crisis, advising on the implementation of agreed bank guarantees. The nature of the crisis meant that every bank and building society was a risk to the state.\par \par \uc2 Against this difficult backdrop, but with no existing legal structures in place, Mr \u211\'00\'D3 R\u237\'00\'EDord\u225\'00\'E1in\u8217\'20\'19s team designed a legal framework that would preserve the legal integrity of the banks but enable the government to take the action it deemed necessary.\par \par \uc2 With that background it is perhaps not surprising that Mr \u211\'00\'D3 R\u237\'00\'EDord\u225\'00\'E1in is a member of the \uc2 European Commission\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s Insolvency Law Expert Group, the advisory body to the Commission on the development of an \uc2 EU\uc2  cross-border regulatory crisis management regime.\par \par \uc2 Penelope Warne, CMS\par \par \uc2 Penelope Warne joined CMS as an oil and gas specialist in 1993 to set up the firm\u8217\'20\'19s Aberdeen office. Twenty years later, she has built this specialism in her role as senior partner and head of energy.\par \par \uc2 She has applied herself to expanding the firm.\par \par \uc2 In 2014, swiftly after becoming senior partner at CMS, Ms Warne drove the merger with Dundas & Wilson that allowed the firm to become Scotland\u8217\'20\'19s market leader.\par \par \uc2 One year on, revenue has grown 30 per cent and profits are up 15 per cent \u8212\'20\'14 making 2014-15 a record year for CMS.\par \par \uc2 Ms Warne has also led the firm\u8217\'20\'19s international expansion, with offices being established in Brazil, Mexico, the Middle East and Asia.\par \par \uc2 She has also worked hard outside her field. She was instrumental in helping War Child, the firm\u8217\'20\'19s charity partner, to raise \u163\'00\'A3150,000 in five months. And she is passionate about helping female lawyers to break through the glass ceiling.\par \par \uc2 Her commitment to creating a leading energy practice, influencing the global energy debate and actively championing diversity and \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  combine to form a picture of a lawyer who can innovate in not just one but a number of areas.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CO\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 brwnl : \uc2 Berwin Leighton Paisner LLP\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\wi