re links between the personal lives of chief executives and the professional results at the companies they run.\par \par \uc2 Those who golf more than 22 times a year have been linked with lower corporate performance, while those who run marathons have better results. Physical traits ranging from the width of a CEO's face to the depth of his voice have been correlated with better performance and higher pay.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Now, researchers have found a link between the gender of a male chief executive's children and how well his company behaves toward society.\par \par \uc2 The most recent issue of \uc2 Harvard Business Review\uc2  spotlighted new research showing that CEOs who have daughters get roughly 12 percent higher ratings for being socially responsible than those who have sons. And the median firm with a CEO who has a daughter spends an extra 13.4 percent of the company's net income on \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  programs, the study found.\par \par \uc2 "Having a daughter seems to make the top executives of publicly traded companies in the U.S. a bit softer, specifically in context of social responsibility," co-author Henrik Cronqvist, a professor at the University of Miami's business school, said in an interview. "They seem to care more about others than just shareholders. Having a daughter seems to push the executives to care more about other stakeholders."\par \par \uc2 Cronqvist and his co-author, China Europe International Business School professor Frank Yu, used databases and Internet searches to compile their own list of S&P 500 chiefs who have children, then looked at \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  data from analytics firm KLD for the years 1992 to 2012. KLD rates firms on six categories - community, diversity, employee relations, \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , human rights and product - and analyzes companies on their strengths and weaknesses in such areas.\par \par \uc2 The pair found 379 CEOs for which they had both \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  scores and information on their children's gender. They found that companies run by male executives with female children rated higher for diversity, employee relations and eco-friendliness. Of those, according to Cronqvist, the category where the impact was the strongest is diversity.\par \par \uc2 What's the reason for the link? In the paper, the researchers pulled from past studies showing that women tend to attach more weight to the well-being of others. In addition, they drew on the idea that while parents influence their children, the opposite is also true: Children have an impact on their parents' thinking and beliefs.\par \par \uc2 An effect known as the "female socialization hypothesis" has been shown to prompt fathers to adopt some of their daughters' values and thinking.\par \par \uc2 For instance, past research has shown that congressmen who have daughters are likely to vote more liberally, particularly on reproductive rights issues. Other studies have found that the daughter effect exists among parents who become more politically liberal and that male federal judges in the United States who have a daughter are pushed to the left on gender-related cases.\par \par \uc2 Cronqvist pointed to former chief justice William Rehnquist, who was believed to have been influenced by his daughters in his opinion that state governments must abide by the Family and Medical Leave Act. British Prime Minister David Cameron mentioned his daughters when he announced his intent to force companies to publish their gender pay gap. "I want them to look back at the gender pay gap in the same way we look back at women not voting and not working - as something outdated and wrong that we overcame, together," he wrote in the Times in July.\par \par \uc2 The average age of chief executives in Cronqvist's study was 57, so many of their daughters are grown. As a result, their initial experiences in the workplace, their choice of college major or their professional aspirations may have begun to influence their fathers' thinking. Another study from 2011, for instance, found that after CEOs of Danish firms had a daughter, female employees' wages rose relative to their male peers, narrowing the wage gap.\par \par \uc2 It's unclear how having children vs. not having children, rather than whether the children were male or female, might affect an executive's behavior. Because fewer than 5 percent of the CEOs had no children, Cronqvist excluded them from his study.\par \par \uc2 Female CEOs also had a small sample in the study. Fewer than 4 percent of the executives studied were women - so while those women did have much stronger \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  ratings than their male peers, it was such a small group that the findings were not reliable.\par \par \uc2 However, Cronqvist did use those figures to make an interesting comparison. Even male chief executives with a daughter tend to have only about one-third the social responsibility rating of CEOs who are women. Or as Cronqvist put it: "Having the daughter seems to make male CEOs one-third more female, with respect to the decisions being made."\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx936