tright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Copyright 2015, The Washington Post Co.  All Rights Reserved.   \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Business school professors have a knack for finding some pretty\u160\'00\'A0bizarre\u160\'00\'A0links between the personal lives\u160\'00\'A0of CEOs and\u160\'00\'A0the professional results at the\u160\'00\'A0companies they run.\par \par \uc2 Those who golf more than 22 times a year are linked with lower corporate performance, while those who run marathons have better results. Physical traits\u160\'00\'A0ranging from the width\u160\'00\'A0of a CEO's face\u160\'00\'A0to the depth of his voice have been correlated with better performance and higher pay.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Now,\u160\'00\'A0researchers are finding a\u160\'00\'A0link between the gender of a male CEO's children and how well his\u160\'00\'A0company behaves toward\u160\'00\'A0society.\par \par \uc2 The most recent issue of\u160\'00\'A0\uc2 Harvard Business Review\uc2  spotlighted\u160\'00\'A0new research\u160\'00\'A0showing\u160\'00\'A0that CEOs who have\u160\'00\'A0daughters get\u160\'00\'A0roughly\u160\'00\'A012 percent higher\u160\'00\'A0ratings for being socially responsible than those\u160\'00\'A0who have sons. And\u160\'00\'A0the median firm with a CEO who has a daughter spends an extra 13.4\u160\'00\'A0percent\u160\'00\'A0of the firm's net income on \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  programs, the\u160\'00\'A0study\u160\'00\'A0found.\par \par \uc2 "H aving a daughter seems to make the top executives of publicly traded companies in the U.S. a bit softer, specifically in context of social responsibility," said co-author Henrik Cronqvist, a professor at University of Miami's business school, in an interview. "They seem to care more about others than just shareholders. H aving a daughter seems to push the executives to care more about other stakeholders."\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 Cronqvist and his co-author,\u160\'00\'A0China Europe International Business School professor Frank Yu, used databases and Internet searches to come up with their own list\u160\'00\'A0of\u160\'00\'A0S&P 500 CEOs who have children, then looked at \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  data from analytics firm KLD for the years 1992 to 2012. KLD rates firms on six categories\u8212\'20\'14community, diversity, employee relations, \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , human rights and product\u8212\'20\'14and analyzes\u160\'00\'A0companies on\u160\'00\'A0their strengths and weaknesses in such areas.\par \par \uc2 The pair\u160\'00\'A0found\u160\'00\'A0379 CEOs for which they had both \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 \u160\'00\'A0scores and information on their\u160\'00\'A0children's gender. They found that\u160\'00\'A0companies run by male executives with female children rated higher for\u160\'00\'A0diversity, employee relations and eco-friendliness. Of those, according to Cronqvist, the category where the impact was the strongest is diversity.\par \par \uc2 What's the reason for the link?\u160\'00\'A0In the paper, the researchers pull\u160\'00\'A0from past studies\u160\'00\'A0showing that women tend\u160\'00\'A0to\u160\'00\'A0attach more weight to the well-being of others. In addition, they draw on the idea that\u160\'00\'A0while we mostly think of parents influencing their children, the opposite is also true: Children\u160\'00\'A0have an impact on their parents' thinking and beliefs.\par \par \uc2 An effect known as the "female socialization hypothesis"\u160\'00\'A0has been shown to\u160\'00\'A0prompt fathers to adopt\u160\'00\'A0some of their daughters' values and thinking.\par \par \uc2 For instance, past research shows\u160\'00\'A0that\u160\'00\'A0congressmen who have daughters are likely\u160\'00\'A0to vote more liberally, particularly on reproductive rights issues. Other studies have shown that the daughter effect exists among parents\u160\'00\'A0generally\u160\'00\'A0becoming more politically liberal, as well as that male federal judges in the United States\u160\'00\'A0who have\u160\'00\'A0a daughter are pushed to the left on gender-related cases.\par \par \uc2 Cronqvist points\u160\'00\'A0to former Chief Justice William Rehnquist,\u160\'00\'A0who was speculated to have been influenced by his daughters in deciding\u160\'00\'A0to vote in favor of state governments having to abide by the Family and Medical Leave Act.\u160\'00\'A0British Prime Minister David Cameron mentioned his daughters when he announced his intent to force companies to publish their gender pay gap.\u160\'00\'A0"I want them to look back at the gender pay gap in the same way we look back at women not voting and not working \u8212\'20\'14 as something outdated and wrong that we overcame, together," he wrote in The Times in July.\par \par \uc2 The average age of CEOs in Cronqvist's\u160\'00\'A0study was 57, so many of their daughters are grown. As a result,\u160\'00\'A0their initial experiences in the workplace, their choice of college major or their professional aspirations may have begun to influence their fathers' thinking.\u160\'00\'A0Another study from 2011, for instance, found that after CEOs of Danish firms had a daughter, female employees'\u160\'00\'A0wages rose relative to their male peers,\u160\'00\'A0narrowing\u160\'00\'A0the wage gap.\par \par \uc2 It's unclear how having children vs. not having children, rather than\u160\'00\'A0whether the children were male or female, might affect a CEO's behavior. Because less than 5\u160\'00\'A0percent of the CEOs had no children, Cronqvist excluded them from his study.\par \par \uc2 Another\u160\'00\'A0group that had a small sample in the study was female CEOs. Less than 4\u160\'00\'A0percent of the executives studied were women\u8212\'20\'14so while those women did have much\u160\'00\'A0stronger \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  ratings than their male peers, it was such a small group that the findings are\u160\'00\'A0not reliable.\par \par \uc2 However,\u160\'00\'A0Cronqvist does use those figures\u160\'00\'A0to make an interesting comparison. Even\u160\'00\'A0male CEOs with a daughter tend to have only\u160\'00\'A0about one-third the social responsibility rating\u160\'00\'A0of CEOs who are women.\u160\'00\'A0Or as Cronqvist puts it: "Having the daughter seems to make male CEOs one third more female, with respect to the decisions being made."\par \par \uc2 Read also:\par \par \uc2 Mothers are more likely than women without children to want top executive jobs\par \par \uc2 The potential payoff for kids of working mothers\par \par \uc2 Like On Leadership? Follow us on \uc2 Facebook\uc2  and \uc2 Twitter\uc2 , and subscribe to our podcast on iTunes.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 i9831 : \uc2 Business Schools | i983 : \uc2 Educational Services | ibcs : \uc2 Business/Consumer Services\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 ccsr : \uc2 Corporate Social Responsibility | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | ncat : \uc2 Content Types | nfact : \uc2 Factiva Filters | nfcpex : \uc2 C&E Executive News Filter\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RE\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 usdc : \uc2 Washington DC | namz : \uc2 North America | usa : \uc2 United States | uss :