stright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2016 The New York Times Company. All rights reserved   \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Way back in 2008, I wrote about \uc2 Wal-Mart\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s emerging {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://corporate.walmart.com/global-responsibility/sustainability/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 effort to cut environmental and social harms}}}\uc2  from its business operations by exerting influence back along globe-spanning supply chains.\par \par \uc2 There were, of course, lots of issues, including this one, as I wrote at the time: \u8220\'20\'1C{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://dotearth.blogs.nytimes.com/2008/10/23/wal-mart-china-ethics-environment/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Wal-Mart is still selling consumerism even as it pledges to cut the social and environmental costs of making the stuff in its stores}}}\uc2 .\u8221\'20\'1D\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 This fall, Marc Gunther, a journalist focused on business and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , filed {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.theguardian.com/sustainable-business/2015/nov/18/walmart-climate-change-carbon-emissions-renewabe-energy-environment"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 an update on Wal-Mart\u8217\'20\'19s performance}}}\uc2  for\u160\'00\'A0\uc2 The Guardian\uc2 , giving the company mostly good grades except on its slow adoption of renewable energy.\par \par \uc2 More generally these\u160\'00\'A0days, it seems, growing ranks of companies are moving beyond pursuing \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  as a marketing strategy (sift \uc2 Twitter\uc2  for \u8220\'20\'1C{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://twitter.com/search?q=%23csr%20marketing&src=typd"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 #CSR #marketing}}}\uc2 \u8221\'20\'1D to get familiar with this arena) and changing basic business models in fundamental ways.\par \par \uc2 Here are some factors that appear to be\u160\'00\'A0driving the shift.\par \par \uc2 Imposed Transparency | For one thing, there has never been greater capacity for independent organizations, media or simply concerned citizens to impose transparency on big companies.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 A fresh example was \uc2 Amnesty International\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.amnesty.org/en/latest/news/2016/01/Child-labour-behind-smart-phone-and-electric-car-batteries/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 report last Tuesday}}}\uc2  offering evidence that \u8220\'20\'1Cmajor electronics brands, including Apple, \uc2 Samsung\uc2  and \uc2 Sony\uc2 , are failing to do basic checks to ensure that cobalt mined by child laborers has not been used in their products.\u8221\'20\'1D Here\u8217\'20\'19s a video summary:\par \par \uc2 Combine those concerns with these powerful demographic realities\u160\'00\'A0described recently on the\u160\'00\'A0green-business website {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.triplepundit.com/2015/12/millennials-trends-reshaping-america/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Triple Pundit in December}}}\uc2 \u160\'00\'A0and you can see why companies are getting serious about change:\par \par \uc2 By 2017 the millennial generation will be both our country\u8217\'20\'19s most employed demographic group and our country\u8217\'20\'19s largest consumer group. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.earth2017.com/five-steps-to-winning-millennial-generation-customers/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Future business success now hinges on satisfying the millennial generation\u8217\'20\'19s sustainability expectations}}}\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Advertising Age recently {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://adage.com/article/digitalnext/ways-marketers-create-smarter-csr-campaigns/301796/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 explored results of surveys}}}\uc2 \u160\'00\'A0by companies eager to woo\u160\'00\'A0young consumers and employees. Here\u8217\'20\'19s an excerpt:\par \par \uc2 They may be the \u8220\'20\'1Cselfie generation,\u8221\'20\'1D but millennials are also focused on creating social change. Their eagerness to make an impact on the world is a hallmark of youth, but millennials are expressing their values in a new way \u8212\'20\'14 by choosing to support brands with strong \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  initiatives.\par \par \uc2 A recent survey\u160\'00\'A0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://philanthropy.com/items/biz/pdf/AflacCorporateSocialResponsibility.pdf"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 from insurer Aflac}}}\uc2 \u160\'00\'A0illustrates just how important CSR is to the younger generation. Two thirds of millennials surveyed responded that they are likely to invest in a company well known for its \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  program, compared with less than half of adults over 34. And according to a study by Horizon Media\u8217\'20\'19s Finger on the Pulse, some\u160\'00\'A0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.forbes.com/sites/larissafaw/2014/05/22/millennials-expect-more-than-good-products-services-to-win-their-loyalty/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 81 percent of millennials}}}\uc2  expect companies to make a public commitment to good corporate citizenship.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CThe \uc2 Aflac\uc2  survey clearly shows that people want to do business with a good company they believe in,\u8221\'20\'1D said Barbara Corcoran,\u160\'00\'A0who is best known as one of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.inc.com/magazine/201505/liz-welch/barbara-corcoran-shark-tank-icons-of-entrepreneurship.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 the tough \u8220\'20\'1Cinvestors\u8221\'20\'1D on the \u8220\'20\'1CShark Tank\u8221\'20\'1D reality television program}}}\uc2  but is also a spokesperson for Aflac on corporate responsibility.\par \par \uc2 Volkswagen\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s managers clearly hadn\u8217\'20\'19t figured this out, she said, adding:\u160\'00\'A0\u8220\'20\'1CVW would have been wise to have been in touch with their consumers in a meaningful way. They\u8217\'20\'19d have seen that if a company stays true to ethics it will outperform.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 As {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/23/science/global-companies-joining-climate-change-efforts.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 The Times reported last September}}}\uc2 , a move by a host of corporations with global markets to shift operations to renewable energy sources is in part driven by concerns of young consumers:\par \par \uc2 Companies have realized that cutting their energy use can save money. But they are also under pressure from consumers, particularly younger ones, to take action, and many companies have begun to see their environmental efforts as a core part of their business strategy.\par \par \uc2 Other companies are rejecting the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.forbes.com/sites/paularosenblum/2015/05/21/fast-fashion-has-completely-disrupted-apparel-retail/#7f13e08218b6"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1Cfast fashion\u8221\'20\'1D}}}\uc2  cycle. Take the \u8220\'20\'1C30-year sweatshirt\u8221\'20\'1D marketed to the millennial generation by Tom Cridland, a 25-year-old British designer. Outside Magazine has {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.outsideonline.com/2040261/30-year-sweatshirt"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 a story describing the insane buy-wear-toss culture}}}\uc2  he\u8217\'20\'19s trying to undermine.\par \par \uc2 One of my Pace University blogging students, Samantha Clarke, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://sc50630p.wix.com/dresswithnature#!30-Years-With-Tom/cmbz/565f2bbe0cf21dcdb62a2ab8"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 wrote about Cridland this fall}}}\uc2  and interviewed\u160\'00\'A0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://twitter.com/maxinebedat"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Maxine B\u233\'00\'E9dat}}}\uc2 , a co-founder of Zady, an online\u160\'00\'A0retailer that is, in essence, aiming to broaden the definition of design to include the sourcing of raw materials and back stories of its suppliers. That information gives conscientious consumers a choice,\u160\'00\'A0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://sc50630p.wix.com/dresswithnature#!A-Vision-to-Make-the-World-Better/cmbz/5668544c0cf28314431eb78b"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 B\u233\'00\'E9dat told Clarke}}}\uc2 .\u160\'00\'A0\u8220\'20\'1CEvery time we buy something we are voting,\u8221\'20\'1D she added.\u160\'00\'A0(Of course, this is a return to days of old in many ways. Older readers may recall that retailers like \uc2 L.L. Bean\uc2  have long stressed durability and offered free replacements for worn items.\par \par \uc2 There\u8217\'20\'19s still a long road ahead, of course. Most consumers are more interested in price than back stories.\par \par \uc2 And then there is the world of consumer attitudes in Asia. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jb8n6_PEhXc"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Social media campaigns}}}\uc2  by celebrities have raised awareness of the impacts of buying ivory, shark fin and other goods coveted by the new middle class.\par \par \uc2 But it\u8217\'20\'19s still unremarkable to pick up a newspaper in, say, Singapore, as I did last week and find {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://graphics8.nytimes.com/images/2016/01/23/blogs/dotsharkfin/dotsharkfin-popup.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 an ad like this one}}}\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Will {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/29/jobs/make-way-for-generation-z.html?_r=0"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Generation Z}}}\uc2  follow suit? We\u8217\'20\'19ll see.\par \par \uc2 More reading from \uc2 The Times\uc2 :\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/21/business/media/marketers-fixation-on-the-millennial-generation.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1COh, to Be Young, Millennial, and So Wanted by Marketers\u8221\'20\'1D}}}\par \par \uc2 A \uc2 New York Times\uc2  inEducation student essay: {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://nytimesineducation.com/spotlight/selfie-or-selfless-stewardship-for-millennials/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 #Selfie or #Selfless? Stewardship for Millennials}}}\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CO\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 afl : \uc2 AFLAC Inc | samgup : \uc2 Samsung Group\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustrig