\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Copyright 2016 Dow Jones & Company, Inc. All Rights Reserved.   \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Socially responsible investing has come a long way from the days when it mostly meant not buying the shares of companies in controversial industries such as tobacco, firearms, alcohol or gambling.\par \par \uc2 Now, investors who favor this approach routinely consider a broad range of corporate behavior under the umbrella of so-called ESG factors\u8212\'20\'14environmental, social and governance, as in corporate governance.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Journal Report\par \par \uc2 * Insights from {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://blogs.wsj.com/experts/category/wealth-management/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 The Experts}}}\par \par \uc2 * Read more at {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://online.wsj.com/public/page/journal-report-wealth.html?mg=inert-wsj"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 WSJ.com/WealthReport}}}\par \par \uc2 More in Big Issues: Personal Finance\par \par \uc2 * {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.wsj.com/articles/can-robo-advisers-replace-human-financial-advisers-1456715553"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Can Robo Advisers Replace Human Advisers?}}}\par \par \uc2 * {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.wsj.com/articles/should-the-u-s-adopt-a-value-added-tax-1456715703"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Should the U.S. Adopt a Value-Added Tax?}}}\par \par \uc2 * {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.wsj.com/articles/whats-the-best-way-to-teach-financial-skills-to-children-1456715769"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 How to Teach Children Financial Skills}}}\par \par \uc2 * {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.wsj.com/articles/is-it-time-to-end-tipping-1456715614"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Is It Time to End Tipping?}}}\par \par \uc2 * {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.wsj.com/articles/should-congress-rescind-the-pay-ratio-rule-1456715962"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Should Congress Drop the CEO Pay-Ratio Rule?}}}\par \par \uc2 For many investors, socially responsible investing is now a guiding principle. The number of mutual funds and exchange-traded funds catering to those investors has mushroomed in recent years, with industry heavyweights \uc2 BlackRock Inc\uc2 . and \uc2 Goldman Sachs Group Inc\uc2 . prominent among those launching funds last year.\par \par \uc2 Something else has changed, as well: Investors now expect a competitive return for investing with a conscience. Some have gotten just that; others haven't. So amid the rising popularity of ESG investing, the question of whether it pays remains.\par \par \uc2 Alex Edmans, a professor of finance at \uc2 London Business School\uc2 , argues that it does. David J. Vogel, a professor at the \uc2 Haas School of Business\uc2 , counters that in most cases it doesn't.\par \par \uc2 Yes: The evidence is clear that investors undervalue socially responsible firms\par \par \uc2 By Alex Edmans\par \par \uc2 Socially responsible investing makes financial sense precisely because many investors incorrectly think that it doesn't\u8212\'20\'14and so they undervalue socially responsible companies. That means bargains are available for astute investors.\par \par \uc2 Traditional investing focuses on tangible measures of a company's value, such as profits and sales growth. But those measures are easy for anyone to see and understand, and so they're already reflected in the stock price.\par \par \uc2 In contrast, social responsibility is intangible, and so investors have a particularly hard time valuing it. How do you measure the value of a company's environmental stewardship? As a result, traditional investors mostly ignore companies' social responsibility. They only catch on when its effects show up on the bottom line, for everyone to see. But then it's too late\u8212\'20\'14the stock price has already risen.\par \par \uc2 Years ahead\par \par \uc2 Where's the evidence that socially responsibility pays for investors?\par \par \uc2 Let's look at the findings of academic studies of four common social-responsibility factors. Returns for companies with high scores on the American Customer Satisfaction Index were {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://journals.ama.org/doi/abs/10.1509/jmkg.2006.70.1.3?journalCode=jmkg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 double}}}\uc2  those of the Dow Jones Industrial Average from 1997 to 2003. Turning to governance, studies found that firms with greater {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=278920"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 shareholder rights}}}\uc2  and firms where the chief executive holds a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=1343179"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 large stake}}}\uc2  outperformed, and those that use {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://fisher.osu.edu/~young.53/Yermack_perks.pdf"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 corporate jets}}}\uc2  underperformed. Moving to the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , companies with high eco-efficiency\u8212\'20\'14that generate the least waste relative to the value of their products and services\u8212\'20\'14{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.cfapubs.org/doi/abs/10.2469/faj.v61.n2.2716?journalCode=faj&"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 outperformed}}}\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Finally, on employee satisfaction, my own study shows that the returns of the 100 Best Companies to Work for in America {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://faculty.london.edu/aedmans/Rowe.pdf"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 beat their peers}}}\uc2  by 2.3 to 3.8 percentage points a year from 1984 to 2011. And although the list is public, it takes the market four to five years to incorporate it into stock prices\u8212\'20\'14because this information is ignored by most investors.\par \par \uc2 A look at specific market sectors provides further evidence of the financial value of socially responsible investing. Ethical investors typically overweight health care (based on the social benefits of treating disease) and technology (because e-commerce uses far fewer resources than physical stores). Both sectors have far outperformed the S&P 500 over the past 10 years, while the energy sector (dominated by production from nonrenewable sources) has been flat overall and coal stocks have fallen substantially.\par \par \uc2 But is concern for customers, governance, the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and employees really socially responsible? Isn't this just good business sense? To a degree. The question is what comes first. Traditional firms will invest in stakeholders only if they can calculate a clear bottom-line impact of doing so. But, many benefits of social responsibility simply can't be predicted. What's the payoff to reducing emissions beyond the threshold that would avoid a fine? Responsible firms invest simply because they think it's the right thing to do, without a mathematical calculation. The profits come as a byproduct, they're not the end goal.\par \par \uc2 Legwork pays\par \par \uc2 None of this means that ethical investing is foolproof. Many socially responsible funds underperform their peers. But so do many traditional mutual funds, and that doesn't mean traditional investing strategies don't make financial sense. The crux is to evaluate socially responsible strategies, not socially responsible funds, because even ethical funds use criteria other than pure social responsibility. The shortcomings of any number of socially responsible mutual funds or companies don't alter the premise proved by broad-based research: Ethical investing works.\par \par \uc2 It isn't easy, but it's getting easier. Investors don't have to rely solely on companies to report their own socially responsible activities. Independent information like the Best Companies list or the American Customer Satisfaction Index is out there for investors willing to do the legwork. Most investors aren't\u8212\'20\'14and again, that's the advantage of socially responsible investing.\par \par \uc2 Dr. Edmans is a professor of finance at \uc2 London Business School\uc2 . He can be reached at {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "mailto:reports@wsj.com"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 reports@wsj.com}}}\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 No: It's absurd to even try to separate responsible from irresponsible firms\par \par \uc2 By David J. Vogel\par \par \uc2 There are several reasons why a socially responsible investment strategy is unlikely to produce superior returns.\par \par \uc2 First, there is no consensus on how to define \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  or how to construct a portfolio based on the concept. Social investment funds and socially screened portfolios employ widely diverse and often inconsistent criteria to assess both corporate responsibility and irresponsibility. How can a socially responsible investment strategy claim to produce superior returns when there is no agreement on what \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  means or how to measure it?\par \par \uc2 Some of the strategies employed by social investment funds and socially screened portfolios have succeeded\u8212\'20\'14but most have not. Over the past five and 10 years, 65% of socially screened funds have trailed the average returns of their peers.\par \par \uc2 Blind spots and complications\par \par \uc2 Second, the data used to assess a company's social responsibility is limited and often flawed. For example, the Global Reporting Initiative, the largest voluntary reporting guideline, contains data on only 1,295 companies\u8212\'20\'14less than 2% of the world's publicly traded firms. Moreover, in the critical area of carbon emissions, analysts must rely on business self-reporting, which may not be accurate and rarely includes the carbon footprints of a firm's products or its supply chain. These and other information gaps severely compromise the value of the criteria on which \u8220\'20\'1Cethical" investors typically rely.\par \par \uc2 Further complicating the picture are the mixed or ambiguous records of many companies. Does \uc2 Monsanto\uc2 's support for genetically modified agriculture make it responsible or irresponsible? Should \uc2 Dow Chemical\uc2  be excluded from a sustainability-screened portfolio because of past pollution or included because of its recent leadership in tracking and reducing its environmental impact and that of its products? What about a fossil-fuel company that has recently expanded its renewable-energy investment portfolio? In the real world, a company's ethical behavior is both constantly changing and often mixed.\par \par \uc2 Third, a company's record or reputation can be a poor predictor of its future behavior. Consider. for example, \uc2 BP\uc2 , \uc2 Volkswagen\uc2  and Chipotle\u8212\'20\'14all of which had highly positive reputations for social responsibility before environmental, safety and health disasters brought down their share prices.\par \par \uc2 Missing links\par \par \uc2 Fourth, the argument that a socially responsible investment strategy \u8220\'20\'1Cpays" assumes that paying more attention to a firm's social responsibility\u8212\'20\'14or lack of it\u8212\'20\'14makes for a better predictor of future share prices. But a firm's social-responsibility policies or practices are rarely of sufficient importance to its earnings to affect its share price. For example, while \uc2 Wal-Mart\uc2 's costs have been reduced by its many \u8220\'20\'1Cgreen" initiatives, those reductions have been ignored by analysts because they aren't material to the firm's future earnings.\par \par \uc2 Previously in Personal Finance\par \par \uc2 * {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.wsj.com/articles/7-things-investors-should-watch-for-in-2016-1454900929"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 7 Things for Investors to Watch in '16}}}\par \par \uc2 * {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.wsj.com/articles/do-elite-colleges-lead-to-higher-salaries-only-for-some-professions-1454295674"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Do Prestigious Colleges Pay Off?}}}\par \par \uc2 * {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.wsj.com/articles/a-strategy-to-maximize-social-security-benefits-1454295687"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 A Strategy to Maximize Social Security Benefits}}}\par \par \uc2 * {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.wsj.com/articles/should-students-be-required-to-work-in-college-1425271057"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Should Students Be Required to Work in College? }}}\par \par \uc2 * {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.wsj.com/articles/is-a-prenuptial-agreement-a-must-for-most-couples-1425271056"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Prenups: Are They a Must for Most Couples?}}}\par \par \uc2 Studies that have shown a connection between certain aspects of \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  and future share prices don't negate studies that have shown no effect or even a negative impact from such responsibility. And any such connection shouldn't be generalized into the superior wisdom of a socially responsible investment strategy.\par \par \uc2 As for the gains of the health-care and technology sectors in recent years, they have little to do with social responsibility\u8212\'20\'14indeed, some of the behavior of many companies in both fields can hardly be called responsible.\par \par \uc2 Finally, a more responsible business strategy is no more likely to be financially successful than one that pays little or no attention to \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The number of relatively responsible firms that nonetheless have suffered financial reverses is a long one and recently includes \uc2 DuPont\uc2  and \uc2 American Apparel\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Dr. Vogel is the Solomon P. Lee emeritus professor in business ethics at the \uc2 University of California, Berkeley's Haas School of Business\uc2 . He can be reached at {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "mailto:reports@wsj.com"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 reports@wsj.com}}}\uc2 .\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CO\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 blaman : \uc2 BlackRock Inc.\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 