widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LA\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 English\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2016 The New York Times Company. All Rights Reserved. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Her husband was away in the fields, she said, when the truckloads of soldiers, police and mining security officials arrived. A half-dozen armed men swarmed into her one-room house, blocking her exit and helping themselves to the meal she had made for her children.\par \par \uc2 For a long time, Margarita Caal Caal did not talk about what happened next that afternoon. None of the women in this tiny village high in the hills of eastern Guatemala did, not even to each other. But that day, she said, the men who had come to evict her from land they said belonged to a Canadian mining company also took turns raping her. After that, they dragged her from her home and set it ablaze.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 \u8216\'20\'18\u8216\'20\'18The fear is not over,\u8217\'20\'19\u8217\'20\'19 she said recently, staring down at her hands while her daughter served coffee to visitors. \u8216\'20\'18\u8216\'20\'18I still fear, all the time.\u8217\'20\'19\u8217\'20\'19\par \par \uc2 Mrs. Caal has taken her case to the courts, but not in Guatemala where Mayan villagers like her, illiterate and living in isolated areas, have had little legal success. She has filed in Canada, where her negligence suit, Caal v. Hudbay Mineral Inc., has sent shivers through the vast Canadian mining, oil and gas industry. More than 50 percent of the world\u8217\'20\'19s publicly listed exploration and mining companies had headquarters in Canada in 2013, according to government statistics. Those 1,500 companies had an interest in some 8,000 properties in more than 100 countries around the world.\par \par \uc2 For decades, overseas subsidiaries have acted as a shield for extractive companies even while human rights advocates say they have chronicled a long history of misbehavior, from environmental damage to the violent submission of protesters and the forced evictions of indigenous peoples.\par \par \uc2 But Mrs. Caal\u8217\'20\'19s negligence claim and those of 10 other women from this village who say they were gang-raped that day in 2007, as well as two other negligence claims against Hudbay, have already passed several significant legal hurdles \u8212\'20\'14 suggesting that Canada-based companies could face new scrutiny about their overseas operations in the future. Last June, a ruling ordered Hudbay to turn over what Mrs. Caal\u8217\'20\'19s lawyers expect will be thousands of pages of internal documents. Hudbay, which was not the owner of the mine at the time of the evictions, denies any wrongdoing.\par \par \uc2 Canadian law does not provide for huge American-style payoffs, even if the court finds in the plaintiff\u8217\'20\'19s favor. But the Hudbay case is being watched carefully because it appears to offer a new legal pathway for those who say they have suffered at the hands of Canadian subsidiaries. A ruling in this case, experts say, could also help establish powerful guidelines for what constitutes acceptable corporate behavior.\par \par \uc2 \u8216\'20\'18\u8216\'20\'18Up until now, we just have not had judicial decisions that help us consider these sorts of relationships,\u8217\'20\'19\u8217\'20\'19 said Sara Seck, an expert on \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  at the Faculty of Law, Western University, in London, Ontario. \u8216\'20\'18\u8216\'20\'18For once, the court is going to look at what really happened here, and that is important.\u8217\'20\'19\u8217\'20\'19\par \par \uc2 The behavior of multinational companies working in poor countries has come under increasing fire in recent years. Social expectations have changed, experts say, with many citizens of rich countries demanding that corporations be more responsible in the countries in which they operate.\par \par \uc2 In Canada, efforts to define a code of good behavior for extractive corporations are longstanding, if so far unsuccessful. Many mining companies are based there because Canada offers a concentration of expertise in mining finance and law, and the government offers incentives including tax breaks.\par \par \uc2 A bill that would have created an ombudsman to investigate complaints and deny access to government loans \u8212\'20\'14 and even consular services \u8212\'20\'14 to companies accused of behaving poorly failed by a narrow margin in 2010 after facing fierce opposition from the extractive industry. John McKay, a member of Parliament from the Liberal Party who sponsored that bill, said he expected Canada\u8217\'20\'19s new government to try again soon.\par \par \uc2 \u8216\'20\'18\u8216\'20\'18There are companies out there doing things that they would never do in their own countries,\u8217\'20\'19\u8217\'20\'19 he said.\par \par \uc2 In a 2014 report , the \uc2 Council on Hemispheric Affairs\uc2 , a Washington-based policy group, concluded that Canadian companies, accounting for 50 percent to 70 percent of the mining in Latin America, were often associated with extensive damage to the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , from erosion and sedimentation to groundwater and river contamination. Of particular note, it said, was that the industry \u8216\'20\'18\u8216\'20\'18demonstrated a disregard for registered nature reserves and protected zones.\u8217\'20\'19\u8217\'20\'19\par \par \uc2 At the same time, the report said, local people were being injured, arrested or, in some cases, killed for protesting.\par \par \uc2 Victims, however, have had little success gaining access to Canadian courts. Their lawyers have often tried to get cases heard on the basis of violations of human rights or international criminal law. But most were told that Canada had no jurisdiction, and that their claims would be more appropriately heard in the country where the events took place, even if the courts were notoriously corrupt or otherwise dysfunctional.\par \par \uc2 But the lawyers for the plaintiffs in the Hudbay case, Murray Klippenstein and Cory Wanless, took a novel approach, making a simpler claim. They said the Canadian parent company was negligent for failing to put an effective monitoring system in place to understand what its Guatemalan subsidiary was doing. Framing the claim in this way allowed the plaintiffs to draw a clear connection between the negligence and Canada.\par \par \uc2 Mrs. Caal and the other women who say they were raped in Lote Ocho have brought claims against Hudbay, which has headquarters in Toronto. The company is also facing claims over the death of a prominent local leader, Adolfo Ich Cham\u225\'00\'E1n, 50, and the shooting and paralyzing of a bystander, German Chub, 28, during demonstrations against mining in the nearby town of El Estor in 2009.\par \par \uc2 Hudbay lawyers moved to have the case dismissed on jurisdictional grounds, and because it was \u8216\'20\'18\u8216\'20\'18plain and obvious\u8217\'20\'19\u8217\'20\'19 that the claims would fail. Before the ruling on jurisdiction, they dropped that claim and went forward with the other one. In July 2013, however, the judge ruled it was not obvious that the claims were without merit.\par \par \uc2 Turning to the courts has not been easy for the plaintiffs, most of whom speak only Q\u8217\'20\'19eqchi\u8217\'20\'19, a Mayan language, have had little or no schooling, and find the prospect of going to Canada terrifying. In addition, they face animosity from a sizable portion of the local population, particularly in El Estor, where there is a giant nickel processing plant.\par \par \uc2 Hudbay officials dispute most of the plaintiffs\u8217\'20\'19 claims. They say that no mining security officials were present during the Lote Ocho evictions and no rapes took place. The company\u8217\'20\'19s website also points out that at the time, Hudbay had nothing to do with the mine. It was owned by Compa\u241\'00\'F1\u237\'00\'EDa Guatemalteca de N\u237\'00\'EDquel, a subsidiary of another Canadian company, Skye Resources, which Hudbay bought in 2008, assuming its liabilities. Hudbay has since sold the mine.\par \par \uc2 Hudbay officials also maintain that there was no negligence in 2009 when it did own the mine. Officials say the killing of Mr. Ich, a teacher, and the shooting of Mr. Chub, a farmer, took place as the mine\u8217\'20\'19s security guards were defending themselves from armed protesters.\par \par \uc2 But some recent events appear to lend credence to the plaintiffs\u8217\'20\'19 claims. The head of the mine\u8217\'20\'19s security during the 2007 evictions and the 2009 shootings, a former army colonel named Mynor Padilla, is now on trial in Guatemala over the shooting of Mr. Ich and Mr. Chub.\par \par \uc2 Moreover, an army officer and a paramilitary officer were convicted in February of raping and enslaving indigenous women in the 1980s, during Guatemala\u8217\'20\'19s long civil war, suggesting, some advocates say, that such behavior has long been entrenched in this country. During the war between the United States-backed government and leftist rebels, the indigenous population in this region was repeatedly attacked for trying to make land claims. Even now, the local Q\u8217\'20\'19eqchi\u8217\'20\'19 population believes much of the land in the area belongs to it, and not to the mining company.\par \par \uc2 At the time of Mrs. Caal\u8217\'20\'19s eviction, there was no mining anywhere near Lote Ocho, but mining officials moved to evict the villagers anyway. High in the hills, the community is made up of about a dozen scattered, flimsy wooden houses, home to about 100 people, most of them children.\par \par \uc2 There is no electricity here or a school for the children. The village is a bumpy 45-minute ride in a pickup truck uphill from the nearest town. But that costs money, so most of the villagers walk there using a footpath, which takes about two hours.\par \par \uc2 Mrs. Caal said the armed men who attacked her during the eviction were so brutal that she could not get up from the spot where they left her. But when her husband asked what had happened to her, she told him only that she had fallen, afraid of how he might react.\par \par \uc2 It is still a subject she turns to reluctantly.\par \par \uc2 \u8216\'20\'18\u8216\'20\'18Remembering is reliving,\u8217\'20\'19\u8217\'20\'19 Mrs. Caal said. \u8216\'20\'18\u8216\'20\'18It hurts. It hurts as a woman.\u8217\'20\'19\u8217\'20\'19\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 grape : \uc2 Sex Crimes | npag : \uc2 Page-One Stories | gcat : \uc2 Political/General News | gcrim : \uc2 Crime/Legal Action | ncat : \uc2 Content Types\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RE\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 cana : \uc2 Canada | guat : \uc2 Guatemala | camz : \uc2 Central America | dvpcoz : \uc2 Developing Economies | lamz : \uc2 Latin America | namz : \uc2 North America\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\in