\cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 The diversity of donors \u8212\'20\'14 in size, race, geography and philosophy \u8212\'20\'14 is undeniable. Gifts have come from across the country, from established foundations to upstarts, from donors who traditionally support the arts and culture to those who made exceptions to support this cause. Some of these gifts represented early votes of confidence in the project; more-recent grants have propelled the effort toward the goal.\par \par \uc2 The gifts continue at a rapid pace. This list represents the major donors as of the end of July, but officials say that a new top donor could join the group between now and the Sept.\u160\'00\'A024 opening and that many others will be added. After paying for the construction of the $540\u160\'00\'A0million building, officials hope to set aside more for endowment and future programs.\par \par \uc2 Oprah WinfreyCharitable Foundation\par \par \uc2 Hollywood, $21 million\par \par \uc2 The entertainment tycoon \u8212\'20\'14 a member of the museum council \u8212\'20\'14 is one of the museum's earliest supporters. Her gifts include $1\u160\'00\'A0million in 2007 and $12\u160\'00\'A0million in 2013, among others, making her the largest donor at that stage.\par \par \uc2 Lilly Endowment\par \par \uc2 Indianapolis, $20 million\par \par \uc2 The private foundation created by the family behind the pharmaceutical business gave $10\u160\'00\'A0million to the capital campaign in 2010 and a second $10\u160\'00\'A0million in 2015 to endow the Center for the Study of African American Religion and a senior curator. The center will collect and preserve religious artifacts and research African American faith.\par \par \uc2 Robert Frederick Smith\par \par \uc2 Austin, $20 million\par \par \uc2 The noted philanthropist is chairman and chief executive of Vista Equity Partners, one of the largest investment firms in the world. A \uc2 Cornell University\uc2  graduate, Smith serves as chairman of Carnegie Hall. He made his gift this year.\par \par \uc2 Andrew W. Mellon Foundation\par \par \uc2 New York, $12 million\par \par \uc2 The private foundation that promotes the arts and humanities awarded a $2\u160\'00\'A0million grant in 2012 to "strengthen curatorial and conservation capacities" at the museum, according to the foundation. A second grant of $10\u160\'00\'A0million was made in 2015 to endow the museum's curatorial research centers.\par \par \uc2 The Atlantic Philanthropies\par \par \uc2 New York, $12 million\par \par \uc2 Founded in 1982 by entrepreneur \uc2 Chuck Feeney\uc2 , the philanthropic organization addresses issues related to aging, children, health, and human rights and reconciliation around the world. Its 2015 grant was intended to "promote racial equity by supporting the creation of the first national, public museum on the African-American experience and the country's racial history," according to the organization.\par \par \uc2 Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation\par \par \uc2 Seattle, $10 million\par \par \uc2 The 2009 gift was outside the traditional focus of the foundation, which supports health and development around the world and education in the United States. It was a "vote of confidence" and a critical step in building broad support for the design and construction of the museum, said the museum's founding director, Lonnie Bunch, when the grant was announced. \uc2 Allan Golston\uc2 , president of the Gates Foundation's U.S. program, serves on the museum council.\par \par \uc2 Rhimes Family Foundation\par \par \uc2 Hollywood, $10 million\par \par \uc2 The $10 million gift from Shonda Rhimes, the TV producer behind "Grey's Anatomy" and "Scandal," was announced at a donor party hosted by Denzel Washington and his wife, Pauletta, in April.\par \par \uc2 David M. Rubenstein\par \par \uc2 Washington, $10 million\par \par \uc2 The Carlyle Group\uc2  co-founder and philanthropist has supported many cultural organizations in the District. A member of the Smithsonian's Board of Regents, he has given millions to the National Zoo, the Renwick Gallery, the National Archives and the Washington Monument. The David M. Rubenstein History Galleries will commemorate his 2015 gift to the new museum's capital campaign. "The museum is a place of learning, inspiration and healing that honors the important contributions African Americans have made to our country over hundreds of years," Rubenstein said.\par \par \uc2 Ford Foundation\par \par \uc2 New York, $8.6 million\par \par \uc2 The private foundation has made several contributions to the museum dating to 2006, according to a Ford spokeswoman. The largest gift, $7.5\u160\'00\'A0million, was made in 2011 for the design and building of the museum galleries focused on African American life after the civil rights movement.\par \par \uc2 Target\par \par \uc2 Minneapolis, $7.05 million\par \par \uc2 The retailer donated to the capital campaign for the construction of the museum in 2011 and made another gift to support the opening ceremonies in September. Target chief executive \uc2 Brian Cornell\uc2  is a member of the museum council. "As a founding donor of the \uc2 National Museum of African American History and Culture\uc2  and a sponsor of its grand opening, \uc2 Target\uc2  celebrates the importance of its mission to tell all Americans the rich story of the African American experience," Cornell said.\par \par \uc2 Kaiser Permanente\par \par \uc2 Oakland, Calif., $7 million\par \par \uc2 One of the country's leading health-care providers, \uc2 Kaiser Permanente\uc2  has contributed several grants to the museum, including a $5\u160\'00\'A0million gift to the capital campaign in 2013, and is a sponsor of the museum's cafe and its September opening ceremonies. The museum's vision of diversity and inclusion reflect the values of the company, officials said. "Our donation ultimately will give millions of people around the world the opportunity to better understand the African American perspective and how generations of our history are interwoven into the fabric of America," said chairman and chief executive \uc2 Bernard J. Tyson\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Robert L. Johnson\par \par \uc2 West Palm Beach, Fla., $6 million\par \par \uc2 The entrepreneur and founder of Black Entertainment Television gave $2\u160\'00\'A0million to the museum's capital campaign between 2007 and 2008 and followed that in 2015 with the donation of several pieces from his art collection, valued at some $4\u160\'00\'A0million. Recognized as the country's first African American billionaire, Johnson is founder and chairman of the RLJ Cos. in Bethesda, Md., and a founding member of the museum council. His donations are meant to "support the museum in telling the story of the tragedy and triumph of the African American experience in America to all Americans and the rest of the world," he said.\par \par \uc2 General Electric\par \par \uc2 Fairfield, Conn., $5.5 million\par \par \uc2 GE\uc2  contributed $5\u160\'00\'A0million in 2014 in 2015 toward the construction of the museum and gave $500,000 last year. "Diversity and inclusiveness are essential to \uc2 GE\uc2 's productivity, creativity, innovation and competitive advantage," \uc2 GE\uc2  said in a statement. "We are excited that this public institution will soon be open to all, where anyone is welcome to participate, collaborate, and learn more about African American history and culture."\par \par \uc2 3M\par \par \uc2 St. Paul, Minn., $5 million\par \par \uc2 3M\uc2 's philanthropy focuses on education, community and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 . A longtime partner of the Smithsonian, the company's first gift to the new museum was made in 2012. "Over our 20-year partnership with the Smithsonian, \uc2 3M\uc2 's support reflects our innovative approach to improving lives," said Kim Price, the manufacturer's senior vice president of corporate communications and enterprise services. "We are honored to support this historic museum as global communities gather for a shared experience."\par \par \uc2 American Express\par \par \uc2 New York, $5 million\par \par \uc2 The financial-services company donated $5\u160\'00\'A0million in 2011 to support the construction of the museum. \uc2 American Express\uc2  has a long history of supporting historic preservation, company officials said. "That work is typically associated with the preservation of buildings and monuments, but it also concerns the preservation of artifacts and cultural heritage," said Tim McClimon, vice president of \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 . "It's a little atypical for us to [fund] construction of a new building." American Express chief executive Kenneth Chenault has been an advocate for the museum. Chenault joined the advisory council in 2004 and became chairman of the capital campaign committee in 2012. He and his wife, Kathryn, are listed among the $1\u160\'00\'A0million donors.\par \par \uc2 Boeing\par \par \uc2 Chicago, $5 million\par \par \uc2 The aerospace company donated $5\u160\'00\'A0million to the museum in 2007 to support development and design. "\uc2 Boeing\uc2  has a strong commitment to diversity and inclusion and recognizes that our success as a company and country is intertwined with the successes and accomplishments of countless African American leaders, scientists, military service members, engineers and innovators," said Gordon Johndroe, Boeing's vice president of communications and government operations.\par \par \uc2 Rockefeller Foundation\par \par \uc2 New York, $5 million\par \par \uc2 The foundation rarely funds capital projects, but it made an exception in 2008 with a $3\u160\'00\'A0million gift toward the museum's design and construction. In 2011, it awarded $2\u160\'00\'A0million more for the content development and design of the "Panorama of the Modern Civil Rights Movement" and "Interactive Lunch Counter" exhibitions. The foundation has a history of funding institutions that advance the participation and representation of African Americans, including the funding of historically black colleges, according to a spokeswoman. Its president, \uc2 Judith Rodin\uc2 , will attend the opening.\par \par \uc2 UnitedHealth Group\par \par \uc2 Silver Spring, Md., $5 million\par \par \uc2 The health-care company was one of several corporations that donated $5\u160\'00\'A0million toward the capital campaign before the 2012 groundbreaking.\par \par \uc2 Walmart\par \par \uc2 Bentonville, Ark., $5 million\par \par \uc2 The retailer donated $5\u160\'00\'A0million in 2010 toward the design and construction of the museum, part of its broad effort to invest in its communities. "As a member of over 10,000 communities across the U.S., we care about giving all our customers a voice to share their heritage, and that's why we are so proud to have played a role in the development of the \uc2 National Museum of African American History and Culture\uc2 ," said Julie Gehrki, senior director of Walmart corporate affairs, adding that the museum "will help tell a vital part of our nation's history."\par \par \uc2 peggy.mcglone@washpost.com\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CO\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 aahcnm : \uc2 Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\as