l \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LA\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 English\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Copyright 2016. The New York Times Company. All Rights Reserved. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 INDORE, India \u8212\'20\'14 Leaving his wife and two young children home on a recent Sunday, a 27-year-old salesman for {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/topic/company/abbott-laboratories?inline=nyt-org"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Abbott Laboratories}}}\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19 operations in {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://topics.nytimes.com/top/news/international/countriesandterritories/india/index.html?inline=nyt-geo"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 India}}}\uc2  \u8212\'20\'14 in fact, one of the American health care company\u8217\'20\'19s top performers there \u8212\'20\'14 rode his motorcycle to a remote railroad track and jumped in front of a train.\par \par \uc2 In his pocket, a note in blue ink, handwritten in a mix of Hindi and English, said, \u8220\'20\'1CI\u8217\'20\'19m going to commit suicide because I can\u8217\'20\'19t meet my company\u8217\'20\'19s sales targets and my company is pressuring me.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Ashish Awasthi\u8217\'20\'19s death last month resonated across India and through the halls of the health care giant. More than 250 fellow Abbott drug representatives in India walked off the job for a day, protesting what some called the company\u8217\'20\'19s overly aggressive sales policies. A national union of drug sales workers called for new government rules to rein in sales practices industrywide, saying they compromised patient health.\par \par \uc2 A six-month investigation by The \uc2 New York Times\uc2  found that in the push to win customers in India\u8217\'20\'19s chaotic and highly competitive drug market, some Abbott managers instructed employees to pursue sales at virtually any cost \u8212\'20\'14 in violation of Indian law, professional medical standards and the company\u8217\'20\'19s own ethics guidelines.\par \par \uc2 Sales jobs with global powerhouses like Abbott are highly prized positions in India. But they can also be extremely demanding, putting employees under inordinate pressure to cut corners, according to interviews with more than a dozen current and former sales representatives and managers and a review of internal Abbott communications provided by two of them.\par \par \uc2 In one of the most common practices, The Times found, Abbott managers told sales staff to hold what the company called health camps, where representatives would perform tests on patients for various ailments in an effort to drum up business for doctors, who would then prescribe Abbott drugs. The camps were typically held at doctor\u8217\'20\'19s offices or as community events.\par \par \uc2 Sales personnel who perform screening tests could be accused of practicing medicine without a license, a criminal offense, said Dr. Jayshree Mehta, president of the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.mciindia.org/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Medical Council of India}}}\uc2 , the country\u8217\'20\'19s medical regulatory agency. Indian medical ethics regulations also prohibit quid pro quo, Dr. Mehta said.\par \par \uc2 Abbott India\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s public affairs director, Anand Kadkol, said the company\u8217\'20\'19s marketing policies \u8220\'20\'1Care aligned with applicable laws\u8221\'20\'1D in India. He called the health camps \u8220\'20\'1Cdisease awareness education programs\u8221\'20\'1D and said that Abbott\u8217\'20\'19s policies did not allow the camps to be conducted \u8220\'20\'1Cin exchange for an explicit or implicit understanding\u8221\'20\'1D to prescribe Abbott products.\par \par \uc2 The company declined to comment on individual employees. Mr. Kadkol said Abbott was \u8220\'20\'1Caware of a number of the allegations raised\u8221\'20\'1D and had addressed them.\par \par \uc2 But Vivek Gupta, a former manager of a sales team in northern India, said he was fired last year under pressure to make his sales representatives do more screenings of patients to promote a new Abbott multivitamin for nerve damage. He tried to resist, he said, out of respect for the national rules and the company\u8217\'20\'19s own policies, which prohibit the use of health camps to influence which medicines are prescribed.\par \par \uc2 Dhirendra Yadav, 26, a former sales agent in central India in the neurology division, said he resigned in December 2013 under what he called \u8220\'20\'1Cimmense pressure to conduct business in unethical ways.\u8221\'20\'1D He said his former manager \u8212\'20\'14 who later became the manager of Mr. Awasthi, the man who committed suicide \u8212\'20\'14 insisted that he use his own money to buy medicines costing nearly 15,000 rupees, or about $220, to help his group meet a sales target. That would be more than half of a typical representative\u8217\'20\'19s monthly pay.\par \par \uc2 Rajeev Khanna, who managed six sales representatives for neurology medicines in northern India, said he was fired after complaining to Abbott\u8217\'20\'19s office of ethics and compliance that his team was submitting fake invoices to increase sales. He described a practice of giving discounts intended for government institutions to private wholesalers as a kickback.\par \par \uc2 Corruption, already pervasive industrywide in India, has intensified with growing competition, according to the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.fmrai.org/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Federation of Medical and Sales Representatives\u8217\'20\'19 Associations of India}}}\uc2 , the largest union of drug sales personnel, representing tens of thousands nationwide, which called for the new regulation.\par \par \uc2 Unethical marketing practices are routine in the Indian pharmaceutical market, said Sanjeev Khandelwal, a union secretary who works as a drug salesman at an Indian company.\par \par \uc2 India\u8217\'20\'19s annual drug sales, estimated at $16 billion, may be small by the standards of the United States or Europe, but the market is attractive because it has been growing faster than 10 percent annually in recent years, placing it far ahead of developed markets in terms of growth.\par \par \uc2 It is also unusually competitive. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2005/03/24/world/asia/india-alters-law-on-drug-patents.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Until about a decade ago}}}\uc2 , Indian intellectual-property law let manufacturers ignore drug patents \u8212\'20\'14 and thousands of manufacturers cropped up. Today India generally honors patents, but its medical marketplace retains its Wild West roots in the form of countless confusing brands and extreme price competition. As a government expert panel noted in a 2011 report, \u8220\'20\'1CThe market is flooded by irrational, nonessential and even hazardous drugs that waste resources and compromise health.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 In this battle for sales, employees like Mr. Awasthi are the drug companies\u8217\'20\'19 front-line foot soldiers.\par \par \uc2 In an email, Mr. Kadkol, the \uc2 Abbott India\uc2  spokesman, said, \u8220\'20\'1CWe are deeply saddened to learn of Ashish Awasthi\u8217\'20\'19s tragic demise,\u8221\'20\'1D describing him as \u8220\'20\'1Camong the top performers in 2015.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 The \u8216\'20\'18Perfect Life\u8217\'20\'19\par \par \uc2 As multinationals like Abbott expand in India, they bring something powerfully attractive to the nation\u8217\'20\'19s emerging middle class: jobs. The positions they offer become highly coveted, both for the prestige of working for a global company and because India\u8217\'20\'19s economy \u8212\'20\'14 despite its 7.6 percent growth \u8212\'20\'14 still produces far too few jobs for the one million people who enter the work force each month.\par \par \uc2 This sets the stage for fierce competition for positions like these \u8212\'20\'14 and a desperation to retain them.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Awasthi embodied these ambitions. Hailing from a farming town about 400 miles northeast of Indore, he was one of the countless people who flock to India\u8217\'20\'19s cities with hopes of climbing the economic and social ladder.\par \par \uc2 In December 2013, when Abbott hired him as a salesman, he felt he had won the lottery, said his 27-year-old widow, Anita Awasthi. He told her, \u8220\'20\'1CI can do everything for you now,\u8221\'20\'1D she recalled recently for visitors who had come to her home to offer their condolences.\par \par \uc2 His job was persuading doctors to use Abbott\u8217\'20\'19s medicines for neurological diseases, and he was a disciplined salesman, according to a former boss, Ramchandra Tiwari. It is a grueling job, Mr. Tiwari said, requiring aggressive efforts to catch doctors\u8217\'20\'19 attention early in the morning or late in the evening.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Awasthi thrived, though. In 2015 he won a top salesman award. The young couple had made many close friends, his wife said, and maintained a busy social life going to movies and visiting area temples. She called theirs the \u8220\'20\'1Cperfect life.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 And they began to stretch financially. Mr. Awasthi bought a car \u8212\'20\'14 a sought-after symbol of arrival in the Indian middle class \u8212\'20\'14 and proudly carried a snapshot of it, garlanded with flowers. And he took out a loan to buy a one-bedroom apartment for about $20,000.\par \par \uc2 The purchases meant money was tight, Ms. Awasthi said. Her husband recently asked a friend to borrow about $70 to pay their 7-year-old daughter\u8217\'20\'19s school fees.\par \par \uc2 Still, all was good, she said, until this June, when he got a new manager. According to his previous manager, Mr. Tiwari, the demands on the sales staff rapidly built. Mr. Tiwari described it as \u8220\'20\'1Cinhuman and unnatural\u8221\'20\'1D pressure to sell.\par \par \uc2 The day he was found dead, Mr. Awasthi had been expected to attend a meeting with his new boss. Ms. Awasthi believes her husband \u8212\'20\'14 despite being a top performer \u8212\'20\'14 expected to lose his coveted job that day.\par \par \uc2 Camps for Checkups\par \par \uc2 Mr. Gupta, the 37-year-old manager for neurology products in the northern city of Chandigarh, arrived at \uc2 Abbott India\uc2  from Solvay Pharma India when the two drug makers merged in 2011. \uc2 Abbott India\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s parent company {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E05E5D8173FF93BA1575AC0A96F9C8B63"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 acquired Solvay Pharmaceuticals, of Belgium}}}\uc2 , for $6.2 billion in 2010.\par \par \uc2 From the start, a contentious issue between Mr. Gupta and his managers was Abbott\u8217\'20\'19s use of sales personnel to perform medical tests at health camps.\par \par \uc2 In India, where many people lack affordable care, these mass screenings have become a common way for drug makers to lift sales, according to current and former Abbott sales representatives and managers.\par \par \uc2 The industry-sponsored camps typically focus on chronic ailments such as {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://health.nytimes.com/health/guides/disease/diabetes/overview.html?inline=nyt-classifier"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 diabetes}}}\uc2 , thyroid disorders, heart problems and lung disease. Sales personnel do the testing at no charge, and participating doctors get to increase their business by advertising free checkups. In return, the doctors are expected to prescribe the drug maker\u8217\'20\'19s product.\par \par \uc2 Some experts say these practices raise the prospect that people may be inappropriately diagnosed and could receive unnecessary treatment.\par \par \uc2 Abbott promotes its health camps nationwide as a core part of its \u8220\'20\'1C\b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 \u8221\'20\'1D program, which is intended partly to meet the Indian government\u8217\'20\'19s requirement that companies contribute to the social good. \u8220\'20\'1CIf it\u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 , then it shouldn\u8217\'20\'19t be linked to the sales of the brand,\u8221\'20\'1D Mr. Gupta said.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Kadkol of \uc2 Abbott India\uc2  said, \u8220\'20\'1CEmployees are not permitted to perform diagnostic tests.\u8221\'20\'1D The company denies that the purpose of the health camps is to have doctors use its drugs.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CAbbott\u8217\'20\'19s procedures clearly state that disease awareness programs must not be conducted or provided or offered in exchange for an explicit or implicit understanding to purchase, order, recommend, prescribe or provide favorable treatment to any Abbott products,\u8221\'20\'1D Mr. Kadkol said in an email.\par \par \uc2 However, more than a dozen internal emails shared with The Times by Mr. Gupta suggest that Abbott viewed the camps as a sales tool and that the strategy came from Abbott management. In a February 2015 email, a group product manager informed the sales force that January sales of Surbex Star, a vitamin Abbott promotes to treat neuropathy in people with diabetes, were \u8220\'20\'1Cway behind the expectations.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CNow is the time to bounce back and surpass February target for Surbex Star,\u8221\'20\'1D the manager wrote. \u8220\'20\'1CHerein below are the 6 easy steps to conduct neuropathy camps.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 The manager did not return phone calls and emails seeking comment.\par \par \uc2 In another email from last year, an Abbott marketing manager told Mr. Gupta and other first-line sales managers that their representatives were supposed to do a minimum of three neuropathy camps per quarter and that they were behind in that goal.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CCamps will go a long way in promoting Surbex Star,\u8221\'20\'1D the marketing manager said in the email.\par \par \uc2 Several senior managers were copied on both emails.\par \par \uc2 Shrey Agrawal, who wrote that email but is no longer with Abbott, said in a telephone interview that \u8220\'20\'1Cthere is no direct link\u8221\'20\'1D between camps and drug sales. Asked how this tracked with his email about Surbex Star, he said he would respond by email. He never did.\par \par \uc2 In another email last year, an Abbott sales agent boasted that a neuropathy camp he had conducted was \u8220\'20\'1Ca big success,\u8221\'20\'1D noting that 30 of the 40 patients tested positive, and that the doctor prescribed Surbex Star to all 30. He did not respond to requests for an interview.\par \par \uc2 A Dive Into Depression\par \par \uc2 As Mr. Gupta clashed with his bosses, he says, they began calling him and sending messages late at night and on Sundays, and he became depressed. After one particularly intense phone call, he grabbed a hot iron that his wife had just used and pushed it into his hand, searing his flesh and leaving a scar. He had thoughts of killing himself, he said, and saw a psychiatrist, who put him on an antidepressant and an antipsychotic.\par \par \uc2 Soon afterward, his bosses told him they wanted to transfer him 1,500 miles away, to the city of Chennai. He refused to go, he said, interpreting it as an effort to make him quit.\par \par \uc2 In an email to top leaders at \uc2 Abbott India\uc2  in August 2015, Mr. Gupta laid out his concerns. He told management that sales representatives were instructed to screen patients to increase sales.\par \par \uc2 As proof that the medical screening was happening, managers were instructing sales personnel to email photos of the tests being performed, Mr. Gupta explained \u8212\'20\'14 but with someone else posing as the tester, to conceal the representatives\u8217\'20\'19 involvement. He said the practices violated Abbott\u8217\'20\'19s code of ethics.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Gupta sent the allegations, and supporting documents, to the company\u8217\'20\'19s office of ethics and compliance in India as well. The Times has reviewed the documents.\par \par \uc2 Last autumn, Mr. Gupta was fired. He was told he had lost the managers\u8217\'20\'19 confidence, he said. Today he works for a hospital.\par \par \uc2 In response to allegations that the camps were improperly used to induce doctors to write prescriptions, Mr. Kadkol of \uc2 Abbott India\uc2  said, \u8220\'20\'1CThat just doesn\u8217\'20\'19t happen.\u8221\'20\'1D He noted that such camps were \u8220\'20\'1Cnot exclusive to a company,\u8221\'20\'1D adding, \u8220\'20\'1CThey happen in many companies across many geographies.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Regarding Mr. Gupta\u8217\'20\'19s other claims, Mr. Kadkol said, \u8220\'20\'1CWe don\u8217\'20\'19t comment on the details of internal compliance investigations.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Mr. Gupta\u8217\'20\'19s former boss, Anup Ray, said in an interview that the purpose of the health camps was for doctors to prescribe Surbex Star. That made Mr. Gupta \u8220\'20\'1Cuncomfortable,\u8221\'20\'1D Mr. Ray said. \u8220\'20\'1CI was also against it.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Suspicions of Kickbacks\par \par \uc2 Mr. Khanna, the former Abbott manager who said he was fired after complaining about questionable sales made at discounted government rates, oversaw a team of neurology-medicine sales representatives in Lucknow, in northern India. Now 48, he had worked for 25 years for Abbott, Solvay and a company it acquired.\par \par \uc2 In 2013, he said, he began to notice the rapid rise in sales at the government discount. Suspicious that the sales were a form of a kickback to wholesalers, to induce more orders, he asked his sales staff and the wholesalers to produce original copies of the orders from government institutions, which they failed to do, Abbott emails show. Mr. Khanna stopped approving the transactions, he said, but another manager then began approving them.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Khanna wrote to Abbott\u8217\'20\'19s ethics office in December 2013, laying out his concern that government purchasing rules were being violated. He said, \u8220\'20\'1CI am afraid if I will continue to resist these unethical practices anymore I may get transferred or may lose my job.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 On July 25, 2014, he says Abbott asked him to resign and accused him of a conflict of interest involving his wife. She had obtained a license the previous year to operate a wholesale drug business in case he left Abbott, where he felt increasingly insecure. Mr. Khanna said that opening a drug company would have violated Abbott\u8217\'20\'19s rules but that his wife had not started a company.\par \par \uc2 He says he refused to resign. Abbott fired him.\par \par \uc2 Asked about Mr. Khanna\u8217\'20\'19s allegations, Mr. Kadkol cited the company\u8217\'20\'19s policy of not discussing individual cases or investigations into internal complaints.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Awasthi\u8217\'20\'19s Final Days\par \par \uc2 Sitting on the floor of her tiny living room just days after her husband\u8217\'20\'19s suicide, Ms. Awasthi recounted the final few weeks of her husband\u8217\'20\'19s life.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CHe told me, \u8216\'20\'18The company is pressuring me,\u8217\'20\'19\u8221\'20\'1D she said, wearing a pink sari, her two young children playing among the mourners. \u8220\'20\'1CI said, \u8216\'20\'18Change jobs.\u8217\'20\'19 He said, \u8216\'20\'18How will I get another job?\u8217\'20\'19\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Work pressure built quickly in June after the new boss, Inder Kumar, took over managing Mr. Awasthi\u8217\'20\'19s sales team. His previous manager, Mr. Tiwari, had been asked to transfer to a city in southern India, more than 1,000 miles away from Indore. He declined the transfer and lost his job.\par \par \uc2 According to two former employees of the new manager, he could be a tough boss. One of them, Mayank Pandey, said he felt so desperate to meet sales targets that he bribed doctors with his own cash to get them to prescribe Abbott drugs. Mr. Pandey quit Abbott this year, describing himself as \u8220\'20\'1Cmentally broken.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Mr. Kumar declined requests for interviews, referring questions to Mr. Kadkol, \uc2 Abbott India\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s public affairs director, who cited the company\u8217\'20\'19s policy not to comment on individual employees.\par \par \uc2 In general, Mr. Kadkol said, \u8220\'20\'1Cretaliatory or denigrating behavior of any kind is not accepted\u8221\'20\'1D at Abbott, which encourages an \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  \u8220\'20\'1Cdevoid of any harassment or undue pressure.\u8221\'20\'1D He said any suggestion that Mr. Awasthi \u8220\'20\'1Cwas singled out for poor performance is without merit.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Ms. Awasthi said Mr. Kumar had summoned her husband to a Monday meeting. The day before, she says, Mr. Awasthi was unusually quiet. He swept their apartment, bathed both of the children and fed them. Then he napped by his wife\u8217\'20\'19s side. At about 6 p.m., he went out, leaving behind his cellphone and wallet.\par \par \uc2 Police found his body the next morning along the railroad track.\par \par \uc2 After Mr. Awasthi\u8217\'20\'19s death, Abbott gave his family a check for 345,000 rupees, about $5,000, which included his salary and allowances for July, various reimbursements, as well as a \u8220\'20\'1Cgratuity.\u8221\'20\'1D Though Ms. Awasthi does not work and needs money, she has refused to cash it.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CHe died because of them,\u8221\'20\'1D she said. \u8220\'20\'1CThey must take responsibility.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Geeta Anand reported from Indore, India, and from New Delhi and Mumbai, and Frederik Joelving from Copenhagen. Suhasini Raj contributed reporting from New Delhi.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b ART\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Gargy, 7, spending a moment with a photograph of her late father, Ashish Awasthi, before going to the school. | Atul Loke for The New York Times | Friends of Mr. Awasthi visiting the spot where he committed suicide. | Atul Loke for The New York Times | A photograph from the Awasthis\u8217\'20\'19 family album. | Atul Loke for The New York Times | A February 2015 email from a marketing manager, Shrey Agrawal, telling sales managers that their representatives were supposed to attend a minimum of three neuropathy camps per quarter. (Some names and identifying information have been redacted.) | Abbott offices in Mumbai, India. | Atul Loke for The New York Times | Anita Awasthi with her daughter Gargy outside their home in Indore, India. | Atul Loke for The New York Times \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 i257 : \uc2 Pharmaceuticals | i951 : \uc2 Health Care/Life Sciences\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\