 the lead in developing moderately priced {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/subjects/e/electric_vehicles/index.html?&inline=nyt-classifier"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 electric cars}}}\uc2 .\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 The rules governing emissions of carbon dioxide and other gases blamed for {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://topics.nytimes.com/top/news/science/topics/globalwarming/index.html?inline=nyt-classifier"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 climate change}}}\uc2  are going to get stricter, he said. If so, that is bad news for the future of vehicles powered by emissions-producing gasoline and other fossil fuels.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CYou know that the only technology that will allow the industry to continue to prosper is zero emissions or very low emissions, \u8220\'20\'1C he said.\par \par \uc2 Given that premise, electric cars, which do not emit CO2, would be the only available large-scale solution.\par \par \uc2 While there is much skepticism on the eve of the meetings about climate change in Marrakesh, Morocco, known as COP22, about whether the world is taking big enough steps to prevent temperatures from rising to dangerous levels, the changing attitudes of business leaders are one reason for cautious optimism.\par \par \uc2 While governments may make the rules, the responsibility will likely fall on businesses to implement energy- and emissions-reducing changes in how they operate and the products they provide to society.\par \par \uc2 Many business leaders say they recognize climate change as a serious problem and that they are under pressure to demonstrate to their customers and employees, as well as governments and regulators, that they are doing something about it.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CI think the demand comes from the people who buy our products,\u8221\'20\'1D said Trisa Thompson, vice president for \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  at \uc2 Dell\uc2 , the computer maker.\par \par \uc2 Dell\uc2  is taking some energy-saving steps, like moving away from delivering computers on daily Boeing 747 flights from China to the United States. Instead, the company is putting the machines on boats.\par \par \uc2 Dell\uc2  is also delving extensively into what is known as the circular economy, reusing the plastics in its computers and even exploring the possibility of using plastic debris gathered in polluted estuaries in its packaging.\par \par \uc2 Ms. Thompson and Mr. Ghosn spoke at a two-day New York Times Energy for Tomorrow conference in Paris that ended Friday.\par \par \uc2 At the conference, technology companies like \uc2 Dell\uc2  and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/topic/company/microsoft-corporation?inline=nyt-org"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Microsoft}}}\uc2  said that they saw many business opportunities in the need to save energy and cut emissions.\par \par \uc2 Rob Bernard, chief environmental strategist at \uc2 Microsoft\uc2 , said the world was on the cusp of what he called a fourth industrial revolution and that there was a \u8220\'20\'1Chealthy paranoia\u8221\'20\'1D in most executive suites that if companies did not make better use of resources they would find themselves out of business.\par \par \uc2 The tech companies say they can make a big contribution through digital strategies, including those that save energy or manage it better. \u8220\'20\'1CWe believe technology is the backbone of the changes that will solve the world\u8217\'20\'19s big hairy problems,\u8221\'20\'1D Ms. Thompson said.\par \par \uc2 Even what seem to be very traditional companies apparently are capable of change.\par \par \uc2 Enel\uc2 , the large Italian utility, is reinventing itself as a much more nimble company focused on renewables and services rather than building large-scale utility projects.\par \par \uc2 Investing directly in renewables is becoming a larger and more stable business, executives said.\par \par \uc2 Torben Moger Pedersen, chief executive of PensionDanmark, a Danish pension fund, said the firm had invested about 3 billion euros, or $3.33 billion, in various renewable projects.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CInvestors looking for opportunities to invest in large-ticket projects can relatively easily find them out there,\u8221\'20\'1D he said.\par \par \uc2 Clean energy sources, like wind and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://topics.nytimes.com/top/news/business/energy-environment/solar-energy/index.html?inline=nyt-classifier"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 solar energy}}}\uc2 , represented more than half of the new electric power capacity installed around the world last year, according to the \uc2 International Energy Agency\uc2 , the Paris-based energy security group, which has added climate change to its portfolio.\par \par \uc2 Yet, leaders of major oil companies warned that despite the powerful shift that was unquestionably occurring, oil and gas would be needed for decades to come.\par \par \uc2 Ben van Beurden, the chief executive of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/topic/company/royal-dutch-shell-plc?inline=nyt-org"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Royal Dutch Shell}}}\uc2 , Europe\u8217\'20\'19s largest oil company, said that while \uc2 Shell\uc2  was investing in biofuels and other renewable energy, there was no alternative to oil and gas that would pay the company\u8217\'20\'19s shareholders the large dividends they expected.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CAt this point in time, of the $30 billion that we invest each year, I cannot find a significant percentage to invest in renewable projects simply because they are not there,\u8221\'20\'1D he told the conference.\par \par \uc2 Correction: November 7, 2016, Monday\par \par \uc2 This article has been revised to reflect the following correction: A picture caption with an earlier version of this article misstated the surname of the chief environmental strategist at \uc2 Microsoft\uc2 . He is Rob Bernard, not Rob Berna.\par \par \uc2 * {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/07/business/energy-environment/tesla-solarcity-merger-shows-how-batteries-and-solar-may-link.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Power Couple: Tie-Up Shows How Batteries and Solar May Link}}}\par \par \uc2 * {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/07/business/energy-environment/the-global-growth-of-electric-cars.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Oil Industry\u8217\'20\'19s New Threat? The Global Growth of Electric Cars}}}\par \par \uc2 * {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/07/business/energy-environment/for-renewable-energy-brexit-spurs-mixed-prospects.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 For Renewable Energy, Brexit Spurs Mixed Prospects}}}\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b ART\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Carlos Ghosn, chairman and chief executive of the Renault-Nissan Alliance, at The New York Times Energy for Tomorrow conference in Paris on Thursday, with Liz Alderman, chief European business correspondent for The Times. | Olivier Vigerie for The New York Times | From left, the modera