n0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Copyright 2017 The Financial Times Ltd. All rights reserved. Please do not cut and paste FT articles and redistribute by email or post to the web. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Immortalised in dark sun-beaten bronze, his shoulders garlanded with fresh orange flowers, Jamsetji Tata gazes out over the eastern Indian city that bears his name. Before his death in 1904, the founder of the\u160\'00\'A0Tata group\u160\'00\'A0drew up a vision of the model town that his company would one day build around its first steel plant.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 He planned to offer his workers a healthy \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  at odds with the disease-ridden slums he had seen on his travels in 19th-century Europe. \u8220\'20\'1CBe sure to lay wide streets planted with shady trees,\u8221\'20\'1D he wrote in 1902 to his son Dorab. \u8220\'20\'1CReserve large areas for football, hockey and parks.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Today, the tree-lined avenues of Jamshedpur, linking Tata-funded amenities from sports academies to a 900-bed hospital, bear witness to a heritage of ethical practice that is one of the group\u8217\'20\'19s most treasured assets. Utilities are handled by a \uc2 Tata Steel\uc2  subsidiary, whose chief executive claims to provide the only safe drinking tap water to be found in any Indian city.\par \par \uc2 A short drive away, company archivist Swarup Sengupta presides over the letters, contracts and directives that Tata, now India\u8217\'20\'19s largest conglomerate, presents as evidence of its stringent moral standards.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 Here are records of the financial crisis that hit \uc2 Tata Steel\uc2  in 1924, when Dorab Tata posted his entire net wealth as collateral for a loan rather than lay off a single worker. Here, too, is proof of the group\u8217\'20\'19s pioneering role in introducing modern benefits \u8212\'20\'14 from free medical aid to maternity pay \u8212\'20\'14 decades before they were required by law. \u8220\'20\'1CMother Teresa and Tata had a very strong relationship down the years,\u8221\'20\'1D says Sengupta.\par \par \uc2 This is the Tata long familiar to Indians and business watchers around the world: a group that tied itself to the principles of public service and humane treatment of workers and communities, a century before \u8220\'20\'1C\b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 \u8221\'20\'1D became a buzzword.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 Since Jamsetji set up his small trading company in 1868, it has expanded into a major name in global business, with annual turnover exceeding $100bn. Even amid this huge growth, it retained a name for stable leadership: in the first 144 years after it was founded in Mumbai, the group had only five leaders, all drawn from Jamsetji\u8217\'20\'19s family.\par \par \uc2 But this carefully guarded reputation for ethics and stability, a source of pride for Tata\u8217\'20\'19s 660,000 employees and India itself, is now\u160\'00\'A0threatened by an unprecedented crisis. The upheaval began in October last year when\u160\'00\'A0\uc2 Cyrus Mistry\uc2 , the first chairman drawn from outside the founding family, was suddenly dismissed without explanation, exposing seething tensions between him and his predecessor\u160\'00\'A0\uc2 Ratan Tata\uc2 .\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 Mr Tata, now 79, who had run the group for 21 years before handing over to Mr Mistry, returned to the helm until a permanent successor could be found, promising to restore stability. But Mr Mistry, from a family of Mumbai tycoons that still owns 18 per cent of the holding company \uc2 Tata Sons\uc2 , has\u160\'00\'A0refused to go quietly.\par \par \uc2 Since his dismissal, Mr Mistry has unleashed a stream of allegations, aimed at destroying Mr Tata\u8217\'20\'19s cherished reputation for integrity and straightforward dealing, in what he says is a campaign to protect the group\u8217\'20\'19s long-term future by ending supposedly\u160\'00\'A0deep-rooted governance flaws.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 Tata Sons\uc2  has dismissed Mr Mistry\u8217\'20\'19s claims \u8212\'20\'14 which range from violation of inside information rules to favourable deals given to Mr Tata\u8217\'20\'19s friends \u8212\'20\'14 as driven by a personal vendetta, and accused him of poor performance and an attempt to amass excessive power.\par \par \uc2 Senior figures in Mumbai\u8217\'20\'19s corporate world have warned privately of the risk that the fallout poses to the reputation of Indian business as a whole. Tata is by far the country\u8217\'20\'19s biggest business group, with products from jewellery to heavy weapons, steel to table salt. It is one of the few Indian conglomerates to have built a truly global brand, with prestigious foreign assets including the UK luxury carmaker \uc2 Jaguar Land Rover\uc2 , and it deploys thousands of IT engineers to leading western companies.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 Crucially, even though its official history omits widely known blemishes such as the founding family\u8217\'20\'19s involvement in the opium trade, Tata has been seen as a beacon of ethical conduct and good governance in India, a company free from the skulduggery for which many of its peers became notorious.\par \par \uc2 Extensive interviews with highly placed insiders at the group and access to internal correspondence have laid bare a feud that has left the Indian business world questioning whether Tata\u8217\'20\'19s unique reputation can ever recover from the extraordinary public infighting that has dogged it over the past few months.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 If Mr Mistry\u8217\'20\'19s legal campaign against the \uc2 Tata Sons\uc2  board results in failure, \u8220\'20\'1Cthe reputational damage will be repaired, to some extent\u8221\'20\'1D, says JN Gupta, managing director of SES, an Indian investment research firm. \u8220\'20\'1CBut it still won\u8217\'20\'19t be the same as it was. The bubble in the glass will still remain.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 ***\par \par \uc2 As Mr Tata prepared to step down from two decades of chairmanship, in 2011, photographs began to appear of the compact,\u160\'00\'A0whitewashed villa in south Mumbai where he would spend his retirement. While highly luxurious by most standards, the new home drew approving comparisons with an ostentatious 27-storey residence a few miles to the north, built at an estimated cost of $1bn by \uc2 Mukesh Ambani\uc2 , the country\u8217\'20\'19s richest man.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 Once more, the press reflected on the down-to-earth character of Mr Tata, a man who had ordered that\u160\'00\'A0stray dogs be permitted to rest in the lobby of the group\u8217\'20\'19s headquarters.\par \par \uc2 Mr Tata\u8217\'20\'19s personal brand of humility was honed over a career spent at his family group, even as he made no secret of\u160\'00\'A0flashier pleasures, such as a bright red Ferrari California.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 Returning to India in 1962 after seven years of architectural studies in New York, the slender 25-year-old was given an unceremonious induction as an apprentice in the fierce heat of \uc2 Tata Steel\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s cavernous blast furnace at Jamshedpur. In leadership positions over the years that followed, he struggled to turn around Tata\u8217\'20\'19s ailing electronics and textiles businesses, so it was a surprise when he was chosen to succeed his uncle JRD Tata as chairman in 1991.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CAll these old satraps said, \u8216\'20\'18But who\u8217\'20\'19s Ratan?\u8217\'20\'19\u8221\'20\'1D recalls one long-time company insider, referring to a group of senior Tata executives. Mr Tata, who declined to be interviewed for this article, spent much of his early years in charge battling with this old guard, and struggling to convince the wider public of his credentials. \u8220\'20\'1CThe backlash that I got, both in the media and the stock market, and from our own employees internally, was scary for a new chairman,\u8221\'20\'1D he once told the FT of his decision to sell Tata\u8217\'20\'19s soap business in 1993.\par \par \uc2 By 2000, Mr Tata was confident enough to focus on a campaign of overseas expansion that would snowball in scale. From the Pierre Hotel in New York to British tea brand Tetley and the Anglo-Dutch steel giant Corus, Tata went on an acquisition spree that established the group as a prominent international brand. Ratan Tata\u8217\'20\'19s name grew with it: he was rewarded for his UK investments with an honorary knighthood in 2009. At home, his tall frame now slightly stooped, he became revered as a visionary elder statesman of Indian business.\par \par \uc2 For one longstanding acquaintance, the adulation of Mr Tata gave cause for concern as the chairman approached the group\u8217\'20\'19s mandatory retirement age of 75. \u8220\'20\'1CIn this last phase, an ordinary man became an icon. His health was beginning to get stressed, and I don\u8217\'20\'19t doubt that he genuinely wanted to find a successor. It was not a charade. But the trouble was, he was convinced that he was irreplaceable.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Mr Tata\u8217\'20\'19s authorisation in 2010 of a committee to find his replacement triggered an avalanche of speculation. Like his uncle, Mr Tata had no offspring but some thought that he could keep the leadership in the family by turning to his half-brother Noel. Others suggested global business titans from the Indian diaspora, such as PepsiCo chief executive \uc2 Indra Nooyi\uc2 . But the committee surprised outsiders by choosing one of its own members: \uc2 Cyrus Mistry\uc2 , an understated \uc2 Tata Sons\uc2  director.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 Though he became the\u160\'00\'A0first chairman from outside the family, the bespectacled 45-year-old represented the closest possible alternative. Like the Tatas, his family traces its presence in India to an ancient exodus of Zoroastrian refugees from Persia. His ancestor Pallonji Mistry took advantage of the opportunities for ambitious young Parsis in the mid-19th century, establishing Shapoorji Pallonji, a construction company that grew into one of the country\u8217\'20\'19s largest.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 The Mistrys were granted a seat on \uc2 Tata Sons\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19 board in 1980, having taken a large minority stake in 1965. The two families became still closer with the marriage of Mr Mistry\u8217\'20\'19s sister, Aloo, to Noel, \uc2 Ratan Tata\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s half-brother.\par \par \uc2 Mr Mistry, softly spoken and stocky, first encountered Mr Tata at his family dining table, listening silently as the older man talked business with his father. Mr Mistry, a keen reader of popular mechanics magazines in childhood, finished his schooling at Dulwich College in London and studied engineering at \uc2 Imperial College London\uc2  before returning to help manage the SP group in 1991.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 Since then, he has lived in his family\u8217\'20\'19s Mumbai home, a tall mansion, liberally scattered with 20th-century Indian artworks and with two Jaguars in a basement garage, built on a steep slope overlooking the Arabian Sea. Known for his long working hours, Mr Mistry has maintained a low-profile life away from work, passing time with his wife and two sons.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CHe\u8217\'20\'19s very smart, very detail-oriented,\u8221\'20\'1D says one former colleague. \u8220\'20\'1CBut he\u8217\'20\'19s also a simple guy. Every time he goes to the US, he gets a \uc2 McDonald\u8217\'20\'19s\uc2  burger with fries and a large Coke.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Like his father before him, Mr Mistry joined the board of \uc2 Tata Sons\uc2 , in 2006 aged 40, and over the next five years was viewed as quiet but diligent by fellow directors, who backed his appointment as chairman despite his lack of executive experience at a major global company. \u8220\'20\'1C\par \par \uc2 My judgment was that we found the best successor,\u8221\'20\'1D says one senior group insider. \u8220\'20\'1CHe had everything that you needed: he had pedigree, he was a humble man, he was cultured, he was inquisitive, and he worked his butt off \u8212\'20\'14 which, at the age of 45, you are supposed to.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Mr Mistry has since claimed that he refused to be considered for the job when first approached by Mr Tata, content with the challenges on offer at his own family group, and relented only after the selection committee was \u8220\'20\'1Cunable to locate a suitable candidate\u8221\'20\'1D. But there were no public signs of misgivings while he learnt the ropes as Mr Tata\u8217\'20\'19s deputy during the latter\u8217\'20\'19s final year in charge \u8212\'20\'14 an extended handover that by all accounts passed off with goodwill on both sides.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 In December 2012, the departing leader retreated to a lakeside property 120km from Mumbai to celebrate his 75th birthday, leaving his successor to settle in to the chairman\u8217\'20\'19s office at Tata\u8217\'20\'19s imposing, stone-clad Bombay House headquarters. In some of his last public remarks as chairman, Mr Tata recounted how he had told the younger man to \u8220\'20\'1Cbe your own person\u8201\'20\'09.\u8201\'20\'09.\u8201\'20\'09.\u8201\'20\'09decide what you want to\u8201\'20\'09.\u8201\'20\'09.\u8201\'20\'09.\u8201\'20\'09I don\u8217\'20\'19t think it\u8217\'20\'19s right to have a ghost to shadow over somebody.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Yet within months, tensions emerged. \u8220\'20\'1CThey\u8217\'20\'19d had the honeymoon, they\u8217\'20\'19d given each other flowers, they\u8217\'20\'19d come back from the Caribbean \u8212\'20\'14 but then [Mr Mistry] had to get to work, and that\u8217\'20\'19s when the rain started,\u8221\'20\'1D says one senior group insider.\par \par \uc2 Before the handover, Mr Tata and Mr Mistry had discussed the need to deal with potential conflicts of interest involving Shapoorji Pallonji \u8212\'20\'14 which had performed engineering and construction work for Tata companies for several decades \u8212\'20\'14 prompting Mr Mistry to resign from all his family group directorships.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 But in a handwritten letter seen by the FT and dated September 24 2013, just nine months after the handover, Mr Tata accused Mr Mistry of failing to address the problem, and urged him to place a ban on all business between the two groups. \u8220\'20\'1CThis matter is so fundamental that if it cannot be resolved between us it will necessarily have to become an issue of a more public nature,\u8221\'20\'1D Mr Tata cautioned, adding that Mr Mistry\u8217\'20\'19s stance \u8220\'20\'1Cdemolishes in spirit and reality the values and ethical standards set by Jamsetji Tata\u8221\'20\'1D.\par \par \uc2 Mr Mistry eventually accepted his demand \u8212\'20\'14 while stressing that he was doing so to avoid a public argument that would be \u8220\'20\'1Cdetrimental to the interests of the entire group\u8221\'20\'1D, and accusing his predecessor of betraying their earlier understanding. This early dispute set the tone for what was to be a recurring theme in the two men\u8217\'20\'19s evolving relationship, with Mr Mistry resisting what he viewed as unjustified interference from the older man, who, in turn, saw his successor\u8217\'20\'19s defiance as a mark of disrespect. One senior insider compares their deteriorating relationship to that between a woman and her mother-in-law, \u8220\'20\'1Cwhere gestures, attitudes, a wave of the hand \u8212\'20\'14 these matter\u8221\'20\'1D.\par \par \uc2 ***\par \par \uc2 Further tension was created by Mr Mistry\u8217\'20\'19s emphasis on the problems caused by struggling investments made during Mr Tata\u8217\'20\'19s era. \u8220\'20\'1CWe inherited a fantastic group with a significant challenge \u8212\'20\'14 one of the biggest challenges in corporate history,\u8221\'20\'1D says one person who worked closely with Mr Mistry.\par \par \uc2 Chief among these was the struggling UK operation of \uc2 Tata Steel\uc2 , acquired through Mr Tata\u8217\'20\'19s blockbuster Corus acquisition. After losses at the unit soared to \u163\'00\'A31m per day, Mr Mistry oversaw the decision last March to seek an exit from the business. Mr Tata viewed this as reflecting a short-term approach and accused Mr Mistry of using him as a scapegoat, telling him in an email days after the decision: \u8220\'20\'1CThe past cannot be blamed for ever.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CHe should have realised that by attacking the legacy, he was attacking Ratan,\u8221\'20\'1D says a person close to the older man.\par \par \uc2 Even after stepping down as \uc2 Tata Sons\uc2  chairman, Mr Tata retained significant power through his chairmanship of the Tata Trusts, charitable bodies that hold 65 per cent of \uc2 Tata Sons\uc2 . He remained in regular contact with his successor, who sought his input on significant decisions through emails, letters and regular meetings at Bombay House. But, in January 2015, this arrangement was suddenly thrown into question by an announcement from the Indian securities regulator that the selective external disclosure of price-sensitive information was to be banned, even if it was not used to trade \u8212\'20\'14 unless the sharing was done in furtherance of a \u8220\'20\'1Clegitimate purpose\u8221\'20\'1D.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 The regulatory change \u8220\'20\'1Cput the fear of god into Cyrus,\u8221\'20\'1D says one person with direct knowledge of the internal discussions on this subject. \u8220\'20\'1CHe said, \u8216\'20\'18Shit, I\u8217\'20\'19m not a lawyer. Every time I move my little finger, someone will say I\u8217\'20\'19m passing on information.\u8217\'20\'19\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 To Mr Tata, \uc2 Tata Sons\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19 position as the controlling shareholder in all listed Tata groups meant that the holding company\u8217\'20\'19s board should be consulted on all key decisions \u8212\'20\'14 and that the Tata Trusts, in turn, should be kept in the know, given their status as the majority shareholder. But Mr Mistry worried that this might fall foul of the law, as it would mean giving \uc2 Tata Sons\uc2  access to price-sensitive information before other shareholders in the group\u8217\'20\'19s listed companies.\par \par \uc2 Conflict spilled into the \uc2 Tata Sons\uc2  boardroom in July last year, after \uc2 Tata Power\uc2 , chaired by Mr Mistry, agreed the $1.4bn acquisition of a renewable energy company without seeking prior approval from the holding company. According to people close to \uc2 Tata Sons\uc2  and Mr Tata, this deal was seen as part of a pattern of behaviour in which Mr Mistry appeared to be trying to amass power, while restricting the involvement of the \uc2 Tata Sons\uc2  board and the Tata Trusts in key decisions.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CThis is the system that they believed Cyrus was trying to build: I\u8217\'20\'19m the chairman of the [operating companies], and I take the decisions at the level of the board, and \uc2 Tata Sons\uc2  is basically an unimportant entity,\u8221\'20\'1D says one person close to Mr Tata. \u8220\'20\'1C[Mr Mistry] really thought he had the upper hand, that Mr Tata was getting very old.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Mr Tata did not let the matter rest. Later that month he sent Mr Mistry an email proposing that the \uc2 Tata Sons\uc2  board should gather to hear competing legal opinions on the matter \u8220\'20\'1Cin order to put an end to this issue once and for all\u8221\'20\'1D. Mr Mistry forwarded the email to \uc2 Tata Sons\uc2  director Ronen Sen, seeking his support in standing up to his predecessor. \u8220\'20\'1CIt is important that the \uc2 Tata Sons\uc2  board does not become defunct,\u8221\'20\'1D he wrote. \u8220\'20\'1CYou all have a role to play in its future.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CBe fair to the guy,\u8221\'20\'1D says one person in whom Mr Mistry confided about the pressure he was coming under. \u8220\'20\'1CYou make him the chairman, he\u8217\'20\'19s trying to clean up the mess, and you tie his hands. I mean, he was getting kicked in the balls every day.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Mr Mistry, meanwhile, was working on a new corporate governance framework aimed at putting an end to Mr Tata\u8217\'20\'19s supposed interference. The former chairman and his fellow trustees would be granted an annual meeting with \uc2 Tata Sons\uc2  to discuss its five-year strategy and annual business plan but would be expected to exert influence over specific decisions only through their representatives on the board.\par \par \uc2 Mr Mistry sought to discuss the proposed document with Mr Tata but was unable to secure a meeting, according to a letter he wrote to his predecessor on September 23, to which he attached a draft version of the framework. \u8220\'20\'1C[I] would be happy to come and get your feedback,\u8221\'20\'1D Mr Mistry concluded, after stating his intention to present the document at \uc2 Tata Sons\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19 October board meeting. It would prove to be his last.\par \par \uc2 ***\par \par \uc2 A few minutes before the meeting\u8217\'20\'19s scheduled start on the afternoon of Monday October 24, Mr Mistry was in his shirtsleeves in his office at Bombay House when he was surprised by the entry of Mr Tata and \uc2 Nitin Nohria\uc2 , the dean of Harvard Business School, who had joined the board of \uc2 Tata Sons\uc2  in 2013.\par \par \uc2 Having both sat down on his sofa, the two men told Mr Mistry that the situation was \u8220\'20\'1Cnot working out\u8221\'20\'1D, and that it was in the interests of all concerned that he should resign. A shocked Mr Mistry refused, according to his version of events, saying: \u8220\'20\'1CYou do what you have to do, and I\u8217\'20\'19ll do what I have to do.\u8221\'20\'1D A person close to Mr Tata attributes harder language to Mr Mistry: \u8220\'20\'1CLook, it\u8217\'20\'19s illegal \u8212\'20\'14 I\u8217\'20\'19ll fight.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Having sent a brief text message to his wife \u8212\'20\'14 \u8220\'20\'1CI\u8217\'20\'19m getting sacked today\u8221\'20\'1D \u8212\'20\'14 Mr Mistry donned a jacket, and made the short walk to the boardroom. Mr Tata was not present in the room but Mr Mistry was faced by three directors \u8212\'20\'14 all prominent figures in Indian finance and industry \u8212\'20\'14 who had been appointed at his predecessor\u8217\'20\'19s behest just two months earlier.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 People close to Mr Mistry accuse Mr Tata of having brought in the new directors to ensure a clear vote for Mr Mistry\u8217\'20\'19s imminent sacking \u8212\'20\'14 a claim denied by the company, which points to the three men\u8217\'20\'19s extensive and diverse business experience.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 The soon-to-be former chairman was informed by company secretary Farokh Subedar that another director would need to be appointed to chair the meeting, since there would be a vote on a matter that concerned Mr Mistry. On what would be the first of several occasions, Mr Mistry protested that his sacking would be illegal since it had not been included in the board agenda \u8212\'20\'14 a complaint that, Indian corporate lawyers say, is unlikely to hold water.\par \par \uc2 Of Mr Mistry\u8217\'20\'19s eight fellow directors, only the former \uc2 World Bank\uc2  executive \uc2 Farida Khambata\uc2  broke ranks and abstained when it came to the vote on his sacking. Over Mr Mistry\u8217\'20\'19s continued objections, the board decided that Mr Tata should return to the company as chairman on an interim basis, pending the search for a new permanent replacement, to be appointed within six months.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 Within an hour, Mr Mistry had departed the building, leaving \uc2 Tata Sons\uc2  to announce the decision to \u8220\'20\'1Creplace him\u8221\'20\'1D, without explanation, in a terse press release that sent shockwaves through India\u8217\'20\'19s corporate world.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 In conversations with the FT in the week of the sacking, some senior members of Mumbai\u8217\'20\'19s business community expressed shock and sympathy for Mr Mistry, who they considered to have been treated in an unacceptably brutal fashion. \u8220\'20\'1CIt\u8217\'20\'19s disgusting what \uc2 Ratan Tata\uc2  has done to humiliate a person so badly,\u8221\'20\'1D said one.\par \par \uc2 ***\par \par \uc2 Mistry was to test the limits of that sympathy with an explosive fightback that few could have predicted, suddenly casting doubt over the vaunted image of his former employer. One of his main targets in this campaign was an aviation joint venture that Mr Tata had arranged in one of his final acts as chairman.\par \par \uc2 Tata lost its first airline to nationalisation in 1953 but aviation had been one of Mr Tata\u8217\'20\'19s passions since early adulthood. One of the few public photographs of his youth shows him at the controls of a light aircraft; aged 73, he donned a jumpsuit to co-pilot a \uc2 Boeing\uc2  fighter jet at an air show in Bangalore.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 Yet it was only in the dying weeks of his chairmanship that Mr Tata secured a corporate return to the skies, agreeing terms for a joint venture with \uc2 Air Asia\uc2 , led by the Malaysian entrepreneur \uc2 Tony Fernandes\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Within three years, however, concerns were raised at the joint venture\u8217\'20\'19s board about the terms of its transactions with Fernandes\u8217\'20\'19s company. \u8220\'20\'1CI am the only one screaming and shouting about this,\u8221\'20\'1D Tata\u8217\'20\'19s general counsel \uc2 Bharat Vasani\uc2  wrote to Mr Mistry in June 2015, shortly before resigning from the Air Asia India board due to his unhappiness over the matter.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 These worries were redoubled last year, when a forensic audit by Deloitte identified unexplained payments worth Rs220m ($3.2m) by the company. \uc2 Air Asia\uc2  and AAI declined to comment, while \uc2 Tata Sons\uc2  said AAI had taken appropriate measures over the report.\par \par \uc2 The trouble at AAI was just one of many explosive revelations and claims that Mr Mistry made public following his sacking, as part of a campaign to expose what he says is a pattern of flawed management that belies Tata\u8217\'20\'19s fabled record of ethical practice. \u8220\'20\'1CThis is about governance \u8212\'20\'14 it\u8217\'20\'19s not about me, it\u8217\'20\'19s not about position,\u8221\'20\'1D he told the FT in December, in the first foreign media interview of his career. \u8220\'20\'1CThis is a group that has to be institutionalised.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 The former chairman\u8217\'20\'19s bombshells began circulating the day after his dismissal, when an email from Mr Mistry to the \uc2 Tata Sons\uc2  board and \uc2 Tata Trust\uc2  trustees, detailing a catalogue of alleged governance failures, was leaked to the media. A succession of further public statements continued over the ensuing two months, culminating in December with the submission to India\u8217\'20\'19s Companies Law Tribunal of a 300-page dossier of complaints and evidence, calling for the forced\u160\'00\'A0removal of the entire \uc2 Tata Sons\uc2  board.\par \par \uc2 Among many allegations, Mr Mistry has homed in on his predecessor\u8217\'20\'19s friendship with the controversial south Indian businessman Chinnakannan Sivasankaran \u8212\'20\'14 a relationship that baffles even loyal allies of Mr Tata. Mr Mistry has claimed that Sivasankaran received undue favours from the Tata group, unveiling documents showing that he was helped by Tata companies to buy shares in Tata\u8217\'20\'19s telecoms company at Rs17 per share, just 12 days before the Singaporean sovereign wealth fund \uc2 Temasek\uc2  bought a stake at a 53 per cent higher valuation.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 Tata Sons\uc2  denies any wrongdoing, stating that its involvement with Sivasankaran\u8217\'20\'19s purchase was aimed only at stopping the shares being acquired by a hostile third party. Lawyers for Sivasankaran declined to comment.\par \par \uc2 Mr Mistry has been joined in his assault on Mr Tata\u8217\'20\'19s reputation by the firebrand ruling-party lawmaker Subramanian Swamy. The former justice minister has gone to court to force action against Mr Tata for\u160\'00\'A0alleged complicity in a notorious $26bn scam a decade ago \u8212\'20\'14 in which telecom spectrum was sold to favoured parties at knockdown prices \u8212\'20\'14 having uncovered an internal report from investigating authorities that recommended Mr Tata\u8217\'20\'19s prosecution. \uc2 Tata Sons\uc2  said the matter was thoroughly investigated by the authorities and no evidence of wrongdoing on its part was found.\par \par \uc2 But sympathy for Mr Mistry is eroding among many in India\u8217\'20\'19s business community, who fret that his campaign is driven largely by a desire for vengeance and may do permanent damage to a treasured national institution. Among the most controversial statements made by Mr Mistry was his claim, in the leaked email, of huge potential writedowns across the group \u8212\'20\'14 an assertion that prompted an immediate plunge in the market capitalisation of Tata\u8217\'20\'19s listed companies, which declined by more than $10bn in the weeks following his sacking.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CWhat he\u8217\'20\'19s doing, to my mind, is completely unprofessional,\u8221\'20\'1D says one senior banker in Mumbai. \u8220\'20\'1CIt\u8217\'20\'19s all for a personal ego trip. If he was so concerned about these things, what was he doing as the chairman of the company?\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 ***\par \par \uc2 On Tuesday, Mr Tata will again officially hand over the chairmanship of \uc2 Tata Sons\uc2  \u8212\'20\'14 this time to a man whose rural southern Indian origins, far removed from the Parsi homes of south Mumbai, in one sense make him the first real outsider to take charge of the group. The appointment of\u160\'00\'A0\uc2 Natarajan Chandrasekaran\uc2 , chief executive of \uc2 Tata Consultancy Services\uc2 , has been broadly welcomed by the market.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 The self-assured marathon runner, known for his assiduous cultivation of business relationships around the world during three decades at TCS, was seen as the obvious choice to restore confidence. Chandrasekaran\u8217\'20\'19s efforts to focus attention on the future could be overshadowed, however, by Mr Mistry\u8217\'20\'19s continuing legal fight against a group in which most of his family wealth is still invested. He is prepared to take the battle to the supreme court, according to people close to him.\par \par \uc2 And despite the criticism of Mr Mistry\u8217\'20\'19s tactics, his claims to have been reduced to a \u8220\'20\'1Clame duck chairman\u8221\'20\'1D have fuelled concerns over the transparency of management at the conglomerate. \u8220\'20\'1C\uc2 Tata Sons\uc2  currently has no accountability to the market at large,\u8221\'20\'1D says Amit Tandon, co-founder of Institutional Investor Advisory Services, a Mumbai research firm.\par \par \uc2 Still more worrying to many is the revelation of the extent of the power exerted by the Tata Trusts \u8212\'20\'14 an issue that has become more pressing given the advanced age of Mr Tata and the fact that no succession plan is yet in place. \u8220\'20\'1CIt is the main concern of everybody and his frailty requires urgent action,\u8221\'20\'1D says one friend. \u8220\'20\'1CHe is fully aware that he needs to do that, but he\u8217\'20\'19s been through a tough time.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Amid calls for the powers of the Tata Trusts to be curbed, there are countervailing warnings that this could open the door to a rival gaining influence over the group, should Mr Mistry\u8217\'20\'19s family finally sell their stake in the holding company. Market rumours are swirling about the possible interest of the Piramal conglomerate, whose chairman was one of the new directors inducted in August. Piramal did not respond to a request for comment.\par \par \uc2 Even if sweeping reform is undertaken, Tandon warns, Tata \u8220\'20\'1Ccannot expect to be treated the same way going forward\u8221\'20\'1D. A blemish seems likely to cling to its once shining corporate image. Senior Mumbai bankers say that its previous reputation for straightforward dealing had serious long-term value, easing its path to agreements with workers, business partners and governments around the world.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 The efforts to repair this damage will be monitored nervously far beyond Bombay House. Such a conspicuous blow to the reputation of India\u8217\'20\'19s largest and most esteemed group has been a painful blow for the country as a whole, at a time when its government and businesses are striving to attract foreign investment by building a reputation for \u8220\'20\'1Cease of doing business\u8221\'20\'1D and casting off the murky image that has shrouded parts of its corporate sector.\par \par \uc2 The chaos at Tata could prove a harbinger of problems elsewhere, cautions Saurabh Mukherjea, head of institutional equities at \uc2 Ambit Capital\uc2 . Mr Tata, he notes, is part of a generation of Indians who oversaw the rapid evolution of the country\u8217\'20\'19s top businesses following the groundbreaking reforms of 1991, which ended the stifling controls of the bureaucratic \u8220\'20\'1CLicence Raj\u8221\'20\'1D.\u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 Many of these businessmen have recently handed over control of their groups or are preparing to do so \u8212\'20\'14 and Mr Tata is not alone in showing a reluctance to cede influence, he says, noting a recent tirade of criticism by the founding chairman of IT company \uc2 Infosys\uc2  against its current management. \u8220\'20\'1CWe are struggling with the first intergenerational shift of power in the post-liberalisation era,\u8221\'20\'1D Mukherjea says. \u8220\'20\'1CIt\u8217\'20\'19s coming down to tussles of ego \u8212\'20\'14 the fading away of one generation and the emergence of the next.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Simon Mundy is the FT\u8217\'20\'19s Mumbai correspondent\par \par \uc2 Photographs: Nishant Shukla; \uc2 Getty Images\uc2 ; Dinodia Photos/Alamy; Reuters; Life Picture Collection/Getty Images; Hulton Archive/Getty Images\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clver